WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:32.960
In the year 1800, a Scottish captain by

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:37.120
the name of Colin Mackenzie

00:00:32.960 --> 00:00:39.920
was traveling in the south of India.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:41.600
Mackenzie was an officer in the British

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:44.000
East India Company,

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:46.879
a trading corporation with a private

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.920
army larger than many countries, that in

00:00:46.879 --> 00:00:53.840
the last century had come to hold sway

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:57.120
over vast areas of India.

00:00:53.840 --> 00:01:00.160
Mackenzie had come to India at the age of

00:00:57.120 --> 00:01:02.640
30, and he became so fascinated with the

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:05.119
place that he would never leave.

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:07.680
He was a curious man and an avid

00:01:05.119 --> 00:01:10.640
collector of artifacts.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:13.760
Over his nearly 40 years in India, he

00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:17.439
amassed a collection of 1,500 historical

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:20.560
manuscripts written on palm leaves in 13

00:01:17.439 --> 00:01:25.360
languages, along with thousands of local

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:27.840
histories and songs, charts, maps, sketches,

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:29.280
and a collection of more than 6,000

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:32.400
coins.

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:34.720
Mackenzie was also himself a skilled map

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:37.200
maker, and he produced the first

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:38.560
authentic geographical map of South

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:41.119
India.

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:42.720
So, we can imagine his excitement as

00:01:41.119 --> 00:01:44.720
he was traveling through the rocky

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:47.759
landscape of the Indian state of

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:49.280
Karnataka, when his local guides told him

00:01:47.759 --> 00:01:52.640
of the existence

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:55.520
of an enormous ruined city nearby that

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:58.320
had once been the capital of a great and

00:01:55.520 --> 00:02:00.960
powerful empire.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:02.560
These ruins, they told him, were crumbling

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:05.119
and overgrown,

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:08.239
and could be found near the town of

00:02:05.119 --> 00:02:09.520
Anagoondy at a small village known as

00:02:08.239 --> 00:02:12.400
Hampi,

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:15.760
a place that the Kannada-speaking locals

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:18.959
had come to know by the name Alputtun,

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:21.760
or ‘the ruined city’.

00:02:18.959 --> 00:02:24.480
Mackenzie urged them to take him there

00:02:21.760 --> 00:02:24.480
at once.

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:30.160
Mackenzie's visit to the ruins is

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:31.040
recorded in a journal he kept at the

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:33.519
time

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:36.400
which has never been published, but which

00:02:33.519 --> 00:02:38.319
exists in rough manuscript form in the

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:41.599
British Library.

00:02:38.319 --> 00:02:44.400
In his neat, curling, cursive handwriting,

00:02:41.599 --> 00:02:46.800
Mackenzie records what it was like to

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:49.920
wander through the overgrown ruins of

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:54.160
this great city as his guides told him

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:54.160
what they could about its history.

00:02:54.560 --> 00:03:00.959
South and half-southwest of Anagoondy

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:04.400
are still remaining many great ruins of

00:03:00.959 --> 00:03:07.280
the ancient city; palaces, pagodas,

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:10.239
droogs, and fortifications, to which the

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:12.239
people gave the name Alputtun,

00:03:10.239 --> 00:03:14.400
or ‘the ruined city’.

00:03:12.239 --> 00:03:16.840
The palaces with the grand stables for

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:20.640
elephants and horses are there to be

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:23.760
seen. On the southeast of one palace is

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:26.560
a place called Vasanta Voodom,

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:29.200
formerly the baths of the rajahs.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:30.799
They say that ancient kings used to

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:33.680
entertain themselves on certain

00:03:30.799 --> 00:03:36.159
festivals with throwing saffron-tinged

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:38.319
water on their women in a little square

00:03:36.159 --> 00:03:41.120
basin in the center of the building,

00:03:38.319 --> 00:03:44.400
surrounded by galleries. Its drain or

00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:45.280
conduit, almost ruined, is to be still

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:48.000
seen.

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:50.879
Westward of this bathing place is a line

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.519
of basins and cups cut out of the fine,

00:03:50.879 --> 00:03:56.720
black stones, and placed on each side of

00:03:53.519 --> 00:03:58.990
the water conduit. They say that here was

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:00.959
formerly the king's garden.

00:04:00.959 --> 00:04:06.720
Here and there, families of monkeys would

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:09.519
have clambered over these great boulders,

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:11.840
chattering and chasing one another.

00:04:09.519 --> 00:04:14.879
Mackenzie climbed up onto the rocky

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:17.440
granite hills nearby, and from there he

00:04:14.879 --> 00:04:19.040
sketched the first comprehensive map of

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:22.000
the site.

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:24.560
He wasn't a man given over to poetry, and

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.840
he let his maps and sketches do the

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:28.560
talking.

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:32.960
But he does make note of the sights that

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:32.960
he saw as he explored the ruins.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:39.280
The interior ramparts, apparently

00:04:36.479 --> 00:04:42.560
designed to enclose the royal quarter,

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:44.720
comprehending the palaces or Mahals.

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:45.919
Waterworks of the most remarkable sort

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:48.320
are visible.

00:04:45.919 --> 00:04:51.600
An eating place, with a number of black

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:53.840
stone slabs laid along a conduit with

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:57.280
dishes in the shape of leaves,

00:04:53.840 --> 00:05:01.039
sculptured on a theme. An octangular

00:04:57.280 --> 00:05:04.479
baton gallery and fountain in ruins.

00:05:01.039 --> 00:05:07.280
An elephant stable of eleven strong

00:05:04.479 --> 00:05:09.199
vaulted divisions, each crowned by a

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:12.240
handsome cupola.

00:05:09.199 --> 00:05:14.160
An aqueduct on stone pillars, which

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:17.199
brought water from the tank near

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:19.199
Camlapoor to the royal quarter, gardens,

00:05:17.199 --> 00:05:23.120
fountains. It appears to have been

00:05:19.199 --> 00:05:27.280
destroyed with much industry.

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:30.479
Only a few decades later, in the 1850s,

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:32.960
another East India Company officer, one

00:05:30.479 --> 00:05:35.919
Colonel Alexander Greenlaw, would visit

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:38.400
the ruined site with an early camera and

00:05:35.919 --> 00:05:40.560
would take some of the most affecting

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:43.120
photographs of the ruins in their

00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:46.320
undisturbed condition.

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:48.880
In them, we can see the same crumbling,

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:50.560
magnificently carved edifices that

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:53.919
Mackenzie would have,

00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:57.360
overgrown with mosses, growths of cactus-

00:05:53.919 --> 00:06:00.400
-like euphorbia and grasses, their ornate

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:03.440
cupolas strangled by vines.

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:06.479
We can see the beautiful bathing houses

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:10.080
spilling over with water weeds, the halls

00:06:06.479 --> 00:06:13.199
of long-dead kings now silent and shaded

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:15.919
beneath cracking roofs.

00:06:13.199 --> 00:06:19.360
In his journal, Mackenzie describes the

00:06:15.919 --> 00:06:21.840
sight of the city now sunken beneath the

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:21.840
earth.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.199
This place is now almost ruined, but its

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:28.400
remains are still very magnificent and

00:06:27.199 --> 00:06:30.560
curious.

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:33.600
The houses of the inhabitants are

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:36.639
entirely destroyed, and the ruins now

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:39.120
form high banks and eminences, under

00:06:36.639 --> 00:06:42.319
which are buried many great houses whose

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:43.680
terraces are level with or sunk below

00:06:42.319 --> 00:06:45.840
the soil.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:48.639
Many of these we can see in passing

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:51.280
among the inner ruins. South of the

00:06:48.639 --> 00:06:54.000
king's palace is a square building, the

00:06:51.280 --> 00:06:55.680
top of which is destroyed now.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.919
This being covered with earth and

00:06:55.680 --> 00:07:01.720
overgrown with bushes, we could not

00:06:57.919 --> 00:07:01.720
penetrate its interior.

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:10.240
These crumbling ruins were the remains

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:12.560
of a city known as Vijayanagara.

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:13.680
As Mackenzie walked between the fallen

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:15.360
pillars,

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:18.560
as he looked down on them from the

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:20.960
hilltop nearby and drew his map,

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:23.759
he was clearly struck by the grandeur

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:25.680
and magnificence of these remains,

00:07:23.759 --> 00:07:29.120
and he must have wondered

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:32.880
how such a great society could build all

00:07:29.120 --> 00:07:34.000
this, flourish, and then vanish into

00:07:32.880 --> 00:08:03.040
nothing.

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:11.280
My name is Paul Cooper, and you're

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:12.800
listening to The Fall of Civilizations

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:15.440
Podcast.

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:18.080
Each episode, I look at a civilization of

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:21.120
the past that rose to glory and then

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:23.039
collapsed into the ashes of history.

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:26.160
I want to ask, what did they have in

00:08:23.039 --> 00:08:28.720
common? What led to their fall? And what

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:29.919
did it feel like to be a person alive at

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:33.760
the time

00:08:29.919 --> 00:08:36.240
who witnessed the end of their world?

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:38.959
In this episode, I want to look at a

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:41.760
civilization that has all but faded from

00:08:38.959 --> 00:08:44.080
memory in many parts of the world.

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:45.860
That's the story of the Vijayanagara

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:46.959
Empire of Southern India.

00:08:46.959 --> 00:08:50.800
I want to tell the story of how this

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:53.600
remarkable society

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:55.200
rose up out of an age of conflict and

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:57.839
fragmentation,

00:08:55.200 --> 00:09:00.720
how it built one of the largest and most

00:08:57.839 --> 00:09:03.519
impressive medieval cities in the world,

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:06.839
and developed an identity that was both

00:09:03.519 --> 00:09:10.399
South Indian in nature and global in

00:09:06.839 --> 00:09:12.800
outlook. Finally, I want to tell the

00:09:10.399 --> 00:09:16.240
story of what happened to bring the

00:09:12.800 --> 00:09:20.600
great stone temples of Vijayanagara

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:23.759
crashing down in fire and flame.

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:35.600
The granite terrain that surrounds the

00:09:32.959 --> 00:09:38.080
small village of Hampi and the ruins of

00:09:35.600 --> 00:09:41.120
Vijayanagara around it is one of the

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:43.760
most distinct and easily recognizable in

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:43.760
the world.

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:52.000
It's a unique and surreal clutter of

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:55.040
enormous rounded boulders teetering in

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:57.519
strange and unlikely balancing acts,

00:09:55.040 --> 00:10:00.000
looking a little like pebbles someone

00:09:57.519 --> 00:10:02.959
has piled up on a beach.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:06.000
A later visitor to the ruins, a British

00:10:02.959 --> 00:10:08.240
man named AH Longhurst, provides the

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:12.160
following vivid description of the

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:12.160
region's distinctive landscape.

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:18.240
The site of the old city is a strangely

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:21.120
wild place to have been the birthplace

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:24.320
and capital of an empire. The whole of it

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:27.040
is dotted with little barren rocky hills,

00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:30.240
and immediately north of it, the wide and

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:32.959
rapid Tungabhadra River hurries along a

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:35.839
boulder-strewn channel down rapids and

00:10:32.959 --> 00:10:38.560
through narrow gorges. The hills are of

00:10:35.839 --> 00:10:41.680
granite, weathered to every shade of

00:10:38.560 --> 00:10:43.920
color from grey to brown, and have hardly

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:46.959
any vegetation on them.

00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:50.000
The alternate burning days and chilly

00:10:46.959 --> 00:10:52.959
nights of the Deccan climate have seamed

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.959
and split in every direction. The huge

00:10:52.959 --> 00:10:57.680
masses of solid rock

00:10:54.959 --> 00:11:00.160
and the earthquakes of remote ages have

00:10:57.680 --> 00:11:03.600
torn from their flanks the enormous

00:11:00.160 --> 00:11:06.720
boulders, and have piled these up round

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:08.160
about their sides in the most fantastic

00:11:06.720 --> 00:11:11.440
confusion,

00:11:08.160 --> 00:11:14.399
or flung them headlong into the valleys

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:16.720
below.

00:11:14.399 --> 00:11:17.839
But despite its often precarious

00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:20.560
appearance,

00:11:17.839 --> 00:11:23.680
this landscape is actually one of the

00:11:20.560 --> 00:11:26.800
most ancient and stable surfaces to be

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:30.000
found anywhere in the world.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:32.399
These vast sheet layers of granite were

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:34.880
formed under the earth's surface between

00:11:32.399 --> 00:11:37.680
about three and three-and-a-half billion

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:39.760
years ago during the earliest formation

00:11:37.680 --> 00:11:42.079
of the Earth's crust.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:44.959
Some of these rocks were around during

00:11:42.079 --> 00:11:47.519
the emergence of the very first life on

00:11:44.959 --> 00:11:48.800
Earth, from the tiniest microbes and

00:11:47.519 --> 00:11:50.639
bacteria.

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:53.200
They have stood here and watched that

00:11:50.639 --> 00:11:55.760
life emerge from the seas, seen the

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:58.800
dinosaurs rule the earth only to be

00:11:55.760 --> 00:12:01.680
wiped out by a visitor from the stars,

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:03.600
then seen the evolution of humans from

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:06.240
small mammals.

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:07.040
While softer rocks have eroded around

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:10.720
them,

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:13.440
these hard granites have remained.

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:16.560
The landmass that they are a part of is

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:18.639
often known as the Indian subcontinent, a

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:21.440
place with one of the most interesting

00:12:18.639 --> 00:12:23.839
interplays of geology and climate in the

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:26.320
world.

00:12:23.839 --> 00:12:28.959
This is a massive peninsula

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:31.360
jutting out of the south of Asia that

00:12:28.959 --> 00:12:33.600
extends south for more than 3,000

00:12:31.360 --> 00:12:35.440
kilometers from the Himalayan

00:12:33.600 --> 00:12:37.680
mountains.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:40.560
It's a landmass that encompasses an

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:42.720
enormous variation in landscapes, from

00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:45.360
the mountainous cloud forests and

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:47.440
coconut-palmed beaches in the south to

00:12:45.360 --> 00:12:50.639
the snowy reaches of the Himalayas in

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:53.200
the north, and the baking Thar Desert in

00:12:50.639 --> 00:12:56.800
the northwest.

00:12:53.200 --> 00:13:00.240
But generally, India is loosely divided

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:02.160
into two regions usually called North

00:13:00.240 --> 00:13:05.519
and South India.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:09.120
The north is a landscape of expansive,

00:13:05.519 --> 00:13:11.040
flat riverlands, grassy plains stretching

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:13.279
off into the distance,

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:14.959
then rising to the foothills of the

00:13:13.279 --> 00:13:17.360
Himalayas.

00:13:14.959 --> 00:13:21.200
But in the south, the landscape is

00:13:17.360 --> 00:13:24.079
dominated by an arid, rocky shelf known

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:26.959
as the Deccan Plateau.

00:13:24.079 --> 00:13:29.519
The name Deccan comes from the same root

00:13:26.959 --> 00:13:32.880
as the Tamil word ‘thekkanam’ and the

00:13:29.519 --> 00:13:36.240
Sanskrit word ‘Dakshina’, which both mean

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:36.240
the province of the south.

00:13:36.320 --> 00:13:43.040
This plateau is a sprawling table of

00:13:39.519 --> 00:13:45.680
rocky land that covers much of Western,

00:13:43.040 --> 00:13:48.399
Central, and Southern India.

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:50.959
It rises from low elevations in the

00:13:48.399 --> 00:13:53.680
north up to more than a thousand meters

00:13:50.959 --> 00:13:57.360
in the south, wedged between the two

00:13:53.680 --> 00:14:01.000
mountain ranges known as the Western and

00:13:57.360 --> 00:14:01.000
Eastern Ghats.

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:10.399
The word ‘ghat’ is used in some South

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:13.360
Indian languages to describe stone steps

00:14:10.399 --> 00:14:15.279
leading down to a river or lake, and so,

00:14:13.360 --> 00:14:18.000
the word is also used for these

00:14:15.279 --> 00:14:19.360
mountains since they look down over the

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:22.399
coast.

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:24.880
The Western Ghats are in fact the eroded

00:14:22.399 --> 00:14:27.120
remnants of what was once the edge of

00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:29.279
this continent.

00:14:27.120 --> 00:14:32.639
A hundred million years ago,

00:14:29.279 --> 00:14:35.680
India was joined to Africa before

00:14:32.639 --> 00:14:38.639
tearing away and beginning a journey of

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:42.720
6,000 kilometers across the ocean,

00:14:38.639 --> 00:14:45.600
before colliding with Asia.

00:14:42.720 --> 00:14:47.440
Directly after the break from Africa,

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:49.760
it's thought that the west coast of

00:14:47.440 --> 00:14:53.839
India would have appeared as a sheer

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:57.199
cliff around a thousand meters high.

00:14:53.839 --> 00:14:59.760
Over the next 100 million years, erosion

00:14:57.199 --> 00:15:02.160
and weathering would wear down this

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:04.880
cliff into the dramatic series of

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:08.639
mountains that today runs the whole

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:11.199
length of the coast and can soar up to

00:15:08.639 --> 00:15:13.920
2,600 meters.

00:15:11.199 --> 00:15:16.079
In the south, they are so massive that

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:17.120
they block the clouds that roll in from

00:15:16.079 --> 00:15:20.000
the sea

00:15:17.120 --> 00:15:22.240
during India's southwest monsoon,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.600
meaning that the land on the west of the

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:27.600
mountains

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:30.720
is a vivid, tropical green, a landscape of

00:15:27.600 --> 00:15:32.959
lagoons and mangrove forests,

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:37.040
while the land of the Deccan Plateau

00:15:32.959 --> 00:15:39.680
beyond them is relatively dry and arid.

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:43.279
But across this rocky landscape,

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:45.680
a number of great rivers do flow.

00:15:43.279 --> 00:15:48.399
They flow down the slope of the land

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:50.399
eastwards, away from the mountains of the

00:15:48.399 --> 00:15:52.880
Western Ghats.

00:15:50.399 --> 00:15:56.480
Some of these Deccan rivers are the

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:58.079
Godavari, the Krishna, the Kaveri, and the

00:15:56.480 --> 00:16:00.560
Tungabhadra,

00:15:58.079 --> 00:16:03.839
and they all flow eastwards until they

00:16:00.560 --> 00:16:06.880
eventually empty into the Bay of Bengal

00:16:03.839 --> 00:16:09.279
on the eastern coast.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:11.920
So, this is the landscape across

00:16:09.279 --> 00:16:15.519
which the great medieval drama of South

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:15.519
India would unfold.

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:25.279
The roots of human civilization in India

00:16:22.959 --> 00:16:28.639
are truly ancient.

00:16:25.279 --> 00:16:30.639
Analysis of mitochondrial DNA shows that

00:16:28.639 --> 00:16:34.720
modern humans began arriving in the

00:16:30.639 --> 00:16:37.600
subcontinent between 75,000 to 50,000

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:40.880
years ago, migrating through the Middle

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:43.519
East and Persia from our origins in

00:16:40.880 --> 00:16:46.720
Eastern Africa.

00:16:43.519 --> 00:16:48.959
Cave paintings dating to around 10,000

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:52.800
years ago have been found in the rock

00:16:48.959 --> 00:16:56.160
shelters of Bhimbetka in Central India.

00:16:52.800 --> 00:16:58.639
These paintings show men riding horses

00:16:56.160 --> 00:17:01.279
and even elephants, suggesting that the

00:16:58.639 --> 00:17:03.920
story of humans in this region has been

00:17:01.279 --> 00:17:05.839
intertwined with those of animals since

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:07.559
the very beginning.

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:12.000
Around the year

00:17:07.559 --> 00:17:15.600
6500 BC, agriculture emerged as people

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:19.679
began to farm winter grasses, barley, and

00:17:15.600 --> 00:17:23.360
wheat in Balochistan in modern Pakistan

00:17:19.679 --> 00:17:25.360
on the banks of the Indus River.

00:17:23.360 --> 00:17:27.919
In the following millennia, these

00:17:25.360 --> 00:17:30.480
techniques spread all the way up the

00:17:27.919 --> 00:17:33.520
Indus Valley.

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:35.919
From about the year 3000 BC,

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:38.160
large cities began to form in this

00:17:35.919 --> 00:17:41.919
region, which today are known by the

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:45.280
names Mohenjo-Daro and Harappa, and which

00:17:41.919 --> 00:17:46.720
are estimated to have held as many as

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:49.200
60,000 people.

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:51.440
The cities of the civilization that grew

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:54.080
up in the Indus Valley

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:56.720
were built from baked bricks, and

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:59.760
featured elaborate drainage systems and

00:17:56.720 --> 00:18:03.360
water supply systems, along with what may

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:06.080
have been temples and workshops.

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:09.039
Its people used a system of standardized

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:12.240
weights to measure out goods, and in some

00:18:09.039 --> 00:18:15.039
cities, large canals and docks have also

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:18.160
been uncovered. There's evidence that the

00:18:15.039 --> 00:18:20.880
Indus Valley may have traded by sea with

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:24.240
the civilizations of Mesopotamia, the

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:27.200
Sumerians and Acadians, and Indus Valley

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:32.080
artifacts have been found as far afield

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:34.480
as Oman, Bahrain, and in the south of Iraq.

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:37.679
It's perhaps here that the people of

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:40.320
India first truly harnessed the immense

00:18:37.679 --> 00:18:43.120
power of the elephant.

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:46.000
The carved seals of the Indus Valley

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:48.720
seem to provide the earliest evidence of

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.840
the organized capturing and training of

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:53.360
elephants

00:18:49.840 --> 00:18:55.840
from as early as 6000 BC.

00:18:53.360 --> 00:18:58.240
By the time the first surviving texts

00:18:55.840 --> 00:19:01.039
were written in India many thousands of

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:04.000
years later, tamed elephants would have

00:19:01.039 --> 00:19:06.880
already been a common, everyday sight,

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:09.520
carrying heavy loads for construction,

00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:13.440
transporting important people, and

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:13.440
fighting as weapons of war.

00:19:15.360 --> 00:19:19.760
The Indus Valley civilization is also

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.919
thought to have experimented with

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:25.039
writing, although the extent to which

00:19:21.919 --> 00:19:27.280
they did so is a matter for debate.

00:19:25.039 --> 00:19:30.080
Archaeologists have uncovered hundreds

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:34.000
of distinct symbols that Indus people

00:19:30.080 --> 00:19:36.559
used on stamped seals or small tablets,

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:38.720
ceramic pots, and what may have been

00:19:36.559 --> 00:19:40.720
signs hanging over the gates of their

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:43.200
inner citadel.

00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:46.400
Most of these inscriptions are tiny,

00:19:43.200 --> 00:19:48.400
containing only four to five characters.

00:19:46.400 --> 00:19:52.000
The longest ever found on a single

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:54.559
surface is only 17 characters long, and

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.640
we can't tell whether this was truly a

00:19:54.559 --> 00:19:59.200
written language.

00:19:56.640 --> 00:20:02.000
If the Indus Valley symbols really are a

00:19:59.200 --> 00:20:04.480
form of writing, the tragedy is that it

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:07.360
has never been decoded.

00:20:04.480 --> 00:20:10.000
So, the names of their cities,

00:20:07.360 --> 00:20:13.679
the names of their kings, their deeds and

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:15.760
works, the lives of everyday people,

00:20:13.679 --> 00:20:17.760
all of it has been lost beneath the

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:20.960
sands of Pakistan,

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:23.520
perhaps forever.

00:20:20.960 --> 00:20:25.760
All that we have left are the names that

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:27.919
later people gave to the remains of

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:30.080
these haunting places.

00:20:27.919 --> 00:20:33.200
One of their largest cities is known

00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:36.000
today as Mohenjo-Daro, which in the

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:39.360
language of Sindhi simply means ‘the

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.360
mound of dead men’.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:44.640
While it's not clear what happened to

00:20:42.080 --> 00:20:46.799
cause the downfall of their society, we

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:48.799
do have some idea.

00:20:46.799 --> 00:20:51.280
The Indus Valley climate grew

00:20:48.799 --> 00:20:53.760
significantly cooler and drier from

00:20:51.280 --> 00:20:55.760
about 1800 BC,

00:20:53.760 --> 00:20:57.840
linked to a general weakening of the

00:20:55.760 --> 00:21:00.400
monsoon at that time,

00:20:57.840 --> 00:21:02.799
an event that may have also contributed

00:21:00.400 --> 00:21:05.440
to the collapse of Sumerian society in

00:21:02.799 --> 00:21:07.520
the valley of Mesopotamia.

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:10.559
The Indus Valley did not use as

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:13.039
extensive irrigation techniques, and so

00:21:10.559 --> 00:21:13.820
were more reliant on the annual floods

00:21:13.039 --> 00:21:15.200
of the river.

00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:20.000
As the floods failed, the capacity of the

00:21:17.760 --> 00:21:22.720
river to support the population would

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:25.600
have collapsed.

00:21:22.720 --> 00:21:27.200
At this time, a people known as the Arya

00:21:25.600 --> 00:21:28.159
are thought to have arrived in the

00:21:27.200 --> 00:21:30.480
valley.

00:21:28.159 --> 00:21:33.280
It's unclear whether these Aryans came

00:21:30.480 --> 00:21:35.919
as settlers or refugees, whether they

00:21:33.280 --> 00:21:38.080
were welcomed or met with conflict,

00:21:35.919 --> 00:21:40.400
whether they brought new technologies

00:21:38.080 --> 00:21:42.799
and language into the valley, or whether

00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:44.480
they simply learned them there.

00:21:42.799 --> 00:21:46.880
But whatever the case,

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:49.600
this pattern would be repeated countless

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:51.919
times over the coming history.

00:21:49.600 --> 00:21:54.480
People would arrive in India from the

00:21:51.919 --> 00:21:57.120
lands beyond, mixed with the people

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:58.559
already there, and a new culture would be

00:21:57.120 --> 00:22:00.960
born,

00:21:58.559 --> 00:22:04.559
a blend of old and new,

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:04.559
foreign and home-grown.

00:22:06.400 --> 00:22:11.039
By the year 1300 BC,

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:13.679
the people of the Indus Valley had left

00:22:11.039 --> 00:22:16.679
their drought-ridden land and migrated

00:22:13.679 --> 00:22:19.280
eastwards, leaving the cities of Harappa,

00:22:16.679 --> 00:22:21.840
Mohenjo-Daro, and many others

00:22:19.280 --> 00:22:24.400
to crumble into the sands.

00:22:21.840 --> 00:22:26.559
They migrated east until they reached a

00:22:24.400 --> 00:22:28.880
large, bountiful river

00:22:26.559 --> 00:22:29.760
which meandered across an enormous flood

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:32.080
plain,

00:22:29.760 --> 00:22:35.039
rich and full of life.

00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:40.360
Here on the banks of this river, the

00:22:35.039 --> 00:22:40.360
next phase of Indian history would begin.

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:45.840
Although the story of Vijayanagara takes

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:48.799
place in the southern realm of the

00:22:45.840 --> 00:22:51.120
Deccan's arid and rocky plateau, it

00:22:48.799 --> 00:22:54.480
begins here in the north,

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:57.200
in this flat and rich river plain, and

00:22:54.480 --> 00:23:00.559
the river that flows across it is known

00:22:57.200 --> 00:23:00.559
as the river Ganges.

00:23:07.440 --> 00:23:11.440
This river

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:15.520
is known locally as the Ganga, and

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:19.360
sometimes Ma Ganga, or mother river.

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:22.480
It begins in an icy cave known as Gomukh,

00:23:19.360 --> 00:23:24.559
or the mouth of the cow, which yawns open

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:28.880
at the bottom of the great glacier

00:23:24.559 --> 00:23:32.080
Gangotri high up in the Himalayas.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:34.000
Since its formation 50 million years ago,

00:23:32.080 --> 00:23:36.400
the enormous weight of the Himalayan

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:39.360
mountain chain has quite literally

00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:42.000
weighed down the land around it.

00:23:39.360 --> 00:23:44.799
To the south, the ground has been pressed

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:47.440
down so it is now almost at sea level,

00:23:44.799 --> 00:23:49.520
and it's across this flat plain that the

00:23:47.440 --> 00:23:52.320
Ganges flows for more than two and a

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:55.679
half thousand kilometers, from east to

00:23:52.320 --> 00:23:58.320
west, down to the hot mangrove swamps of

00:23:55.679 --> 00:24:02.640
the Bay of Bengal, where it finally

00:23:58.320 --> 00:24:05.279
empties its silty waters into the sea.

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:07.520
For millennia, this great waterway has

00:24:05.279 --> 00:24:11.279
sustained around a tenth of the world's

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:14.080
population with food, water, and fish,

00:24:11.279 --> 00:24:17.760
and has provided a highway for people

00:24:14.080 --> 00:24:20.400
and trade to pass up and down the river.

00:24:17.760 --> 00:24:23.360
On one of the main tributaries of

00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:28.370
the Ganges, a smaller river known as the

00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:37.360
Yamuna, sits the city of Delhi.

00:24:37.360 --> 00:24:41.039
Delhi is one of the oldest cities in the

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:43.279
world.

00:24:41.039 --> 00:24:45.679
It has been continually inhabited for

00:24:43.279 --> 00:24:48.080
more than 8,000 years.

00:24:45.679 --> 00:24:48.960
The soil on the banks of the Yamuna is

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:51.120
rich,

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:51.880
and so, the people here have always

00:24:51.120 --> 00:24:52.960
flourished.

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:57.440
It's in this region of northwestern

00:24:55.200 --> 00:24:59.039
India, during the period following the

00:24:57.440 --> 00:25:01.840
collapse of the Indus Valley

00:24:59.039 --> 00:25:04.480
civilization, that the earliest examples

00:25:01.840 --> 00:25:08.400
of written texts were laid down in the

00:25:04.480 --> 00:25:10.880
ancient northern language of Sanskrit.

00:25:08.400 --> 00:25:13.360
These texts began to be written around

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:17.120
three and a half thousand years ago, and

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:17.120
they are known as the Vedas.

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:23.600
Unfortunately for us, many of these early

00:25:20.320 --> 00:25:24.880
texts were written on fragile, perishable

00:25:23.600 --> 00:25:27.600
substances,

00:25:24.880 --> 00:25:30.320
many of them on paper made of the bark

00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:32.000
of the Himalayan birch tree, using inks

00:25:30.320 --> 00:25:34.559
made of ash.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:36.960
Some of these texts, remarkably, have

00:25:34.559 --> 00:25:40.080
survived from as far back as the third

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:43.360
or fourth centuries, but in most cases

00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:46.880
they have been lost. The oldest of these

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:49.279
Sanskrit texts, known as the Rigveda,

00:25:46.880 --> 00:25:51.840
was probably transmitted orally from at

00:25:49.279 --> 00:25:56.000
least the second millennium BC,

00:25:51.840 --> 00:25:59.039
or more than four thousand years ago.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:01.520
In it is contained a poetic vision of

00:25:59.039 --> 00:26:04.520
how written language developed in this

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:04.520
region.

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:15.120
When in giving names,

00:26:12.559 --> 00:26:16.559
they first set forth the beginning of

00:26:15.120 --> 00:26:18.480
language.

00:26:16.559 --> 00:26:20.640
Their most excellent

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:22.840
and spotless secret

00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:26.080
was laid bare through

00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:27.919
love. When the wise ones formed language

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:29.440
with their mind,

00:26:27.919 --> 00:26:32.559
purifying it

00:26:29.440 --> 00:26:36.080
like grain with a winnowing fan,

00:26:32.559 --> 00:26:39.200
then friends knew friendships,

00:26:36.080 --> 00:26:41.600
an auspicious mark placed on their

00:26:39.200 --> 00:26:41.600
language.

00:26:47.600 --> 00:26:53.520
The publication of these texts had an

00:26:50.080 --> 00:26:57.360
enormous impact. For about a thousand

00:26:53.520 --> 00:27:00.400
years after 300 BC, the language of

00:26:57.360 --> 00:27:03.200
Sanskrit, once spoken only in the north

00:27:00.400 --> 00:27:05.840
of India, would spread to eclipse all

00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:09.600
others, becoming the common language of

00:27:05.840 --> 00:27:12.480
art, science, religion, and poetry, much as

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:14.720
Latin once was in Europe.

00:27:12.480 --> 00:27:17.520
It was in this period that the Vedic

00:27:14.720 --> 00:27:19.039
religion formed based on the script of

00:27:17.520 --> 00:27:21.440
the Vedas,

00:27:19.039 --> 00:27:24.399
and from this, after a number of

00:27:21.440 --> 00:27:28.690
adaptations and evolutions, would emerge

00:27:24.399 --> 00:27:31.809
the religion we know today as Hinduism.

00:27:33.120 --> 00:27:39.200
Today, the lands of India are united in a

00:27:36.559 --> 00:27:41.840
single, modern nation, but it's perhaps

00:27:39.200 --> 00:27:42.720
one of the most diverse nation states on

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:44.960
earth,

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:46.960
and certainly the largest nation to

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:49.120
comprise so many different cultures

00:27:46.960 --> 00:27:52.080
within its borders.

00:27:49.120 --> 00:27:54.880
The citizens of Tamil Nadu, Karnataka,

00:27:52.080 --> 00:27:57.360
Maharashtra, and all the 28 states of

00:27:54.880 --> 00:27:59.840
modern India are as different from one

00:27:57.360 --> 00:28:02.799
another as the citizens of France,

00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:04.399
Germany, and Italy. They vary in their

00:28:02.799 --> 00:28:08.320
traditional dress,

00:28:04.399 --> 00:28:11.120
diet, ritual observances, and in the 22

00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:13.200
official major languages spoken across

00:28:11.120 --> 00:28:16.320
the subcontinent.

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:18.559
South of Maharashtra in Central India,

00:28:16.320 --> 00:28:21.760
the languages belong to the Dravidian

00:28:18.559 --> 00:28:22.799
family, a body of languages found only in

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:25.760
India,

00:28:22.799 --> 00:28:28.000
while Maharashtra's Marathi language and

00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:30.559
all the major languages of the north,

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:33.600
including the ancient tongue of Sanskrit,

00:28:30.559 --> 00:28:37.440
belong to the Indo-European family, of

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:39.840
which English is also a member.

00:28:37.440 --> 00:28:42.240
But perhaps the most marked differences

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:44.559
from region to region are in the realm

00:28:42.240 --> 00:28:47.200
of religion.

00:28:44.559 --> 00:28:49.760
Today, the word Hinduism is applied

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:52.399
clumsily to a whole variety of different

00:28:49.760 --> 00:28:55.039
religious traditions that originate in

00:28:52.399 --> 00:28:57.600
India and that take the ancient texts of

00:28:55.039 --> 00:29:00.240
the Vedas as their starting point.

00:28:57.600 --> 00:29:03.120
Many Hindus refer to their religion as

00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:04.960
Sanatana Dharma, the eternal way, or the

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:07.440
eternal duty.

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:10.000
But Indian religion was never united

00:29:07.440 --> 00:29:14.880
under a central authority, and so, it

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:18.080
gives rise to a great deal of variation.

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:21.520
In very simple terms, Hindus generally

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:24.240
believe in one god named Brahman, who is

00:29:21.520 --> 00:29:26.320
refracted into many different aspects,

00:29:24.240 --> 00:29:28.640
the way a beam of light refracted

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:31.360
through a glass prism can be shown to

00:29:28.640 --> 00:29:34.799
contain many colours.

00:29:31.360 --> 00:29:37.279
The ancient text, the Maitri Upanishad,

00:29:34.799 --> 00:29:39.919
explains this refracted conception of

00:29:37.279 --> 00:29:42.880
god, in which each living being also

00:29:39.919 --> 00:29:45.840
contains a spark of this original,

00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:45.840
supreme power.

00:29:56.720 --> 00:30:00.320
Now, the part of him which belongs to

00:29:59.120 --> 00:30:02.399
darkness,

00:30:00.320 --> 00:30:04.320
that is called Rudra,

00:30:02.399 --> 00:30:05.679
that part of him which belongs to

00:30:04.320 --> 00:30:07.600
obscurity,

00:30:05.679 --> 00:30:09.520
that is called Brahma.

00:30:07.600 --> 00:30:10.799
That part of him which belongs to

00:30:09.520 --> 00:30:12.880
goodness,

00:30:10.799 --> 00:30:14.720
that is called Vishnu.

00:30:12.880 --> 00:30:16.159
He, being one,

00:30:14.720 --> 00:30:20.399
becomes three,

00:30:16.159 --> 00:30:22.480
becomes eight, becomes eleven, becomes

00:30:20.399 --> 00:30:24.880
twelve, becomes infinite,

00:30:22.480 --> 00:30:26.320
because he thus came to be,

00:30:24.880 --> 00:30:30.080
he is the being.

00:30:26.320 --> 00:30:33.840
He moves about, having entered all beings.

00:30:30.080 --> 00:30:36.799
He has become the lord of all beings.

00:30:33.840 --> 00:30:37.760
That is the soul within and without,

00:30:36.799 --> 00:30:40.770
yet

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:43.039
within and without.

00:30:51.840 --> 00:30:57.200
Although this one god can manifest in

00:30:54.640 --> 00:31:00.320
many different ways, generally most

00:30:57.200 --> 00:31:02.399
Hindus predominantly worship one of two

00:31:00.320 --> 00:31:06.880
different manifestations;

00:31:02.399 --> 00:31:06.880
these are Shiva and Vishnu.

00:31:07.440 --> 00:31:12.720
In traditional Hebrew, Christian, and

00:31:10.320 --> 00:31:15.760
Islamic conceptions of the world, the

00:31:12.720 --> 00:31:18.480
universe is created by god, who acts to

00:31:15.760 --> 00:31:22.000
preserve all that is good within it.

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:25.039
He is opposed by Satan or Shaitan, who

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:27.120
acts to destroy and corrupt.

00:31:25.039 --> 00:31:28.960
But Hindu conceptions of the universe

00:31:27.120 --> 00:31:31.919
are a little different.

00:31:28.960 --> 00:31:33.600
In Hinduism, Shiva is both the creator

00:31:31.919 --> 00:31:36.240
and the destroyer,

00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:38.480
a beautiful and fearsome god who

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:40.559
represents the primal energy of the

00:31:38.480 --> 00:31:43.440
universe.

00:31:40.559 --> 00:31:45.919
Shiva is often depicted as a dancer,

00:31:43.440 --> 00:31:48.559
reflecting the dance of the universe as

00:31:45.919 --> 00:31:51.600
it passes from creation to destruction,

00:31:48.559 --> 00:31:53.039
as the flowers bloom, blossom, wither, and

00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:55.200
then die,

00:31:53.039 --> 00:31:58.799
as people pass from childhood to

00:31:55.200 --> 00:32:01.519
adulthood, to old age, and then to death,

00:31:58.799 --> 00:32:04.159
all of it part of the same cycle, the

00:32:01.519 --> 00:32:05.760
same dance that goes on and on into

00:32:04.159 --> 00:32:08.000
eternity.

00:32:05.760 --> 00:32:10.399
To imagine this way of thinking, we might

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:13.039
consider that creation and destruction

00:32:10.399 --> 00:32:14.960
are often not opposed, but a part of the

00:32:13.039 --> 00:32:17.360
same process.

00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:19.760
A beautiful mushroom might spring out of

00:32:17.360 --> 00:32:22.480
the decay of a fallen tree.

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:23.440
The death of a gazelle gives life to the

00:32:22.480 --> 00:32:26.320
cheetah,

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:29.519
and the fall of one civilization can

00:32:26.320 --> 00:32:32.000
give rise to another.

00:32:29.519 --> 00:32:33.679
But the god Vishnu, on the other hand, is

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:35.760
the preserver.

00:32:33.679 --> 00:32:38.720
As Shiva's dance of creation and

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:41.600
destruction rolls on, Vishnu is the one

00:32:38.720 --> 00:32:42.640
who holds things together, if only for a

00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:45.279
time.

00:32:42.640 --> 00:32:48.320
Whenever the need arises, he appears on

00:32:45.279 --> 00:32:51.519
Earth in human form as great mythical

00:32:48.320 --> 00:32:56.919
heroes like Rama and Krishna, as this

00:32:51.519 --> 00:32:56.919
stanza in the Bhagavad Gita shows.

00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:11.279
Whenever righteousness wanes

00:33:07.840 --> 00:33:14.159
and unrighteousness increases, I send

00:33:11.279 --> 00:33:18.000
myself forth for the protection of the

00:33:14.159 --> 00:33:20.480
good and for the destruction of evil,

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:21.840
and for the establishment of

00:33:20.480 --> 00:33:23.280
righteousness.

00:33:21.840 --> 00:33:29.670
I come into being age after age.

00:33:34.080 --> 00:33:38.799
So, these are some important points to

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:41.120
remember going forward,

00:33:38.799 --> 00:33:44.159
that India at this time was home to a

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:46.720
great variety of different sects, orders,

00:33:44.159 --> 00:33:48.559
and religious traditions that today we

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:51.200
might group together under the label

00:33:48.559 --> 00:33:53.039
Hinduism, but that the people of the time

00:33:51.200 --> 00:33:55.600
would have considered to be considerably

00:33:53.039 --> 00:33:58.559
different, and between which there often

00:33:55.600 --> 00:34:00.320
existed great hostility.

00:33:58.559 --> 00:34:02.320
As the people of India had

00:34:00.320 --> 00:34:05.200
increasing contact with the people of

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:07.600
the wider world, in the second half of

00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:10.000
the first millennium AD,

00:34:07.600 --> 00:34:12.720
a new religion would enter the diverse

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:17.480
mix of Indian belief.

00:34:12.720 --> 00:34:17.480
That is the religion of Islam.

00:34:29.040 --> 00:34:32.839
This new religion would bring both

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:36.320
conquest and

00:34:32.839 --> 00:34:38.720
culture. It would form a cultural rift

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:39.839
that would split the Indian subcontinent

00:34:38.720 --> 00:34:42.079
in two,

00:34:39.839 --> 00:34:44.960
but that would also connect it to the

00:34:42.079 --> 00:34:48.000
great capitals of the wider world and

00:34:44.960 --> 00:34:49.919
bring a new age of technology and

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:52.560
advancement.

00:34:49.919 --> 00:34:56.159
Its influence would bring about a time

00:34:52.560 --> 00:34:58.480
of paradoxes, contrasts, and ironies,

00:34:56.159 --> 00:35:01.359
and chief among these is that it was the

00:34:58.480 --> 00:35:03.760
arrival of Islam that would lead to the

00:35:01.359 --> 00:35:06.400
building of perhaps the greatest Hindu

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:07.839
empire to ever arise on the Indian

00:35:06.400 --> 00:35:12.040
peninsula,

00:35:07.839 --> 00:35:12.040
the empire of Vijayanagara.

00:35:14.960 --> 00:35:21.040
The history of Islam in India is long

00:35:18.720 --> 00:35:23.599
and complex.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:26.079
According to traditional claims,

00:35:23.599 --> 00:35:27.440
the world's youngest major religion

00:35:26.079 --> 00:35:29.599
arrived on the shores of the

00:35:27.440 --> 00:35:31.200
subcontinent during the life of the

00:35:29.599 --> 00:35:33.920
Prophet Muhammad,

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:35.760
brought by traders who arrived by sea

00:35:33.920 --> 00:35:38.560
from the Persian Gulf.

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:41.280
At first, this young religion must

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:42.800
have felt very alien to the people of

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:45.599
India.

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:48.880
While Hindus did not eat beef as a

00:35:45.599 --> 00:35:51.440
result of religious reverence of the cow,

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:54.320
Muslims quite happily ate it, but were

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:56.560
forbidden from eating pork. Hindus

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:58.880
generally believe that god appears in

00:35:56.560 --> 00:36:01.680
multiple different forms,

00:35:58.880 --> 00:36:04.320
while Muslims believed emphatically in

00:36:01.680 --> 00:36:06.079
one indivisible god.

00:36:04.320 --> 00:36:08.480
While Hindus believed that you could

00:36:06.079 --> 00:36:12.240
access god by giving offerings to

00:36:08.480 --> 00:36:14.800
statues and idols, Muslims rejected any

00:36:12.240 --> 00:36:16.079
depiction of god in sculpture or

00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:18.720
painting.

00:36:16.079 --> 00:36:21.119
But while Islam arrived through trade in

00:36:18.720 --> 00:36:23.760
the south, its arrival in the north of

00:36:21.119 --> 00:36:26.760
India would be a much less peaceful

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:26.760
affair.

00:36:32.480 --> 00:36:38.320
In the past, the Indian subcontinent has

00:36:35.839 --> 00:36:41.680
often been depicted by historians as a

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:44.240
kind of geographical fortress sealed off

00:36:41.680 --> 00:36:45.760
on every side by the mountains and the

00:36:44.240 --> 00:36:47.520
sea.

00:36:45.760 --> 00:36:50.160
But when we look at the history of the

00:36:47.520 --> 00:36:52.880
region, the true picture is one of

00:36:50.160 --> 00:36:54.480
constant movements of people in and out

00:36:52.880 --> 00:36:56.640
of its landmass,

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:59.520
bringing with them their cultures,

00:36:56.640 --> 00:37:02.079
cuisines, architectural styles, and

00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:02.079
beliefs.

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:08.240
In fact, India was not a fortress at all.

00:37:06.480 --> 00:37:10.800
The sea that appears to hem the

00:37:08.240 --> 00:37:13.359
continent in on either side was

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:15.760
actually a busy highway connecting India

00:37:13.359 --> 00:37:18.800
to the Persian Gulf and the Red Sea on

00:37:15.760 --> 00:37:21.359
one side, and Cambodia, Sri Lanka,

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:23.280
Indonesia, and China on the other,

00:37:21.359 --> 00:37:25.920
meaning that the port cities of India

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:28.079
were always diverse and booming centres

00:37:25.920 --> 00:37:29.920
of trade.

00:37:28.079 --> 00:37:32.480
This meant that Indian pepper and

00:37:29.920 --> 00:37:35.359
cinnamon even flavored the meals eaten

00:37:32.480 --> 00:37:37.520
by Roman senators, and an Indian bronze

00:37:35.359 --> 00:37:40.400
figure of the Buddha has been found in a

00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:43.440
9th century viking grave on the small

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:45.680
Swedish island of Helgo.

00:37:43.440 --> 00:37:48.079
In the northwest of India, the mountains

00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:50.400
of Pakistan and Afghanistan were a

00:37:48.079 --> 00:37:52.880
formidable boundary, but a number of

00:37:50.400 --> 00:37:55.760
routes like the Khyber Pass and Bolan

00:37:52.880 --> 00:37:58.240
pass cut through their rugged cliffs in

00:37:55.760 --> 00:38:00.320
the region of the Indus River Valley, and

00:37:58.240 --> 00:38:03.359
these passes were home to just as

00:38:00.320 --> 00:38:05.680
livelier traffic as the seas.

00:38:03.359 --> 00:38:07.920
These roads were so well-established

00:38:05.680 --> 00:38:10.320
that Alexander the Great was able to

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:14.079
march his large army into the region of

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:16.160
the Punjab in the 4th century BC,

00:38:14.079 --> 00:38:20.000
and he would be followed by many other

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:22.079
would-be conquerors down the ages.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:24.560
While the Himalayas were the most

00:38:22.079 --> 00:38:26.960
impenetrable boundary of all, that didn't

00:38:24.560 --> 00:38:29.280
stop Indian Buddhism from spreading

00:38:26.960 --> 00:38:32.240
across them into Tibet and on to the

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:35.359
rest of Southeast Asia, reaching as far

00:38:32.240 --> 00:38:35.359
north as Japan.

00:38:35.760 --> 00:38:41.040
In the first millennium AD, powerful

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:44.079
Hindu empires like the Pallavas, the

00:38:41.040 --> 00:38:46.079
Pandyas, and the Cholas grew up in India

00:38:44.079 --> 00:38:48.720
and spread their influence right across

00:38:46.079 --> 00:38:51.920
the continent, so that Hindu gods can be

00:38:48.720 --> 00:38:55.440
found carved into temples as far afield

00:38:51.920 --> 00:38:57.599
as Indonesia, Malaysia, and Cambodia, and

00:38:55.440 --> 00:39:00.320
the language of Sanskrit would become

00:38:57.599 --> 00:39:03.280
the language of learning and religion

00:39:00.320 --> 00:39:05.440
right across the Asian landmass.

00:39:03.280 --> 00:39:08.000
But while these highways generated

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:10.560
enormous opportunities in connecting

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:13.680
India to the world outside, they also

00:39:10.560 --> 00:39:16.400
contained great dangers.

00:39:13.680 --> 00:39:19.040
Powerful enemies lived in the lands

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:21.359
beyond the mountains.

00:39:19.040 --> 00:39:24.000
Some of these enemies were nomadic

00:39:21.359 --> 00:39:26.640
armies of horsemen from the wild steps

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:28.800
of Central Asia that could reach truly

00:39:26.640 --> 00:39:31.040
astonishing sizes.

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:33.359
These would periodically sweep down

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:34.400
through the Khyber Pass to raid and

00:39:33.359 --> 00:39:38.320
pillage

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:41.580
before disappearing back into the wilds.

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:44.889
But other peoples came to conquer.

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:52.000
Within 20 years of the death of the

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:54.400
Prophet Muhammad, Muslim armies had

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:56.880
achieved one of the most spectacular

00:39:54.400 --> 00:40:00.000
feats of military campaigning that has

00:39:56.880 --> 00:40:02.079
ever been seen in world history.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:04.480
Once a small and relatively

00:40:02.079 --> 00:40:07.280
insignificant regional power, the

00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:09.839
Arabic-speaking peoples had emerged onto

00:40:07.280 --> 00:40:12.480
the world stage and immediately knocked

00:40:09.839 --> 00:40:16.240
out two ancient heavyweights; the

00:40:12.480 --> 00:40:18.079
Byzantine and Sassanid Empires.

00:40:16.240 --> 00:40:21.200
They then followed the same course

00:40:18.079 --> 00:40:24.160
eastward as Alexander the Great, toppling

00:40:21.200 --> 00:40:26.640
empire after empire until the Arab

00:40:24.160 --> 00:40:27.839
domains stretched across three

00:40:26.640 --> 00:40:30.880
continents,

00:40:27.839 --> 00:40:32.720
with borders touching China, Europe, and

00:40:30.880 --> 00:40:34.800
India.

00:40:32.720 --> 00:40:37.040
To the Muslims of the time, this was

00:40:34.800 --> 00:40:39.520
clear proof of the divine nature of

00:40:37.040 --> 00:40:42.240
their prophet's revelations.

00:40:39.520 --> 00:40:44.400
But just as Alexander had found out

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:47.119
nearly a millennium before,

00:40:44.400 --> 00:40:51.440
spectacular conquests don't simply

00:40:47.119 --> 00:40:54.319
transform overnight into a stable empire.

00:40:51.440 --> 00:40:57.040
Just like Alexander's empire, the newly

00:40:54.319 --> 00:40:59.359
conquered Arab territories burst like a

00:40:57.040 --> 00:41:01.920
bubble and quickly broke off into

00:40:59.359 --> 00:41:05.440
separate Muslim kingdoms stretching

00:41:01.920 --> 00:41:08.319
across the Middle East and Central Asia.

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:10.800
These were ruled over by sultans,

00:41:08.319 --> 00:41:13.200
a word derived from the Arabic word

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:16.720
‘sultah’, or power,

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:19.680
literally meaning ‘the one who has power’.

00:41:16.720 --> 00:41:22.079
These new Muslim kingdoms now sat on the

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:24.480
other side of the Indus River,

00:41:22.079 --> 00:41:28.720
and for the next 300 years, they would

00:41:24.480 --> 00:41:31.599
not make any move to advance into India.

00:41:28.720 --> 00:41:33.839
The Hindu kings who ruled North India

00:41:31.599 --> 00:41:35.599
would eye them with suspicion, but it

00:41:33.839 --> 00:41:37.920
seems they didn't think of them any

00:41:35.599 --> 00:41:40.800
differently to any of the other peoples

00:41:37.920 --> 00:41:43.119
who had come and gone in these regions.

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:46.480
They referred to them sometimes as Turks

00:41:43.119 --> 00:41:48.880
or Turushkas, sometimes as Tajiks,

00:41:46.480 --> 00:41:51.839
other times slightly confusedly as

00:41:48.880 --> 00:41:53.280
Greeks, but more usually with the word

00:41:51.839 --> 00:41:55.440
‘mleccha’,

00:41:53.280 --> 00:41:57.599
a word that means something like

00:41:55.440 --> 00:42:00.160
barbarian.

00:41:57.599 --> 00:42:02.560
To these Muslim kingdoms, the wealthy

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:06.319
lands of the Ganges plain would have

00:42:02.560 --> 00:42:08.960
looked like an irresistible target.

00:42:06.319 --> 00:42:11.119
At this time in history, India likely had

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:12.319
the most sophisticated economy in the

00:42:11.119 --> 00:42:14.800
world,

00:42:12.319 --> 00:42:17.599
and unlike Alexander the Great,

00:42:14.800 --> 00:42:20.880
the Muslim sultans knew just how large

00:42:17.599 --> 00:42:23.520
and wealthy India was.

00:42:20.880 --> 00:42:25.920
From the year 1000 on,

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:28.800
increasingly aggressive raids began to

00:42:25.920 --> 00:42:30.800
take place, often originating from

00:42:28.800 --> 00:42:32.640
warrior kingdoms in the region of

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:35.520
Afghanistan.

00:42:32.640 --> 00:42:37.040
These horsemen would ride south down the

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:39.760
Bolan Pass

00:42:37.040 --> 00:42:42.560
and raid the lands of India.

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:45.520
But towards the end of the 12th century,

00:42:42.560 --> 00:42:48.720
a new and more ambitious group would

00:42:45.520 --> 00:42:50.880
arrive in the region, and they would come

00:42:48.720 --> 00:42:53.920
to stay.

00:42:50.880 --> 00:42:57.880
These were a group of Turkic peoples

00:42:53.920 --> 00:42:57.880
known as the Ghurids. The Ghurids

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:10.960
were a dynasty of Iranian origin, but who

00:43:08.240 --> 00:43:13.200
currently ruled over the Ghor region of

00:43:10.960 --> 00:43:15.599
present-day Afghanistan.

00:43:13.200 --> 00:43:18.880
They had long raided the northern lands

00:43:15.599 --> 00:43:22.000
of India, riding down from the hills and

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:24.400
burning cities, taking away loot, but in

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:27.920
recent years they had come under Persian

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:31.280
influence and converted to Islam.

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:33.760
Now one Ghurid ruler set his sights

00:43:31.280 --> 00:43:36.960
on greater riches than what could be

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:40.319
looted and strapped to a horse.

00:43:36.960 --> 00:43:42.800
He was a man known today as Muhammad

00:43:40.319 --> 00:43:42.800
Ghuri.

00:43:44.800 --> 00:43:52.240
Muhammad Ghuri was born in the year 1149

00:43:49.200 --> 00:43:54.560
in the mountainous region of Ghor.

00:43:52.240 --> 00:43:57.520
Ghor had been primarily populated by

00:43:54.560 --> 00:44:00.240
Buddhists for the last thousand years,

00:43:57.520 --> 00:44:02.480
but from the 11th century on, it became

00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:05.200
increasingly Muslim and would soon

00:44:02.480 --> 00:44:08.000
become a center of learning, home to

00:44:05.200 --> 00:44:11.520
Muslim teachers and scholars.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:14.000
Muhammad Ghuri was a warlord, and he wanted

00:44:11.520 --> 00:44:16.240
not just to loot and rob North India

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:18.800
like his ancestors, but to conquer

00:44:16.240 --> 00:44:21.040
territory for himself and settle down

00:44:18.800 --> 00:44:23.200
there for good.

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:26.400
When the annual monsoon ended in

00:44:23.200 --> 00:44:28.560
northern India, Muhammad Ghuri swept down

00:44:26.400 --> 00:44:31.200
the Khyber Pass.

00:44:28.560 --> 00:44:33.599
With an army powered by strong Afghan

00:44:31.200 --> 00:44:36.720
horses and bolstered with a large

00:44:33.599 --> 00:44:39.839
contingent of slave soldiers, he quickly

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:43.119
seized territory in the Punjab, a lush,

00:44:39.839 --> 00:44:45.839
green land at the foot of the Himalayas.

00:44:43.119 --> 00:44:48.319
The chronicler Ferishta, a Persian

00:44:45.839 --> 00:44:51.760
scholar who settled in India in the 16th

00:44:48.319 --> 00:44:54.240
century, recounts this campaign in sparse

00:44:51.760 --> 00:44:54.240
terms.

00:44:54.880 --> 00:45:00.240
In the year following, Muhammad Ghuri,

00:44:57.760 --> 00:45:03.280
having recruited his forces, marched

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:05.760
towards Peshawar, which in a short time

00:45:03.280 --> 00:45:09.200
was brought under subjection.

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:12.480
Muhammad Ghuri now returned to Ghazni,

00:45:09.200 --> 00:45:15.119
but in the next year marched towards

00:45:12.480 --> 00:45:17.920
Deebul in the province of Sind, and

00:45:15.119 --> 00:45:21.280
overran the whole country as far as the

00:45:17.920 --> 00:45:23.680
sea coast, returning laden with rich

00:45:21.280 --> 00:45:23.680
spoil.

00:45:25.119 --> 00:45:30.319
In the borderlands of the Punjab,

00:45:27.440 --> 00:45:33.040
Muhammad Ghuri created a Sunni Islamic

00:45:30.319 --> 00:45:35.760
kingdom of his own which extended east

00:45:33.040 --> 00:45:38.319
of the Indus River, and he began to

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:41.040
expand it.

00:45:38.319 --> 00:45:44.560
He tasked his generals with taking more

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:47.440
territory, and in the year 1193, one of

00:45:44.560 --> 00:45:50.079
these generals, a military slave,

00:45:47.440 --> 00:45:52.319
captured the small regional capital of

00:45:50.079 --> 00:45:54.480
Delhi.

00:45:52.319 --> 00:45:56.800
After the return of Muhammad Ghuri, his

00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:59.440
general took the fort of Merut and the

00:45:56.800 --> 00:46:00.640
city of Delhi, and it is owing to this

00:45:59.440 --> 00:46:03.760
circumstance

00:46:00.640 --> 00:46:07.119
that foreign nations say the empire of

00:46:03.760 --> 00:46:08.560
Delhi was founded by a slave,

00:46:07.119 --> 00:46:11.200
and making Delhi the seat of his

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:13.680
government, established himself there, and

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:17.680
compelled all the districts around to

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:17.680
acknowledge the faith of Islam.

00:46:17.839 --> 00:46:23.680
In doing so, Muhammad Ghuri laid the

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:27.040
foundation for the Muslim kingdom that

00:46:23.680 --> 00:46:30.560
for the next 300 years would rule over a

00:46:27.040 --> 00:46:32.880
large part of India and establish Muslim

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:35.680
culture there for good.

00:46:32.880 --> 00:46:39.880
This was the power that became known as

00:46:35.680 --> 00:46:39.880
the sultanate of Delhi.

00:46:42.480 --> 00:46:47.760
We know surprisingly little about what

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:50.800
life was like for the everyday people of

00:46:47.760 --> 00:46:51.839
India, many of them Hindu, Jain, and

00:46:50.800 --> 00:46:56.400
Buddhist

00:46:51.839 --> 00:46:59.040
while living under Islamic rule.

00:46:56.400 --> 00:47:02.160
People's experiences must have differed

00:46:59.040 --> 00:47:03.839
greatly across time and from person to

00:47:02.160 --> 00:47:06.640
person.

00:47:03.839 --> 00:47:09.520
While many Hindus no doubt greatly

00:47:06.640 --> 00:47:11.760
resented their new Muslim rulers, others

00:47:09.520 --> 00:47:13.920
simply got on with their lives,

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:16.560
and others still would have seen great

00:47:13.920 --> 00:47:19.599
opportunity in the new arrangement, with

00:47:16.560 --> 00:47:22.480
many even converting.

00:47:19.599 --> 00:47:24.480
The sources are surprisingly thin on any

00:47:22.480 --> 00:47:27.599
kind of religious conflict between the

00:47:24.480 --> 00:47:30.000
Muslim rulers and their Hindu subjects.

00:47:27.599 --> 00:47:32.559
Certainly some Hindu temples were

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:35.599
demolished or turned into mosques,

00:47:32.559 --> 00:47:37.839
although many were left standing.

00:47:35.599 --> 00:47:40.160
Muslim rulers were often contemptuous

00:47:37.839 --> 00:47:42.240
towards the Hindu religion, condemning

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:46.160
what they thought of as the worship of

00:47:42.240 --> 00:47:48.480
idols, but Hindu worship was never banned.

00:47:46.160 --> 00:47:51.680
For the most part, Muslim rulers were

00:47:48.480 --> 00:47:53.760
clearly pragmatic and had no desire to

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:55.680
unnecessarily aggravate their new

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:57.920
subjects.

00:47:55.680 --> 00:48:00.880
Pockets of resistance seem to have been

00:47:57.920 --> 00:48:03.760
most fierce among tribal peoples living

00:48:00.880 --> 00:48:06.480
in remote areas, but in the cities, there

00:48:03.760 --> 00:48:08.800
is little evidence of uprisings, and

00:48:06.480 --> 00:48:11.119
while the Muslim sultans certainly

00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:13.680
portrayed their conquests as religious

00:48:11.119 --> 00:48:15.520
missions in their propaganda, it's not

00:48:13.680 --> 00:48:17.440
clear that religion was always at the

00:48:15.520 --> 00:48:19.280
forefront of their minds.

00:48:17.440 --> 00:48:21.920
Much more pressing was the everyday

00:48:19.280 --> 00:48:25.520
matters of power and prestige that

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:28.079
occupy the thoughts of most rulers.

00:48:25.520 --> 00:48:29.760
Historical sources contain much more

00:48:28.079 --> 00:48:32.319
information about the ceaseless

00:48:29.760 --> 00:48:34.640
conflicts that took place between Muslim

00:48:32.319 --> 00:48:38.220
rulers and other Muslims than any

00:48:34.640 --> 00:48:42.900
conflict with their own Hindu citizens.

00:48:43.599 --> 00:48:48.319
The resistance that did occur, often

00:48:45.839 --> 00:48:49.920
among tribal people, could still be

00:48:48.319 --> 00:48:53.440
fierce.

00:48:49.920 --> 00:48:56.079
In the year 1206, Muhammad Ghuri, the

00:48:53.440 --> 00:48:58.160
conqueror of North India, was campaigning

00:48:56.079 --> 00:49:00.720
in the mountainous region of Sind,

00:48:58.160 --> 00:49:04.160
crushing a rebellion by the Punjabi hill

00:49:00.720 --> 00:49:06.960
tribe known as the Gukkurs.

00:49:04.160 --> 00:49:10.079
One night, with exceptional stealth, a

00:49:06.960 --> 00:49:13.200
small group of Gukkur warriors snuck into

00:49:10.079 --> 00:49:17.760
his camp and dealt their revenge,

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:20.160
as the chronicler Ferishta recalls.

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:22.319
On the second of Shaban, having reached

00:49:20.160 --> 00:49:25.359
the village of Rohtuk on the banks of the

00:49:22.319 --> 00:49:27.760
Indus, 20 Gukkurs who had lost some of

00:49:25.359 --> 00:49:30.079
their relations in the late wars, entered

00:49:27.760 --> 00:49:31.440
into a conspiracy against the king's

00:49:30.079 --> 00:49:33.359
life.

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:34.559
They found their way up to the tents in

00:49:33.359 --> 00:49:37.280
the night.

00:49:34.559 --> 00:49:39.119
One of them advanced to the tent door,

00:49:37.280 --> 00:49:42.079
but being stopped by a sentry who was

00:49:39.119 --> 00:49:45.200
about to seize him, he plunged his dagger

00:49:42.079 --> 00:49:47.200
into his breast. The other assassins took

00:49:45.200 --> 00:49:49.359
the opportunity of cutting their way

00:49:47.200 --> 00:49:52.000
into the king's tent.

00:49:49.359 --> 00:49:52.960
He was asleep, with two slaves fanning

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:56.079
him.

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:58.960
These stood petrified with terror when

00:49:56.079 --> 00:50:00.880
they beheld the Gukkurs’ enter, who,

00:49:58.960 --> 00:50:02.880
without hesitation,

00:50:00.880 --> 00:50:04.079
sheathed their daggers in the king's

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:06.160
body,

00:50:04.079 --> 00:50:10.319
which was afterwards found to have been

00:50:06.160 --> 00:50:13.200
pierced by no fewer than 22 wounds.

00:50:10.319 --> 00:50:16.800
Thus fell Sultan Muhammad Ghuri after a

00:50:13.200 --> 00:50:16.800
reign of 32 years.

00:50:17.359 --> 00:50:23.040
From there, the Muslims’ fortunes

00:50:19.760 --> 00:50:23.040
would only get worse.

00:50:24.720 --> 00:50:31.200
That same year, far away in the steppes of

00:50:27.839 --> 00:50:34.240
Mongolia, a vast federation of nomadic

00:50:31.200 --> 00:50:37.040
peoples would unite together and crown

00:50:34.240 --> 00:50:38.839
Genghis Khan as the emperor of all the

00:50:37.040 --> 00:50:42.079
steppe people of

00:50:38.839 --> 00:50:44.800
Mongolia. Genghis Khan would soon unleash

00:50:42.079 --> 00:50:47.760
an invasion of China, where anywhere

00:50:44.800 --> 00:50:49.440
between 10 to 40 million people may have

00:50:47.760 --> 00:50:52.000
been killed.

00:50:49.440 --> 00:50:54.400
From there, he would march through Persia

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:57.119
and the Middle East, tearing the heart

00:50:54.400 --> 00:50:59.839
out of the Muslim world and burning its

00:50:57.119 --> 00:51:02.000
intellectual capitals like Baghdad to

00:50:59.839 --> 00:51:04.880
the ground.

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:07.359
In just a few decades, around 10 percent

00:51:04.880 --> 00:51:09.280
of the world's population is thought to

00:51:07.359 --> 00:51:12.800
have been killed.

00:51:09.280 --> 00:51:15.760
Muslim Turks from Pakistan, Afghanistan,

00:51:12.800 --> 00:51:19.280
Persia, and beyond would flee the advance

00:51:15.760 --> 00:51:21.520
of the Khan's horde in enormous numbers,

00:51:19.280 --> 00:51:26.160
and many of them would come to settle in

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:28.559
the newly Muslim kingdoms of North India.

00:51:26.160 --> 00:51:31.040
While they had come as conquerors,

00:51:28.559 --> 00:51:35.280
Muslims would soon be arriving in great

00:51:31.040 --> 00:51:37.920
numbers as desperate refugees.

00:51:35.280 --> 00:51:40.800
After the death of Muhammad Ghuri, the

00:51:37.920 --> 00:51:43.880
next hundred years saw a succession of

00:51:40.800 --> 00:51:46.559
weak rulers, tyrants, and constant

00:51:43.880 --> 00:51:48.800
assassinations, as well as repeated

00:51:46.559 --> 00:51:50.400
attempts by the armies of the great

00:51:48.800 --> 00:51:53.200
Khans of Mongolia

00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:55.119
to conquer northern India.

00:51:53.200 --> 00:51:56.880
But time and again,

00:51:55.119 --> 00:51:59.839
the horse-powered armies of the

00:51:56.880 --> 00:52:02.720
sultanate were able to turn them back,

00:51:59.839 --> 00:52:05.440
sometimes inflicting massive defeats on

00:52:02.720 --> 00:52:08.160
Mongol armies.

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:11.520
It's one of the great ironies of Muslim

00:52:08.160 --> 00:52:14.559
rule in India that the sultans of Delhi,

00:52:11.520 --> 00:52:16.800
who themselves had arrived as conquerors,

00:52:14.559 --> 00:52:19.280
were perhaps the only thing that stopped

00:52:16.800 --> 00:52:21.839
the armies of the Khans from riding

00:52:19.280 --> 00:52:24.319
south across India and committing the

00:52:21.839 --> 00:52:26.880
kinds of atrocities that they inflicted

00:52:24.319 --> 00:52:28.400
on the helpless civilian population of

00:52:26.880 --> 00:52:30.640
China.

00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:33.280
The sultans were able to hold off the

00:52:30.640 --> 00:52:35.760
Mongol attacks, and with their armies

00:52:33.280 --> 00:52:38.559
well-trained and now exceptionally

00:52:35.760 --> 00:52:41.200
experienced, they even strengthened their

00:52:38.559 --> 00:52:43.359
hold on North India.

00:52:41.200 --> 00:52:45.760
One by one, they swept away the

00:52:43.359 --> 00:52:48.319
fragmented Hindu kingdoms that ruled

00:52:45.760 --> 00:52:50.720
there, and as the Mongol threat gradually

00:52:48.319 --> 00:52:55.040
diminished in the north, they extended

00:52:50.720 --> 00:52:57.520
their borders even further to the south.

00:52:55.040 --> 00:53:00.400
Under the Khilji Dynasty, whose armies

00:52:57.520 --> 00:53:03.520
were led by a eunuch slave general named

00:53:00.400 --> 00:53:05.680
Malik Kafur, the armies of the sultanate

00:53:03.520 --> 00:53:07.680
crossed the Vindya mountains, the

00:53:05.680 --> 00:53:11.119
traditional boundary between north and

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:13.040
South India, conquered lands there, and

00:53:11.119 --> 00:53:14.960
forced the kingdoms beyond to pay

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:18.000
tribute.

00:53:14.960 --> 00:53:20.240
By the year 1300, the Delhi Sultanate had

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:22.079
established a lasting power that

00:53:20.240 --> 00:53:24.640
stretched from the Indus Valley to the

00:53:22.079 --> 00:53:27.520
Bay of Bengal, from the foothills of the

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:29.760
Himalayas to the gateway to the arid

00:53:27.520 --> 00:53:33.040
plateau of the Deccan.

00:53:29.760 --> 00:53:36.079
This power was Sunni Islamic, culturally

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:38.880
a blend of Turkic and Persian, and in its

00:53:36.079 --> 00:53:41.760
more stable moments, its rulers dreamed

00:53:38.880 --> 00:53:44.160
of expanding ever further into the south

00:53:41.760 --> 00:53:46.880
and eventually raising their banner over

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:49.520
the entire subcontinent.

00:53:46.880 --> 00:53:51.440
These dreams would finally be realized

00:53:49.520 --> 00:53:53.920
by perhaps the most complex and

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:59.760
controversial figure to ever rule over

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:59.760
India, a man named Muhammad bin Tughlaq.

00:54:05.680 --> 00:54:11.240
Muhammad bin Tughlaq came to the throne of

00:54:08.559 --> 00:54:15.599
the Delhi Sultanate in the year

00:54:11.240 --> 00:54:17.760
1325 at the age of 35.

00:54:15.599 --> 00:54:19.760
In this year around the world, the

00:54:17.760 --> 00:54:23.200
greatest king of the West African

00:54:19.760 --> 00:54:25.839
kingdom of Mali, Mansa Musa, completed his

00:54:23.200 --> 00:54:27.920
pilgrimage to Mecca, giving out so much

00:54:25.839 --> 00:54:30.319
gold on the way that he crashed the

00:54:27.920 --> 00:54:32.880
economies of the Middle East.

00:54:30.319 --> 00:54:35.359
In the Valley of Mexico, a bedraggled

00:54:32.880 --> 00:54:37.440
band of travelers settled down on an

00:54:35.359 --> 00:54:39.920
island in the middle of a lake and

00:54:37.440 --> 00:54:42.079
founded what would become the great city

00:54:39.920 --> 00:54:44.720
of Tenochtitlan.

00:54:42.079 --> 00:54:47.760
In the court of Delhi, a new sultan

00:54:44.720 --> 00:54:51.559
was crowned amid rumors of treachery,

00:54:47.760 --> 00:54:51.559
murder, and betrayal.

00:54:53.520 --> 00:54:59.040
Muhammad bin Tughlaq was an enigmatic and

00:54:56.640 --> 00:55:02.079
mercurial ruler.

00:54:59.040 --> 00:55:05.520
On one hand, he was an intellectual, an

00:55:02.079 --> 00:55:08.720
expert in the Quran and Islamic law, who

00:55:05.520 --> 00:55:10.079
could speak Persian, Arabic, Turkish, and

00:55:08.720 --> 00:55:13.599
Sanskrit,

00:55:10.079 --> 00:55:15.839
as well as a famous lover of poetry.

00:55:13.599 --> 00:55:18.559
Like all the sultans of Delhi, he was a

00:55:15.839 --> 00:55:20.960
Muslim, but was mostly tolerant of other

00:55:18.559 --> 00:55:22.880
religions, and was the only sultan

00:55:20.960 --> 00:55:25.280
recorded to have taken part in his

00:55:22.880 --> 00:55:30.160
people's Hindu festivals.

00:55:25.280 --> 00:55:30.160
But he also had a much darker side.

00:55:30.960 --> 00:55:35.440
Muhammad bin Tughlaq’s father had come

00:55:33.520 --> 00:55:38.640
from humble origins,

00:55:35.440 --> 00:55:41.359
the son of a slave and a Hindu mother,

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:43.680
but he had risen to power and founded

00:55:41.359 --> 00:55:46.799
the Tughlaq Dynasty.

00:55:43.680 --> 00:55:50.160
But then, only five years into his reign,

00:55:46.799 --> 00:55:52.960
a freak accident occurred.

00:55:50.160 --> 00:55:55.280
The sultan was sitting under a pavilion

00:55:52.960 --> 00:55:56.960
with his favorite son and the intended

00:55:55.280 --> 00:55:59.200
crown prince,

00:55:56.960 --> 00:56:02.640
when without warning, the structure

00:55:59.200 --> 00:56:04.240
collapsed, crushing them both to death.

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:09.119
In some sources, the event is attributed

00:56:06.880 --> 00:56:10.880
to a bolt of lightning striking the

00:56:09.119 --> 00:56:13.839
pavilion.

00:56:10.880 --> 00:56:16.000
One scholar of the time named Barani

00:56:13.839 --> 00:56:16.510
describes the event in the following

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:18.319
terms.

00:56:18.319 --> 00:56:22.400
A thunderbolt from the sky descended

00:56:20.079 --> 00:56:25.280
upon the earth, and the roof under which

00:56:22.400 --> 00:56:27.280
the sultan was seated fell down,

00:56:25.280 --> 00:56:28.480
crushing him and five or six other

00:56:27.280 --> 00:56:31.680
persons

00:56:28.480 --> 00:56:34.720
so that they died.

00:56:31.680 --> 00:56:36.799
But the Moroccan traveler Ibn Batuta, who

00:56:34.720 --> 00:56:39.599
visited the Delhi Sultanate during this

00:56:36.799 --> 00:56:42.640
time and wrote his account once he was

00:56:39.599 --> 00:56:45.599
safely back in his home city of Fez,

00:56:42.640 --> 00:56:48.240
gives a different version of the story.

00:56:45.599 --> 00:56:49.359
He claims that the pavilion collapse was

00:56:48.240 --> 00:56:50.960
planned,

00:56:49.359 --> 00:56:53.599
an assassination

00:56:50.960 --> 00:56:55.920
orchestrated by the king's younger son

00:56:53.599 --> 00:56:59.839
who would go on to take the throne;

00:56:55.920 --> 00:56:59.839
Muhammad bin Tughlaq.

00:57:00.319 --> 00:57:04.720
The scheme was that whenever the

00:57:02.319 --> 00:57:07.359
elephants would tread on one side of it,

00:57:04.720 --> 00:57:10.079
the whole building would fall in ruins.

00:57:07.359 --> 00:57:11.839
The sultan alighted and his son asked

00:57:10.079 --> 00:57:13.359
his permission to parade the elephants

00:57:11.839 --> 00:57:15.119
before him.

00:57:13.359 --> 00:57:16.960
The elephants were led up from one

00:57:15.119 --> 00:57:19.040
direction as was planned,

00:57:16.960 --> 00:57:21.119
and when they walked on that side, the

00:57:19.040 --> 00:57:23.040
pavilion fell in on the sultan and his

00:57:21.119 --> 00:57:25.520
son, Mahmud.

00:57:23.040 --> 00:57:28.160
Muhammad bin Tughlaq gave orders to fetch

00:57:25.520 --> 00:57:30.640
axes and mattocks in order to dig for them,

00:57:28.160 --> 00:57:32.319
but he made a sign to delay, and in

00:57:30.640 --> 00:57:34.640
consequence, they were not brought out

00:57:32.319 --> 00:57:36.960
until after sunset.

00:57:34.640 --> 00:57:39.680
They cleared away the ruins and found

00:57:36.960 --> 00:57:43.040
the sultan dead with his back bent over

00:57:39.680 --> 00:57:43.040
his son to protect him.

00:57:44.880 --> 00:57:49.520
As with many rulers who came to power

00:57:46.960 --> 00:57:51.920
through treachery, Muhammad bin Tughlaq

00:57:49.520 --> 00:57:54.960
would spend his reign in a state of deep

00:57:51.920 --> 00:57:57.760
paranoia, always afraid that someone else

00:57:54.960 --> 00:58:00.240
would do the same thing to him.

00:57:57.760 --> 00:58:02.160
Throughout his time on the throne, he

00:58:00.240 --> 00:58:05.280
would dole out extremely harsh

00:58:02.160 --> 00:58:08.319
punishments to those who displeased him.

00:58:05.280 --> 00:58:12.720
The traveller Ibn Batuta was shocked by

00:58:08.319 --> 00:58:12.720
his harsh treatment of his citizens.

00:58:12.799 --> 00:58:16.480
The sultan was far too free in shedding

00:58:15.040 --> 00:58:19.280
blood.

00:58:16.480 --> 00:58:21.839
He used to punish small faults and great

00:58:19.280 --> 00:58:25.680
without respect of persons, whether men

00:58:21.839 --> 00:58:27.599
of learning or piety or noble descent.

00:58:25.680 --> 00:58:30.720
Every day there are brought to the

00:58:27.599 --> 00:58:32.720
audience hall hundreds of people, chained,

00:58:30.720 --> 00:58:34.839
pinioned, and fettered,

00:58:32.720 --> 00:58:38.160
and those who are for execution are

00:58:34.839 --> 00:58:41.599
executed. Those for torture are tortured,

00:58:38.160 --> 00:58:44.720
and those for beating are beaten.

00:58:41.599 --> 00:58:47.119
The chronicler Ferishta goes even

00:58:44.720 --> 00:58:47.119
further.

00:58:47.280 --> 00:58:52.160
So little did he hesitate to spill the

00:58:49.520 --> 00:58:54.079
blood of god's creatures that one might

00:58:52.160 --> 00:58:57.760
have supposed his object was to

00:58:54.079 --> 00:59:00.160
exterminate the human species altogether.

00:58:57.760 --> 00:59:03.200
No single week passed without his having

00:59:00.160 --> 00:59:06.400
put to death one or more of the learned

00:59:03.200 --> 00:59:10.319
and holy men who surrounded him, or some

00:59:06.400 --> 00:59:12.720
of the secretaries who attended him.

00:59:10.319 --> 00:59:14.799
This cruel streak would earn him the

00:59:12.720 --> 00:59:17.520
name Muhammad Khuni,

00:59:14.799 --> 00:59:20.319
or Muhammad the Bloody.

00:59:17.520 --> 00:59:21.520
Intriguingly, Tughlaq was also a passionate

00:59:20.319 --> 00:59:24.000
reformer,

00:59:21.520 --> 00:59:26.640
and was determined to enact a sweeping

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:28.000
series of modernization policies in the

00:59:26.640 --> 00:59:30.000
sultanate,

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:32.160
but each and every one of these was a

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:35.119
disaster.

00:59:32.160 --> 00:59:37.599
Perhaps inspired by China, he introduced

00:59:35.119 --> 00:59:40.640
the use of copper coins to replace the

00:59:37.599 --> 00:59:43.200
old silver ones to make the economy less

00:59:40.640 --> 00:59:44.720
vulnerable to fluctuations in the supply

00:59:43.200 --> 00:59:47.520
of silver.

00:59:44.720 --> 00:59:49.599
But these copper coins were very easy to

00:59:47.520 --> 00:59:51.920
counterfeit, and people across the

00:59:49.599 --> 00:59:54.640
sultanate began melting down the copper

00:59:51.920 --> 00:59:55.920
objects in their homes to turn them into

00:59:54.640 --> 00:59:58.319
coins.

00:59:55.920 --> 01:00:01.040
The value of the new currency soon

00:59:58.319 --> 01:00:05.040
crashed, and the silver coins had to be

01:00:01.040 --> 01:00:07.680
re-introduced at enormous cost.

01:00:05.040 --> 01:00:09.839
I think it's not unreasonable to assume

01:00:07.680 --> 01:00:12.000
that Muhammad bin Tughlaq actually

01:00:09.839 --> 01:00:13.440
suffered from some kind of mental

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:16.000
illness.

01:00:13.440 --> 01:00:18.799
One report by the Portuguese writer and

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:22.319
traveller, Fernao Nuniz, recounts a

01:00:18.799 --> 01:00:22.319
popular story about him.

01:00:22.559 --> 01:00:27.440
There are tales of him which do indeed

01:00:25.040 --> 01:00:28.799
seem most marvelous of the things that

01:00:27.440 --> 01:00:31.680
he did,

01:00:28.799 --> 01:00:34.000
as for instance how he made ready an

01:00:31.680 --> 01:00:36.319
army because one day in the morning,

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:37.920
while standing dressing at a window

01:00:36.319 --> 01:00:41.040
which was closed,

01:00:37.920 --> 01:00:43.760
a ray of sun came into his eyes,

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:46.720
and he cried out that he would not rest

01:00:43.760 --> 01:00:49.119
until he had killed or vanquished

01:00:46.720 --> 01:00:51.920
whomsoever had dared to enter his

01:00:49.119 --> 01:00:54.319
apartments while he was dressing.

01:00:51.920 --> 01:00:56.559
All his nobles could not dissuade him

01:00:54.319 --> 01:00:59.359
from his purpose, even though they told

01:00:56.559 --> 01:01:01.760
him it was the sun that had done it,

01:00:59.359 --> 01:01:02.640
a thing without which they could not

01:01:01.760 --> 01:01:05.119
live,

01:01:02.640 --> 01:01:07.599
that it was a celestial thing and was

01:01:05.119 --> 01:01:11.599
located in the sky, and that he could

01:01:07.599 --> 01:01:14.000
never do any harm to it. With all this, he

01:01:11.599 --> 01:01:16.960
made his forces ready, saying that he

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:19.520
must go in search of his enemy.

01:01:16.960 --> 01:01:22.720
As he was going along with large

01:01:19.520 --> 01:01:26.079
forces raised in the country, so much

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:28.400
dust arose that it obscured the sun.

01:01:26.079 --> 01:01:31.359
When he lost sight of it, the captains

01:01:28.400 --> 01:01:33.520
told him that he had put to flight him

01:01:31.359 --> 01:01:35.839
who he had come to seek.

01:01:33.520 --> 01:01:38.319
Content with this, the king returned to

01:01:35.839 --> 01:01:39.200
the road, saying that since his enemy had

01:01:38.319 --> 01:01:42.240
fled,

01:01:39.200 --> 01:01:42.240
he was satisfied.

01:01:44.240 --> 01:01:49.839
While some of these stories have the

01:01:46.640 --> 01:01:52.160
sound of apocryphal folk tales, it's

01:01:49.839 --> 01:01:55.680
clear that the king who inspired them

01:01:52.160 --> 01:01:57.839
was indecisive and unstable.

01:01:55.680 --> 01:02:00.319
At one point, he apparently raised an

01:01:57.839 --> 01:02:02.799
army of a hundred thousand men and

01:02:00.319 --> 01:02:05.200
marched it up into the Himalayas, where

01:02:02.799 --> 01:02:08.559
it was easily ambushed and cut off by

01:02:05.200 --> 01:02:10.480
the Hindu tribes who lived there.

01:02:08.559 --> 01:02:13.200
It's recorded that only a single

01:02:10.480 --> 01:02:16.319
horseman made it back to Delhi to tell

01:02:13.200 --> 01:02:16.319
of the army's fate.

01:02:17.039 --> 01:02:23.440
One of the most devastating decisions he

01:02:19.359 --> 01:02:26.079
took was to relocate his capital.

01:02:23.440 --> 01:02:28.799
He decided that Delhi was too vulnerable

01:02:26.079 --> 01:02:32.000
to attack by Mongols and other steppe

01:02:28.799 --> 01:02:35.280
peoples, and so, he would move his capital

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:38.640
to the city of Devagiri, more than 1,200

01:02:35.280 --> 01:02:38.640
kilometers to the south.

01:02:40.160 --> 01:02:45.200
He ordered that every citizen of Delhi

01:02:42.640 --> 01:02:47.119
should relocate and make the long

01:02:45.200 --> 01:02:48.480
journey by road.

01:02:47.119 --> 01:02:52.480
Accounts recall

01:02:48.480 --> 01:02:55.280
that thousands died on the way.

01:02:52.480 --> 01:02:57.280
The traveller Ibn Batuta arrived in

01:02:55.280 --> 01:02:59.839
Delhi around this time,

01:02:57.280 --> 01:03:02.640
and remembers finding it a deserted

01:02:59.839 --> 01:03:04.799
ghost town.

01:03:02.640 --> 01:03:07.280
The sultan ordered all the inhabitants

01:03:04.799 --> 01:03:09.280
to quit the city of Delhi, and made a

01:03:07.280 --> 01:03:11.839
proclamation stating that should any

01:03:09.280 --> 01:03:14.160
person whatsoever be found in any of its

01:03:11.839 --> 01:03:15.599
houses or streets, they should receive

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:18.160
punishment.

01:03:15.599 --> 01:03:20.559
Upon this, they all went out.

01:03:18.160 --> 01:03:22.640
When I entered Delhi, it was almost a

01:03:20.559 --> 01:03:25.200
desert.

01:03:22.640 --> 01:03:27.359
Batuta relates that during this time,

01:03:25.200 --> 01:03:30.559
the king climbed onto the roof of his

01:03:27.359 --> 01:03:33.920
palace and saw the city empty, its

01:03:30.559 --> 01:03:35.920
streets silent, with no smoke rising from

01:03:33.920 --> 01:03:40.319
its chimneys.

01:03:35.920 --> 01:03:42.799
Then he sighed and said the following.

01:03:40.319 --> 01:03:45.839
Now my heart is satisfied and my

01:03:42.799 --> 01:03:45.839
feelings are appeased.

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:51.280
Characteristically for Muhammad bin

01:03:48.160 --> 01:03:53.599
Tughlaq, soon after the mass relocation

01:03:51.280 --> 01:03:55.760
of Delhi had been completed,

01:03:53.599 --> 01:03:58.480
he changed his mind,

01:03:55.760 --> 01:04:02.640
and much of the city's population was

01:03:58.480 --> 01:04:04.480
forced to march all the way back.

01:04:02.640 --> 01:04:06.720
But to the people of the south, the

01:04:04.480 --> 01:04:09.520
sultan's failed attempt to move his

01:04:06.720 --> 01:04:10.839
capital in their direction can't have

01:04:09.520 --> 01:04:13.839
passed without

01:04:10.839 --> 01:04:16.160
notice. It must have been clear that the

01:04:13.839 --> 01:04:19.200
ambitions of the sultans were now moving

01:04:16.160 --> 01:04:21.920
ever closer towards them.

01:04:19.200 --> 01:04:24.839
By this time, the power of the Delhi

01:04:21.920 --> 01:04:26.480
Sultanate was seemingly

01:04:24.839 --> 01:04:28.880
unstoppable.

01:04:26.480 --> 01:04:31.680
Its empire continued to grow

01:04:28.880 --> 01:04:33.520
even through the 26-year reign of this

01:04:31.680 --> 01:04:35.599
temperamental king.

01:04:33.520 --> 01:04:38.960
The sultans swallowed up the South

01:04:35.599 --> 01:04:41.599
Indian people known as the Kakatiyas and

01:04:38.960 --> 01:04:44.079
other surrounding Hindu kingdoms

01:04:41.599 --> 01:04:48.160
until the empire's territory reached its

01:04:44.079 --> 01:04:50.559
largest extent around the year 1335.

01:04:48.160 --> 01:04:51.760
It would now stretch for thousands of

01:04:50.559 --> 01:04:55.280
kilometers,

01:04:51.760 --> 01:04:57.680
form a belt across India from sea to sea,

01:04:55.280 --> 01:04:59.200
and would nearly encompass the entire

01:04:57.680 --> 01:05:04.760
peninsula.

01:04:59.200 --> 01:05:04.760
But this success was not to last.

01:05:10.160 --> 01:05:16.720
The mad sultan Muhammad bin Tughlaq died

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:19.920
in the year 1351

01:05:16.720 --> 01:05:22.480
while out on campaign to crush a Turkic

01:05:19.920 --> 01:05:26.240
tribe in the mountains of Pakistan.

01:05:22.480 --> 01:05:28.720
The exact cause of his death is unknown,

01:05:26.240 --> 01:05:32.559
but one scholar of the time reported the

01:05:28.720 --> 01:05:32.559
news with the following quip.

01:05:32.799 --> 01:05:37.280
The sultan

01:05:34.160 --> 01:05:38.880
was rid of the people,

01:05:37.280 --> 01:05:40.130
and the people

01:05:38.880 --> 01:05:42.160
of the sultan.

01:05:42.160 --> 01:05:47.200
But despite his erratic and tyrannical

01:05:44.720 --> 01:05:49.359
ruling style, it's clear that something

01:05:47.200 --> 01:05:52.640
in the harsh character of Muhammad bin

01:05:49.359 --> 01:05:53.920
Tughlaq had been acting to hold the empire

01:05:52.640 --> 01:05:56.480
together.

01:05:53.920 --> 01:05:59.280
After his death, the sultanate of Delhi

01:05:56.480 --> 01:06:03.520
began to disintegrate, and all its newly

01:05:59.280 --> 01:06:06.559
conquered lands rose up in rebellion.

01:06:03.520 --> 01:06:09.280
Soon, a war of succession tore the Delhi

01:06:06.559 --> 01:06:12.000
Sultanate into multiple factions,

01:06:09.280 --> 01:06:15.760
with nobles across the empire setting up

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:16.839
their own states and declaring freedom.

01:06:15.760 --> 01:06:20.160
The year

01:06:16.839 --> 01:06:22.740
1345 is the last year that imperial

01:06:20.160 --> 01:06:24.240
coins were minted in South India.

01:06:24.240 --> 01:06:30.319
The following years saw the empire

01:06:26.480 --> 01:06:33.039
devolve into anarchy and disintegration,

01:06:30.319 --> 01:06:35.920
and opportunist enemies waiting behind

01:06:33.039 --> 01:06:37.359
the mountains to the north soon got word

01:06:35.920 --> 01:06:39.280
of this.

01:06:37.359 --> 01:06:42.319
One of those enemies was the Turko

01:06:39.280 --> 01:06:43.520
Mongolian warlord and emperor known as

01:06:42.319 --> 01:06:46.160
Timur,

01:06:43.520 --> 01:06:48.319
the last of the great nomadic conquerors

01:06:46.160 --> 01:06:50.240
of the Eurasian steppe.

01:06:48.319 --> 01:06:51.920
After hearing of the weakness of the

01:06:50.240 --> 01:06:55.039
Delhi Sultanate,

01:06:51.920 --> 01:06:58.799
Timur marched his army south to Delhi in

01:06:55.039 --> 01:07:01.359
the year 1398, plundering and killing all

01:06:58.799 --> 01:07:04.079
the way. When he reached the city, he

01:07:01.359 --> 01:07:06.559
utterly sacked it, looted it, and put its

01:07:04.079 --> 01:07:08.480
people to the sword.

01:07:06.559 --> 01:07:12.720
Estimates for the casualties in this

01:07:08.480 --> 01:07:15.680
massacre go as high as 200,000 people.

01:07:12.720 --> 01:07:18.480
Timur himself would later write the

01:07:15.680 --> 01:07:20.480
following slightly unconvincing account

01:07:18.480 --> 01:07:22.319
of the atrocity.

01:07:20.480 --> 01:07:25.039
There was likewise an immense loot of

01:07:22.319 --> 01:07:26.000
rubies, diamonds, garnets, pearls, and other

01:07:25.039 --> 01:07:29.039
gems,

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:31.200
vessels of gold and silver, and brocades

01:07:29.039 --> 01:07:33.520
and silks of great value.

01:07:31.200 --> 01:07:36.079
Excepting the quarter of the Sayyids, the

01:07:33.520 --> 01:07:38.240
scholars, and the other Mussulmans,

01:07:36.079 --> 01:07:40.160
the whole city was sacked.

01:07:38.240 --> 01:07:43.280
The pen of fate had written down their

01:07:40.160 --> 01:07:46.160
destiny for the people of this city.

01:07:43.280 --> 01:07:48.079
Although I was desirous of sparing them,

01:07:46.160 --> 01:07:49.920
I could not succeed,

01:07:48.079 --> 01:07:53.760
for it was the will of god that this

01:07:49.920 --> 01:07:53.760
calamity should befall the city.

01:07:54.079 --> 01:07:58.240
Timur had no intention of staying in

01:07:57.039 --> 01:08:00.640
India.

01:07:58.240 --> 01:08:03.520
He simply collected up all the wealth he

01:08:00.640 --> 01:08:07.039
could loot, along with countless enslaved

01:08:03.520 --> 01:08:10.160
people, particularly skilled artisans, and

01:08:07.039 --> 01:08:12.319
returned to his capital of Samarkand in

01:08:10.160 --> 01:08:15.680
modern Uzbekistan.

01:08:12.319 --> 01:08:18.799
Like the sacking of Rome, Timur's sack of

01:08:15.680 --> 01:08:21.040
Delhi tore the heart out of this already

01:08:18.799 --> 01:08:23.359
struggling empire.

01:08:21.040 --> 01:08:26.000
The dynasties that followed had no

01:08:23.359 --> 01:08:28.400
ability to maintain their far-flung

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:30.560
territories, and would now be little more

01:08:28.400 --> 01:08:32.799
than local warlords.

01:08:30.560 --> 01:08:35.359
The people and lands that had once been

01:08:32.799 --> 01:08:39.040
part of the empire were left in a state

01:08:35.359 --> 01:08:41.759
of anarchy, chaos, and plague.

01:08:39.040 --> 01:08:44.400
It was a time of immense change,

01:08:41.759 --> 01:08:49.199
a time of terrible suffering, and for

01:08:44.400 --> 01:08:52.560
some, a time of enormous opportunity.

01:08:49.199 --> 01:08:55.040
Into this terrain of blood and fire, two

01:08:52.560 --> 01:08:58.000
brothers would rise from obscure

01:08:55.040 --> 01:08:59.600
upbringings to change the shape of power

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:01.679
in this region,

01:08:59.600 --> 01:09:04.839
and it's with these two brothers that

01:09:01.679 --> 01:09:07.679
the story of Vijayanagara would truly

01:09:04.839 --> 01:09:10.480
begin. They would move the center of

01:09:07.679 --> 01:09:12.080
Indian power from the Muslim north to

01:09:10.480 --> 01:09:14.560
the Hindu south,

01:09:12.080 --> 01:09:16.799
and build a city there that would stand

01:09:14.560 --> 01:09:18.000
among the great cities of the medieval

01:09:16.799 --> 01:09:20.719
world.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:25.679
They were known as the Sangama brothers,

01:09:20.719 --> 01:09:25.679
and their names were Bukka and Harihara.

01:09:31.839 --> 01:09:37.520
The exact origins of the Sangama

01:09:34.159 --> 01:09:40.080
brothers are wreathed in mystery.

01:09:37.520 --> 01:09:42.319
Many historians believe that Bukka and

01:09:40.080 --> 01:09:44.239
Harihara were commanders of the southern

01:09:42.319 --> 01:09:46.080
Hoysala Empire.

01:09:44.239 --> 01:09:48.159
According to these accounts, they may

01:09:46.080 --> 01:09:50.640
have been stationed on the rocky banks

01:09:48.159 --> 01:09:53.199
of the Tungabhadra River, with orders to

01:09:50.640 --> 01:09:54.480
repel any Muslim incursions from the

01:09:53.199 --> 01:09:57.600
north.

01:09:54.480 --> 01:09:59.679
Some more dramatic and fanciful stories

01:09:57.600 --> 01:10:02.400
recount how the brothers were generals

01:09:59.679 --> 01:10:04.960
of the conquered Kakatiyas, captured as

01:10:02.400 --> 01:10:06.880
prisoners of war, and taken to Delhi

01:10:04.960 --> 01:10:10.159
where they were forced to convert to

01:10:06.880 --> 01:10:12.400
Islam, later escaping and converting back

01:10:10.159 --> 01:10:14.400
to their native faiths.

01:10:12.400 --> 01:10:16.719
But none of this is mentioned in

01:10:14.400 --> 01:10:19.760
contemporary sources, meaning that these

01:10:16.719 --> 01:10:22.239
accounts are likely unreliable.

01:10:19.760 --> 01:10:25.040
Many of these legends suggest that these

01:10:22.239 --> 01:10:27.040
brothers met a Hindu sage named Shri

01:10:25.040 --> 01:10:29.600
Vidyaranya.

01:10:27.040 --> 01:10:32.320
One traditional story recalls that

01:10:29.600 --> 01:10:35.280
Harihara was out hunting one day when he

01:10:32.320 --> 01:10:38.080
saw a miraculous sight, and the sage

01:10:35.280 --> 01:10:42.920
advised him on how to interpret it, as

01:10:38.080 --> 01:10:42.920
the historian Robert Sewell recounts.

01:10:44.239 --> 01:10:48.159
During his reign,

01:10:45.760 --> 01:10:50.400
this chief was one day hunting amongst

01:10:48.159 --> 01:10:52.960
the mountains south of the river

01:10:50.400 --> 01:10:56.320
when a hare, instead of fleeing from his

01:10:52.960 --> 01:10:59.040
dogs, flew at them and bit them.

01:10:56.320 --> 01:11:01.440
The king, astonished at this marvel, was

01:10:59.040 --> 01:11:04.080
returning homewards, lost in meditation,

01:11:01.440 --> 01:11:07.120
when he met on the riverbank the sage

01:11:04.080 --> 01:11:09.360
named Vidyaranya or Forest of Learning,

01:11:07.120 --> 01:11:10.640
who advised the chief to found a city on

01:11:09.360 --> 01:11:13.280
the spot.

01:11:10.640 --> 01:11:16.000
So, the king did, and on that very day

01:11:13.280 --> 01:11:18.210
began work on his houses, and he enclosed

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:20.320
the city roundabout.

01:11:20.320 --> 01:11:25.679
While this is most likely a fable, it

01:11:22.960 --> 01:11:28.400
does contain an illuminating image of

01:11:25.679 --> 01:11:30.560
how the young power of Vijayanagara

01:11:28.400 --> 01:11:32.960
would go on to see itself,

01:11:30.560 --> 01:11:36.130
as the hunted rabbit who had turned

01:11:32.960 --> 01:11:40.220
around and learned how to bite.

01:11:44.560 --> 01:11:49.760
As the power of the Delhi Sultanate

01:11:46.719 --> 01:11:51.040
collapsed, the two brothers Bukka and

01:11:49.760 --> 01:11:53.280
Harihara

01:11:51.040 --> 01:11:56.400
raised a considerable army

01:11:53.280 --> 01:12:00.000
made up of angry Hindu lords, but also

01:11:56.400 --> 01:12:02.480
large cohorts of Muslim mercenaries.

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:04.960
These may even have been soldiers who

01:12:02.480 --> 01:12:07.840
had once fought for the Delhi Sultanate

01:12:04.960 --> 01:12:10.159
but who were no longer getting paid.

01:12:07.840 --> 01:12:12.640
With this force, the brothers set out to

01:12:10.159 --> 01:12:15.600
capture the areas of South India that

01:12:12.640 --> 01:12:18.080
the sultanate had left behind.

01:12:15.600 --> 01:12:19.600
Their offer to Hindu lords in the region

01:12:18.080 --> 01:12:22.159
was clear;

01:12:19.600 --> 01:12:25.040
join us, and we will ensure that South

01:12:22.159 --> 01:12:26.880
India is run by Hindus,

01:12:25.040 --> 01:12:29.600
and it's clear that many found this

01:12:26.880 --> 01:12:32.320
offer irresistible.

01:12:29.600 --> 01:12:34.400
Within only a few decades, the Sangama

01:12:32.320 --> 01:12:36.800
brothers had brought a large part of

01:12:34.400 --> 01:12:39.199
South India under their control,

01:12:36.800 --> 01:12:41.440
but many areas in the south were still

01:12:39.199 --> 01:12:44.640
ruled by Muslim powers,

01:12:41.440 --> 01:12:47.199
now cut off and isolated.

01:12:44.640 --> 01:12:50.320
These included the arid lands of Tamil

01:12:47.199 --> 01:12:52.960
Nadu, India's southernmost state, which

01:12:50.320 --> 01:12:55.040
was still ruled by a short-lived Muslim

01:12:52.960 --> 01:12:57.760
power continuing to fight for its

01:12:55.040 --> 01:12:59.000
existence in South India, known as the

01:12:57.760 --> 01:13:02.080
Madurai Sultanate.

01:13:02.080 --> 01:13:06.960
At this time, the Sangama brother Bukka

01:13:04.800 --> 01:13:10.719
was on the throne, and his wife was a

01:13:06.960 --> 01:13:13.440
woman named Ganga Devi, a famed poet.

01:13:10.719 --> 01:13:16.480
She wrote one vaulting, epic poem in the

01:13:13.440 --> 01:13:20.320
language of Sanskrit entitled Madhura

01:13:16.480 --> 01:13:22.880
Vijayam, or The Victory of Madurai.

01:13:20.320 --> 01:13:25.679
In it, she describes how a woman from the

01:13:22.880 --> 01:13:28.560
holy city of Madurai comes to king

01:13:25.679 --> 01:13:30.320
Bukka's court and begs him to take the

01:13:28.560 --> 01:13:32.400
town back.

01:13:30.320 --> 01:13:35.040
She describes how the ancient Hindu

01:13:32.400 --> 01:13:39.440
temples of Madurai had fallen into

01:13:35.040 --> 01:13:39.440
disrepair under its Muslim rulers.

01:13:40.880 --> 01:13:46.880
White ants have destroyed the doors.

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:49.679
The door frame of the sanctum is broken

01:13:46.880 --> 01:13:50.470
due to the wild growth of trees, plants,

01:13:49.679 --> 01:13:51.679
and creepers.

01:13:51.679 --> 01:13:56.239
The temple premises

01:13:53.600 --> 01:13:57.520
that formerly echoed the soft beating of

01:13:56.239 --> 01:14:01.120
the drums

01:13:57.520 --> 01:14:03.840
are now full of wild, wallowing jackals.

01:14:01.120 --> 01:14:06.480
The place once filled with the odor of

01:14:03.840 --> 01:14:08.880
sacrificial smoke and the melodious

01:14:06.480 --> 01:14:12.640
chant of Vedic mantras

01:14:08.880 --> 01:14:15.360
is now full of the foul smell of meat.

01:14:12.640 --> 01:14:17.280
The beautiful line of statues that adorn

01:14:15.360 --> 01:14:19.120
the tall towers of the beautiful

01:14:17.280 --> 01:14:24.080
buildings in the city

01:14:19.120 --> 01:14:24.080
are now covered with layers of cobwebs.

01:14:25.280 --> 01:14:30.400
Whether truly motivated by these

01:14:27.360 --> 01:14:32.800
religious concerns or not, the Sangama

01:14:30.400 --> 01:14:35.440
brothers marched south and quickly

01:14:32.800 --> 01:14:36.960
conquered the now isolated Madurai

01:14:35.440 --> 01:14:39.040
Sultanate.

01:14:36.960 --> 01:14:41.600
With the southern Tamil country now

01:14:39.040 --> 01:14:44.159
under their control, the Sangama brothers

01:14:41.600 --> 01:14:45.840
now ruled over a large and wealthy

01:14:44.159 --> 01:14:48.400
territory.

01:14:45.840 --> 01:14:50.080
They returned to their former post on

01:14:48.400 --> 01:14:52.400
the rocky granite banks of the

01:14:50.080 --> 01:14:55.760
Tungabhadra River.

01:14:52.400 --> 01:14:58.400
It was an unassuming sight, just a small

01:14:55.760 --> 01:15:01.040
and fairly insignificant village

01:14:58.400 --> 01:15:03.440
known only for its shrine to Shiva, a

01:15:01.040 --> 01:15:06.159
focal point of pilgrimage.

01:15:03.440 --> 01:15:08.159
But here, they began to build a city

01:15:06.159 --> 01:15:09.280
that would announce in its size and

01:15:08.159 --> 01:15:12.239
ambition

01:15:09.280 --> 01:15:14.239
the arrival of a new confident power in

01:15:12.239 --> 01:15:17.520
the south of India.

01:15:14.239 --> 01:15:21.120
They named this city Vijayanagara, from

01:15:17.520 --> 01:15:23.360
the Sanskrit ‘vijaya’, meaning victory, and

01:15:21.120 --> 01:15:27.120
‘nagara’, meaning city,

01:15:23.360 --> 01:15:27.120
the city of victory.

01:15:33.760 --> 01:15:38.960
The city that the Sangamas built on the

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:40.880
banks of the Tungabhadra River testified

01:15:38.960 --> 01:15:42.719
to the ambitions that they held for

01:15:40.880 --> 01:15:45.440
their new kingdom.

01:15:42.719 --> 01:15:48.080
It would be a city of soaring temples

01:15:45.440 --> 01:15:51.040
and wide avenues built with an

01:15:48.080 --> 01:15:53.600
impressive grasp of urban planning, but

01:15:51.040 --> 01:15:55.679
the city was also a testament to the

01:15:53.600 --> 01:15:58.800
dangerous world that they now found

01:15:55.679 --> 01:16:01.280
themselves at the heart of.

01:15:58.800 --> 01:16:03.600
They would build Vijayanagara as a

01:16:01.280 --> 01:16:06.400
formidable fortress.

01:16:03.600 --> 01:16:08.800
The impassible granite hills already

01:16:06.400 --> 01:16:11.440
provided excellent defense while the

01:16:08.800 --> 01:16:14.000
wide, torrential Tungabhadra River

01:16:11.440 --> 01:16:16.960
protected it on the north side, almost

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:18.880
impossible for an army to ford.

01:16:16.960 --> 01:16:21.520
The brothers enhanced these natural

01:16:18.880 --> 01:16:24.000
defenses by fortifying the passes

01:16:21.520 --> 01:16:26.960
between the hills with strong gates and

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:29.440
towers, and these massive walls can still

01:16:26.960 --> 01:16:32.719
be traced in the landscape today,

01:16:29.440 --> 01:16:35.520
enclosing an area of more than 650

01:16:32.719 --> 01:16:39.360
square kilometers.

01:16:35.520 --> 01:16:42.239
The Afghan envoy Abdur Razzak, who visited

01:16:39.360 --> 01:16:45.760
in the 15th century, wrote the following

01:16:42.239 --> 01:16:45.760
description of the city.

01:16:47.120 --> 01:16:52.880
It is built in such a manner that seven

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:54.640
citadels and the same number of walls

01:16:52.880 --> 01:16:57.120
enclose each other.

01:16:54.640 --> 01:17:00.239
The seventh fortress, which is placed in

01:16:57.120 --> 01:17:03.199
the center of the other, occupies an area

01:17:00.239 --> 01:17:05.120
ten times larger than the marketplace of

01:17:03.199 --> 01:17:07.679
the city of Herat.

01:17:05.120 --> 01:17:11.040
It is the place which is used as the

01:17:07.679 --> 01:17:11.040
residence of the king.

01:17:12.239 --> 01:17:17.440
These walls were manned by soldiers who

01:17:15.040 --> 01:17:20.080
watched from the ramparts, operating

01:17:17.440 --> 01:17:22.000
watch posts on the broad roads that ran

01:17:20.080 --> 01:17:24.080
in and out of the city,

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:26.400
and in between the layers of walls were

01:17:24.080 --> 01:17:29.280
areas filled with boulders known as

01:17:26.400 --> 01:17:31.679
horse stones, designed to disrupt the

01:17:29.280 --> 01:17:33.600
movement of cavalry and guarantee that

01:17:31.679 --> 01:17:35.840
any attacking army would have a

01:17:33.600 --> 01:17:38.480
difficult time advancing while the

01:17:35.840 --> 01:17:41.679
soldiers of Vijayanagara rained arrow

01:17:38.480 --> 01:17:43.440
fire down on their heads.

01:17:41.679 --> 01:17:46.000
When you look at the situation that

01:17:43.440 --> 01:17:49.040
surrounded the city and the new empire

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:51.280
of Vijayanagara, it's not hard to see why

01:17:49.040 --> 01:17:54.000
these defensive fortifications were

01:17:51.280 --> 01:17:56.000
considered necessary.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:17:58.239
That's because the collapse of the Delhi

01:17:56.000 --> 01:18:00.800
Sultanate had left a number of

01:17:58.239 --> 01:18:04.159
fragmented kingdoms behind,

01:18:00.800 --> 01:18:07.600
who, like Vijayanagara, rose out of the

01:18:04.159 --> 01:18:09.840
chaos of the collapsing empire.

01:18:07.600 --> 01:18:12.560
The most powerful of these in South

01:18:09.840 --> 01:18:15.470
India was the society known as the

01:18:12.560 --> 01:18:21.920
Bahmani Sultanate.

01:18:21.920 --> 01:18:26.560
According to tradition, the Bahmani

01:18:24.400 --> 01:18:29.199
Sultanate was founded by an army

01:18:26.560 --> 01:18:31.920
commander named Zafar Khan, who had

01:18:29.199 --> 01:18:34.719
served under the erratic sultan Muhammad

01:18:31.920 --> 01:18:34.719
bin Tughlaq.

01:18:35.199 --> 01:18:39.920
It's clear that at some point he felt

01:18:37.440 --> 01:18:43.840
the waning power of the Delhi Sultanate

01:18:39.920 --> 01:18:46.560
in its final years, and in the year 1347,

01:18:43.840 --> 01:18:49.679
declared himself an independent king in

01:18:46.560 --> 01:18:53.679
South India, seizing a large portion of

01:18:49.679 --> 01:18:56.480
the rocky Deccan Plateau for himself.

01:18:53.679 --> 01:18:59.360
His gamble paid off;

01:18:56.480 --> 01:19:02.480
the weakened Delhi Sultanate, beset with

01:18:59.360 --> 01:19:05.280
problems on all sides, was no longer able

01:19:02.480 --> 01:19:06.480
to project its power south of the Vindhya

01:19:05.280 --> 01:19:10.400
mountains,

01:19:06.480 --> 01:19:10.400
and it did nothing to stop him.

01:19:10.480 --> 01:19:15.440
This newly independent power had to

01:19:13.280 --> 01:19:17.360
fight for its survival from its first

01:19:15.440 --> 01:19:20.080
days.

01:19:17.360 --> 01:19:22.480
After defeating one local Hindu ruler,

01:19:20.080 --> 01:19:24.960
the Bahmani Sultanate received as

01:19:22.480 --> 01:19:27.280
tribute a magnificent gift,

01:19:24.960 --> 01:19:30.000
an ornate throne decorated with

01:19:27.280 --> 01:19:32.719
turquoise enamel that would become a

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:37.440
symbol of their new empire,

01:19:32.719 --> 01:19:40.800
as the chronicler Ferishta recalls.

01:19:37.440 --> 01:19:44.159
The throne was in length nine feet and

01:19:40.800 --> 01:19:47.280
three in breadth, made of ebony covered

01:19:44.159 --> 01:19:50.960
with plates of pure gold, and set with

01:19:47.280 --> 01:19:53.440
precious stones of immense value.  Every

01:19:50.960 --> 01:19:55.840
prince of the House of Bahmani who

01:19:53.440 --> 01:19:58.800
possessed this throne made a point of

01:19:55.840 --> 01:20:00.800
adding to it some rich stones.

01:19:58.800 --> 01:20:03.360
I learned that it was called the

01:20:00.800 --> 01:20:06.080
Turquoise Throne from being partly

01:20:03.360 --> 01:20:09.040
enameled of a sky colour, which was in

01:20:06.080 --> 01:20:11.520
time totally concealed by the number of

01:20:09.040 --> 01:20:11.520
jewels.

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:16.960
This would become known as the Turquoise

01:20:14.400 --> 01:20:19.520
Throne of the Bahmanis, and it would

01:20:16.960 --> 01:20:21.280
become a symbol of Muslim power in the

01:20:19.520 --> 01:20:23.440
south of India.

01:20:21.280 --> 01:20:26.000
Above this throne, they affixed an

01:20:23.440 --> 01:20:29.280
umbrella, which the scholar Ferishta

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:29.280
also gushes about.

01:20:29.920 --> 01:20:36.239
He fixed a golden ball set with jewels,

01:20:33.199 --> 01:20:38.560
on which was a bird of paradise composed

01:20:36.239 --> 01:20:39.679
of precious stones at the top of the

01:20:38.560 --> 01:20:41.920
umbrella.

01:20:39.679 --> 01:20:45.120
On the bird's head was a ruby

01:20:41.920 --> 01:20:48.239
inestimable in value, which had been

01:20:45.120 --> 01:20:51.360
presented to the late sultan by the king

01:20:48.239 --> 01:20:51.360
of Vijayanagara.

01:20:51.920 --> 01:20:57.120
When this first sultan of the Bahmanis

01:20:54.480 --> 01:20:59.520
died, with his last words, he declared

01:20:57.120 --> 01:21:01.040
that his son Mohammed Shah Bahmani would

01:20:59.520 --> 01:21:03.440
take his throne,

01:21:01.040 --> 01:21:06.480
and he entreated his sons to stand

01:21:03.440 --> 01:21:10.159
united and build a kingdom that would

01:21:06.480 --> 01:21:12.880
stand the test of time, as the chronicler

01:21:10.159 --> 01:21:15.920
Ferishta writes.

01:21:12.880 --> 01:21:18.639
I conjure you, as you value the

01:21:15.920 --> 01:21:20.080
performance of this kingdom, to agree

01:21:18.639 --> 01:21:22.800
with each other.

01:21:20.080 --> 01:21:26.639
Mohammed is my successor.

01:21:22.800 --> 01:21:29.040
Esteem submission and loyalty to him as

01:21:26.639 --> 01:21:31.600
your duty in this world,

01:21:29.040 --> 01:21:34.239
and you’re surely for happiness

01:21:31.600 --> 01:21:34.239
in the next.

01:21:35.040 --> 01:21:40.159
The Bahmani Sultanate was a powerful

01:21:37.520 --> 01:21:42.639
Muslim kingdom in the heart of South

01:21:40.159 --> 01:21:45.120
India that would last for the best part

01:21:42.639 --> 01:21:48.080
of the next two centuries.

01:21:45.120 --> 01:21:52.000
For the Hindu people of Vijayanagara,

01:21:48.080 --> 01:21:55.560
it represented a constant looming threat

01:21:52.000 --> 01:21:55.560
on their border.

01:21:58.639 --> 01:22:04.719
Historians in India and in the West who

01:22:02.080 --> 01:22:07.360
subscribed to a nationalist idea of

01:22:04.719 --> 01:22:10.080
history have often framed the conflict

01:22:07.360 --> 01:22:13.360
between these two medieval kingdoms in

01:22:10.080 --> 01:22:15.440
terms of a clash of cultures.

01:22:13.360 --> 01:22:17.120
In this conception of history, they

01:22:15.440 --> 01:22:20.639
imagine the Hindu kingdom of

01:22:17.120 --> 01:22:24.480
Vijayanagara as a bastion defending

01:22:20.639 --> 01:22:26.960
Hindu culture from Islamic invaders.

01:22:24.480 --> 01:22:29.040
But there's little evidence to be found

01:22:26.960 --> 01:22:31.840
that the people or the rulers of

01:22:29.040 --> 01:22:33.360
Vijayanagara thought of the situation in

01:22:31.840 --> 01:22:35.520
this way.

01:22:33.360 --> 01:22:37.600
One inscription from the time of the

01:22:35.520 --> 01:22:40.239
Sangama brothers celebrates the

01:22:37.600 --> 01:22:41.679
victories of the Vijayanagara king

01:22:40.239 --> 01:22:43.840
Bukka Raya,

01:22:41.679 --> 01:22:46.800
and in it, we can see that they thought

01:22:43.840 --> 01:22:49.440
of the Turkic Bahmani Sultanate as just

01:22:46.800 --> 01:22:51.760
one of the many enemies that the kingdom

01:22:49.440 --> 01:22:54.080
of Vijayanagara faced.

01:22:51.760 --> 01:22:56.639
Its other enemies were all Hindu

01:22:54.080 --> 01:22:56.639
kingdoms.

01:22:56.719 --> 01:23:00.800
When his sword began to dance on the

01:22:58.320 --> 01:23:03.679
battlefield, the faces of the Turks

01:23:00.800 --> 01:23:05.280
shriveled up, Konkaya Sankaparya was

01:23:03.679 --> 01:23:08.080
filled with fear,

01:23:05.280 --> 01:23:09.760
the Andhras ran into caves, the Gurjaras

01:23:08.080 --> 01:23:10.560
lost the use of their limbs on every

01:23:09.760 --> 01:23:13.040
road,

01:23:10.560 --> 01:23:16.480
the Kambojas’ courage was broken, the

01:23:13.040 --> 01:23:16.480
Kalingas suffered defeat.

01:23:17.120 --> 01:23:21.840
Here, there is no mention of religion, and

01:23:20.000 --> 01:23:25.040
neither is there any hint that the

01:23:21.840 --> 01:23:28.400
Muslim Bahmanis were any more despicable

01:23:25.040 --> 01:23:31.120
to the kings of Vijayanagara than say

01:23:28.400 --> 01:23:32.800
the Hindu kings of Kalinga on the east

01:23:31.120 --> 01:23:34.960
coast.

01:23:32.800 --> 01:23:37.679
There's little evidence that the kings

01:23:34.960 --> 01:23:40.560
of Vijayanagara thought of themselves as

01:23:37.679 --> 01:23:43.280
defending Hinduism, and indeed, the idea

01:23:40.560 --> 01:23:46.639
of a unified Hindu identity simply

01:23:43.280 --> 01:23:49.199
didn't exist in the 14th century.

01:23:46.639 --> 01:23:52.080
While the two powers did fight long and

01:23:49.199 --> 01:23:54.159
bitter wars, the kings of Vijayanagara

01:23:52.080 --> 01:23:57.520
fought equally bitter wars with the

01:23:54.159 --> 01:24:00.159
Hindu Gajapatis, whose kings ruled over

01:23:57.520 --> 01:24:02.000
the humid, elephant-filled forest regions

01:24:00.159 --> 01:24:04.159
to the east.

01:24:02.000 --> 01:24:06.800
When religious divisions emerged

01:24:04.159 --> 01:24:09.360
within the kingdom of Vijayanagara, it

01:24:06.800 --> 01:24:12.480
was overwhelmingly between the followers

01:24:09.360 --> 01:24:15.600
of Vishnu and Shiva among the Hindus, or

01:24:12.480 --> 01:24:18.080
between Hindus and Jains.

01:24:15.600 --> 01:24:21.360
In fact, conflicts between the Bahmani

01:24:18.080 --> 01:24:23.760
Sultans and Vijayanagara often occurred

01:24:21.360 --> 01:24:24.800
due to greatly practical economic

01:24:23.760 --> 01:24:27.840
matters,

01:24:24.800 --> 01:24:31.280
like access to resources, supply lines,

01:24:27.840 --> 01:24:33.920
and trade routes. One bitter issue of

01:24:31.280 --> 01:24:37.760
contention was a rich tract of land

01:24:33.920 --> 01:24:40.480
between them known as the Raichur Doab.

01:24:37.760 --> 01:24:42.719
This was a triangle of land formed at

01:24:40.480 --> 01:24:44.480
the point where the rivers Krishna and

01:24:42.719 --> 01:24:47.920
Tungabhadra met,

01:24:44.480 --> 01:24:50.719
and it was immensely fertile.

01:24:47.920 --> 01:24:53.600
But it also held great deposits of iron

01:24:50.719 --> 01:24:56.000
and even diamonds. Other conflicts would

01:24:53.600 --> 01:24:59.280
break out over the rich river deltas to

01:24:56.000 --> 01:25:02.080
the east and the western coast of India,

01:24:59.280 --> 01:25:05.040
home to rich trading ports.

01:25:02.080 --> 01:25:07.600
These ports controlled traffic by sea

01:25:05.040 --> 01:25:10.560
with the Muslim world, and were a crucial

01:25:07.600 --> 01:25:13.520
conduit for the most important strategic

01:25:10.560 --> 01:25:16.880
military supply of the time; the powerful

01:25:13.520 --> 01:25:19.199
war horses imported from Arabia, Persia,

01:25:16.880 --> 01:25:21.199
and Central Asia.

01:25:19.199 --> 01:25:23.280
With these contentious territorial

01:25:21.199 --> 01:25:25.360
issues always on the minds of their

01:25:23.280 --> 01:25:28.000
rulers, wars between the Bahmani

01:25:25.360 --> 01:25:29.679
Sultanate and Vijayanagara broke out

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:31.280
constantly.

01:25:29.679 --> 01:25:33.920
With their connections to the Muslim

01:25:31.280 --> 01:25:36.560
world, the Bahmanis had the advantage for

01:25:33.920 --> 01:25:39.360
much of this region's history.

01:25:36.560 --> 01:25:42.880
Well-supplied with horses, the sultan of

01:25:39.360 --> 01:25:45.840
the Bahmanis became known as Ashvapati,

01:25:42.880 --> 01:25:49.280
or the Lord of Horses, while the kings of

01:25:45.840 --> 01:25:51.040
Vijayanagara were known as or

01:25:49.280 --> 01:25:53.040
Narapati, or the Lord of Men,

01:25:51.040 --> 01:25:55.520
alluding to their armies made up of

01:25:53.040 --> 01:25:57.520
largely massed infantry.

01:25:55.520 --> 01:25:59.920
The king of the Hindu Gajapatis in

01:25:57.520 --> 01:26:02.400
the east, with their vast stables of

01:25:59.920 --> 01:26:06.800
elephants, completed the triangle and

01:26:02.400 --> 01:26:06.800
became known as the Lord of Elephants.

01:26:07.360 --> 01:26:12.480
The Portuguese visitor Domingo Paes was

01:26:10.480 --> 01:26:14.960
suitably impressed by the infantry of

01:26:12.480 --> 01:26:18.880
Vijayanagara when he saw them marching in

01:26:14.960 --> 01:26:20.880
procession in the year 1520.

01:26:18.880 --> 01:26:22.719
The troops on foot are so many that they

01:26:20.880 --> 01:26:24.880
surrounded all the valleys and hills in

01:26:22.719 --> 01:26:26.880
a way with which nothing in the world

01:26:24.880 --> 01:26:28.719
can compare.

01:26:26.880 --> 01:26:31.600
At the waist, they have swords and small

01:26:28.719 --> 01:26:33.120
battleaxes, and in their hands, javelins

01:26:31.600 --> 01:26:35.920
with the shafts covered with gold and

01:26:33.120 --> 01:26:38.080
silver. You will see amongst them dresses

01:26:35.920 --> 01:26:39.440
of such rich cloths that I do not know

01:26:38.080 --> 01:26:41.600
where they came from.

01:26:39.440 --> 01:26:43.520
Nor could anyone tell you how many

01:26:41.600 --> 01:26:45.679
colors they have;

01:26:43.520 --> 01:26:48.320
shield-men with their shields, with many

01:26:45.679 --> 01:26:50.400
flowers of gold and silver on them,

01:26:48.320 --> 01:26:52.159
others with figures of tigers and other

01:26:50.400 --> 01:26:53.120
great beasts,

01:26:52.159 --> 01:26:55.840
others

01:26:53.120 --> 01:26:58.800
all are covered with silver leaf work,

01:26:55.840 --> 01:26:58.800
beautifully wrought.

01:26:58.880 --> 01:27:03.040
But in the early days, they were no match

01:27:01.280 --> 01:27:05.600
for the horsepower of the Bahmani

01:27:03.040 --> 01:27:08.320
Sultanate, and with their connections to

01:27:05.600 --> 01:27:11.040
the vibrant intellectual world of Muslim

01:27:08.320 --> 01:27:13.600
learning, the Bahmanis also enjoyed a

01:27:11.040 --> 01:27:16.080
technological advantage.

01:27:13.600 --> 01:27:18.560
One of the first sultans, Mohammed Shah

01:27:16.080 --> 01:27:20.880
Bahmani, was a keen follower of new

01:27:18.560 --> 01:27:23.360
technologies. He even established

01:27:20.880 --> 01:27:26.639
gunpowder factories in the sultanate to

01:27:23.360 --> 01:27:28.719
make use of the emerging technology.

01:27:26.639 --> 01:27:30.880
Gunpowder had first been introduced to

01:27:28.719 --> 01:27:32.159
India and the Middle East by the Mongols,

01:27:30.880 --> 01:27:33.679
who had learned about it from the

01:27:32.159 --> 01:27:35.920
Chinese.

01:27:33.679 --> 01:27:38.639
At this point, it was used mostly to

01:27:35.920 --> 01:27:40.880
create burning or exploding projectiles

01:27:38.639 --> 01:27:43.600
to be fired from catapults, and

01:27:40.880 --> 01:27:46.080
occasionally to create crude rockets.

01:27:43.600 --> 01:27:48.639
But soon, experiments would begin in

01:27:46.080 --> 01:27:52.400
using it to propel heavy projectiles

01:27:48.639 --> 01:27:55.760
along metal tubes, first as siege weapons

01:27:52.400 --> 01:27:58.080
and then as weapons on the battlefield.

01:27:55.760 --> 01:28:00.400
Soon, the sounds of cannon fire would

01:27:58.080 --> 01:28:03.440
ring out over the battlefields of

01:28:00.400 --> 01:28:05.840
medieval India, and the Bahmani sultans’

01:28:03.440 --> 01:28:08.000
early adoption of this technology would

01:28:05.840 --> 01:28:10.719
put them in a strong position in the

01:28:08.000 --> 01:28:13.679
coming centuries.

01:28:10.719 --> 01:28:16.000
So, although the Hindus of Vijayanagara

01:28:13.679 --> 01:28:18.639
were the larger and often wealthier

01:28:16.000 --> 01:28:20.880
kingdom, they often found themselves in

01:28:18.639 --> 01:28:23.040
the position of paying tribute to their

01:28:20.880 --> 01:28:25.520
Muslim neighbours to the north,

01:28:23.040 --> 01:28:27.840
whose powerful cavalry armies, soon

01:28:25.520 --> 01:28:31.199
backed by the technological might of

01:28:27.840 --> 01:28:33.840
cannons, gave them the upper hand.

01:28:31.199 --> 01:28:35.040
But these wars were never true wars of

01:28:33.840 --> 01:28:37.040
conquest.

01:28:35.040 --> 01:28:39.679
The two powers would fight over a

01:28:37.040 --> 01:28:42.800
seaport or the rich diamond mines of

01:28:39.679 --> 01:28:45.280
Raichur between them, but when the war's

01:28:42.800 --> 01:28:48.080
result became clear, the loser would

01:28:45.280 --> 01:28:50.480
inevitably sue for peace, agree to pay an

01:28:48.080 --> 01:28:52.639
enormous sum of money to the victor,

01:28:50.480 --> 01:28:55.040
often hand over one of their daughters

01:28:52.639 --> 01:28:57.840
in marriage, and then they would both

01:28:55.040 --> 01:29:00.480
return home.

01:28:57.840 --> 01:29:03.120
There was never any suggestion that one

01:29:00.480 --> 01:29:05.600
side in this rivalry would ever conquer

01:29:03.120 --> 01:29:07.520
and consume the other.

01:29:05.600 --> 01:29:10.320
Still, the growing power of the

01:29:07.520 --> 01:29:12.800
Bahmanis was of growing concern to the

01:29:10.320 --> 01:29:15.199
kings of Vijayanagara.

01:29:12.800 --> 01:29:17.760
Soon, the Bahmani Sultanate stretched

01:29:15.199 --> 01:29:20.800
right across India from east coast to

01:29:17.760 --> 01:29:23.600
west, an unbroken belt that walled off

01:29:20.800 --> 01:29:26.719
the people of Vijayanagara to the north,

01:29:23.600 --> 01:29:29.040
that seized the rich lands of Raichur, and

01:29:26.719 --> 01:29:31.840
meant that the Hindus of the south were

01:29:29.040 --> 01:29:35.199
forever looking with fearful eyes to

01:29:31.840 --> 01:29:35.199
their northern borders.

01:29:37.280 --> 01:29:46.520
But despite these concerns, the city of

01:29:40.320 --> 01:29:46.520
Vijayanagara grew with astonishing speed.

01:29:56.880 --> 01:30:03.360
From the mid-14th century, the capital of

01:30:00.520 --> 01:30:05.920
Vijayanagara grew steadily

01:30:03.360 --> 01:30:09.440
from the center of a wealthy kingdom

01:30:05.920 --> 01:30:11.360
into a great world capital.

01:30:09.440 --> 01:30:13.600
Thanks to developments in water

01:30:11.360 --> 01:30:15.679
management in the countryside, the

01:30:13.600 --> 01:30:18.400
population boomed.

01:30:15.679 --> 01:30:21.280
Enormous work teams would have dug new

01:30:18.400 --> 01:30:24.400
irrigation systems and reservoirs lined

01:30:21.280 --> 01:30:26.800
with stone, as well as distinctive step-

01:30:24.400 --> 01:30:29.679
-wells so that its people could draw

01:30:26.800 --> 01:30:33.040
water up from the earth.

01:30:29.679 --> 01:30:36.080
The city expanded rapidly, sprawling to

01:30:33.040 --> 01:30:39.280
absorb villages and towns around it, and

01:30:36.080 --> 01:30:42.400
soon grew to house as many as 300,000

01:30:39.280 --> 01:30:44.800
people at a time when London had only a

01:30:42.400 --> 01:30:47.600
fifth of that population, and when the

01:30:44.800 --> 01:30:49.360
largest city in Europe was Paris,

01:30:47.600 --> 01:30:50.800
with little more than two hundred

01:30:49.360 --> 01:30:52.960
thousand.

01:30:50.800 --> 01:30:55.520
By the year 1500,

01:30:52.960 --> 01:30:59.120
Vijayanagara was the world's second-

01:30:55.520 --> 01:31:02.719
-largest medieval city after Beijing,

01:30:59.120 --> 01:31:04.560
and probably India's richest. One poet

01:31:02.719 --> 01:31:07.520
alive at the time of the city's

01:31:04.560 --> 01:31:10.159
flourishing wrote the following ode to

01:31:07.520 --> 01:31:10.159
its beauty.

01:31:11.199 --> 01:31:18.719
Walk around the great city of victory.

01:31:15.360 --> 01:31:21.360
Go where you will on city streets.

01:31:18.719 --> 01:31:23.840
Everywhere you walk, bright assembly

01:31:21.360 --> 01:31:26.639
halls decked out with golden vessels

01:31:23.840 --> 01:31:28.800
will dazzle your eyes.

01:31:26.639 --> 01:31:31.199
On many streets, homes with mirrored

01:31:28.800 --> 01:31:33.600
doors will shine, and sugarcane and

01:31:31.199 --> 01:31:35.440
plantain all around will invite you with

01:31:33.600 --> 01:31:37.760
welcomes.

01:31:35.440 --> 01:31:38.880
You'll find able-bodied fighters and

01:31:37.760 --> 01:31:42.000
horses,

01:31:38.880 --> 01:31:44.719
elephants and riders. You'll smell aromas

01:31:42.000 --> 01:31:47.520
of camphor and musk from breasts of

01:31:44.719 --> 01:31:49.679
exquisite doe-eyed women.

01:31:47.520 --> 01:31:51.040
You will face gardens lush with

01:31:49.679 --> 01:31:53.920
enjoyments,

01:31:51.040 --> 01:31:58.480
precious stones and glowing gold,

01:31:53.920 --> 01:32:01.600
a city of wealth and glory gleaming.

01:31:58.480 --> 01:32:04.159
You'll agree that this magnificent city

01:32:01.600 --> 01:32:06.480
is the most enchanting place you've ever

01:32:04.159 --> 01:32:06.480
seen.

01:32:06.719 --> 01:32:11.679
The city also benefited from being

01:32:09.280 --> 01:32:14.800
surrounded by a seemingly inexhaustible

01:32:11.679 --> 01:32:16.719
amount of exceptional building material

01:32:14.800 --> 01:32:20.880
in the form of the large granite

01:32:16.719 --> 01:32:24.159
boulders of Hampi's ancient terrain.

01:32:20.880 --> 01:32:26.560
Vijayanagara was truly a city of stone,

01:32:24.159 --> 01:32:29.440
with all its palaces and stables, its

01:32:26.560 --> 01:32:32.560
towers and walls, even the houses of its

01:32:29.440 --> 01:32:34.560
citizens carved out of blocks of solid

01:32:32.560 --> 01:32:37.360
granite.

01:32:34.560 --> 01:32:40.960
An ambassador from the Timurid capital

01:32:37.360 --> 01:32:43.679
of Samarkand named Abdur Razzak, working

01:32:40.960 --> 01:32:46.000
as an ambassador for the Persian king,

01:32:43.679 --> 01:32:47.760
passed through Vijayanagara in the year

01:32:46.000 --> 01:32:50.639
1443,

01:32:47.760 --> 01:32:53.040
and by this time, the city's skyline had

01:32:50.639 --> 01:32:56.960
grown impressive enough for him to give

01:32:53.040 --> 01:32:56.960
the following glowing report.

01:32:57.120 --> 01:33:03.120
The city of Bidjnagar is such that the

01:33:00.400 --> 01:33:06.639
pupil of the eye has never seen a place

01:33:03.120 --> 01:33:08.480
like it, and the ear of intelligence has

01:33:06.639 --> 01:33:11.760
never been informed

01:33:08.480 --> 01:33:14.400
that there existed anything to equal it

01:33:11.760 --> 01:33:14.400
in the world.

01:33:15.120 --> 01:33:21.440
Vijayanagara would continue to grow.

01:33:18.239 --> 01:33:22.400
By the early 16th century, some 50 years

01:33:21.440 --> 01:33:24.400
later,

01:33:22.400 --> 01:33:26.800
it would be home to as many as half a

01:33:24.400 --> 01:33:29.520
million people, and the Portuguese writer

01:33:26.800 --> 01:33:32.239
Domingo Paes was stunned to see the

01:33:29.520 --> 01:33:34.239
heights it had reached.

01:33:32.239 --> 01:33:36.880
The size of the city cannot all be seen

01:33:34.239 --> 01:33:38.960
from one spot, but I climbed a hill whence

01:33:36.880 --> 01:33:40.800
I could see a great part of it.

01:33:38.960 --> 01:33:43.120
I could not see it all because it lies

01:33:40.800 --> 01:33:45.920
between several ranges of hills.

01:33:43.120 --> 01:33:47.360
What I saw from then seemed to me as

01:33:45.920 --> 01:33:51.120
large as Rome

01:33:47.360 --> 01:33:53.679
and very beautiful to the sight.

01:33:51.120 --> 01:33:56.080
Paes was also impressed by the great

01:33:53.679 --> 01:33:58.880
abundance available in the markets of

01:33:56.080 --> 01:33:58.880
Vijayanagara.

01:33:59.280 --> 01:34:02.080
Going forward, you have a broad and

01:34:00.719 --> 01:34:04.239
beautiful street,

01:34:02.080 --> 01:34:06.239
full of rows of fine houses and streets

01:34:04.239 --> 01:34:08.080
of sorts I've described, and it is

01:34:06.239 --> 01:34:10.239
understood that the houses belong to men

01:34:08.080 --> 01:34:12.719
rich enough to afford such.

01:34:10.239 --> 01:34:14.239
In this city live many merchants,

01:34:12.719 --> 01:34:16.719
and there you will find all sorts of

01:34:14.239 --> 01:34:19.679
rubies and diamonds and emeralds and

01:34:16.719 --> 01:34:21.360
pearls and seed pearls and cloths,

01:34:19.679 --> 01:34:25.440
and every other sort of thing there is

01:34:21.360 --> 01:34:25.440
on the earth that you may wish to buy.

01:34:26.159 --> 01:34:30.800
Vijayanagara was divided into a number

01:34:28.719 --> 01:34:32.719
of different districts, each with a

01:34:30.800 --> 01:34:34.960
unique character.

01:34:32.719 --> 01:34:37.040
Near the river was the area known today

01:34:34.960 --> 01:34:39.120
as the Sacred Center,

01:34:37.040 --> 01:34:41.679
so called because of the many large

01:34:39.120 --> 01:34:44.960
temples that can be found here. Here, the

01:34:41.679 --> 01:34:48.159
mighty Virupaksha temple still soars up

01:34:44.960 --> 01:34:51.360
to the sky, with its enormous carved gate

01:34:48.159 --> 01:34:53.520
tower known as a gopuram.

01:34:51.360 --> 01:34:55.840
The streets here would have been full of

01:34:53.520 --> 01:34:58.719
the sounds of chanting hymns and the

01:34:55.840 --> 01:35:01.760
clanging of temple bells, the smoke of

01:34:58.719 --> 01:35:04.719
incense, and the pleas of the faithful

01:35:01.760 --> 01:35:07.280
as they came to pray, to be healed, and to

01:35:04.719 --> 01:35:09.840
be closer to the gods.

01:35:07.280 --> 01:35:12.080
Many of these temples were so large that

01:35:09.840 --> 01:35:14.480
for tax purposes, they were classed as

01:35:12.080 --> 01:35:16.719
towns in their own right.

01:35:14.480 --> 01:35:19.360
These enormous building complexes

01:35:16.719 --> 01:35:22.960
supported a huge cast of retainers and

01:35:19.360 --> 01:35:25.679
specialists, dancers and labourers, cooks

01:35:22.960 --> 01:35:28.880
and cleaners, as well as scholars, holy

01:35:25.679 --> 01:35:31.280
men, and artists.

01:35:28.880 --> 01:35:34.719
Further south is what's been termed the

01:35:31.280 --> 01:35:37.199
urban core, a walled area of around 20

01:35:34.719 --> 01:35:40.480
square kilometers that contains both

01:35:37.199 --> 01:35:43.440
houses and markets, as well as workshops,

01:35:40.480 --> 01:35:46.400
rest houses, and other places of business,

01:35:43.440 --> 01:35:48.880
as the historian Atul Chandra Chatterjee

01:35:46.400 --> 01:35:50.719
recalls.

01:35:48.880 --> 01:35:53.440
The great majority of the houses were

01:35:50.719 --> 01:35:55.920
naturally small and undistinguished, but

01:35:53.440 --> 01:35:59.280
among them were scattered palaces,

01:35:55.920 --> 01:36:02.800
temples, public buildings, wide streets of

01:35:59.280 --> 01:36:05.119
shops shaded by trees, busy markets, and

01:36:02.800 --> 01:36:07.520
all the equipment of a great and wealthy

01:36:05.119 --> 01:36:07.520
city.

01:36:08.000 --> 01:36:12.960
Here, the ruined remains of the city

01:36:10.480 --> 01:36:14.400
clearly show a great amount of religious

01:36:12.960 --> 01:36:17.360
diversity.

01:36:14.400 --> 01:36:19.840
Local temples here cater to the Jains, as

01:36:17.360 --> 01:36:22.800
well as Hindu temples for both Vishnu

01:36:19.840 --> 01:36:24.880
and Shiva followers, and one area with a

01:36:22.800 --> 01:36:27.920
mosque.

01:36:24.880 --> 01:36:30.239
The Portuguese traveler Duarte Barbosa,

01:36:27.920 --> 01:36:33.119
arriving in Vijayanagara around the year

01:36:30.239 --> 01:36:36.800
1501, gave the following vivid

01:36:33.119 --> 01:36:39.360
description of this district.

01:36:36.800 --> 01:36:42.080
The houses are thatched, but are

01:36:39.360 --> 01:36:44.960
nonetheless very well-built and arranged

01:36:42.080 --> 01:36:47.199
according to occupations in long streets

01:36:44.960 --> 01:36:49.760
with many open places,

01:36:47.199 --> 01:36:51.920
and the folk here are ever in such

01:36:49.760 --> 01:36:53.760
numbers that the streets and places

01:36:51.920 --> 01:36:56.560
cannot contain them.

01:36:53.760 --> 01:36:59.600
There is a great traffic and an endless

01:36:56.560 --> 01:37:02.719
number of merchants and wealthy men.

01:36:59.600 --> 01:37:05.520
The king allows such freedom that every

01:37:02.719 --> 01:37:08.639
man may come and go according to his

01:37:05.520 --> 01:37:11.119
creed, without suffering any annoyance,

01:37:08.639 --> 01:37:13.520
and without inquiry whether he is

01:37:11.119 --> 01:37:15.920
Christian, Jew, Moor,

01:37:13.520 --> 01:37:18.880
or Heathen.

01:37:15.920 --> 01:37:21.199
Barbosa also pays particular attention

01:37:18.880 --> 01:37:23.600
to the smells that would have wafted

01:37:21.199 --> 01:37:26.800
through the air from the markets selling

01:37:23.600 --> 01:37:30.320
spices and perfumes.

01:37:26.800 --> 01:37:31.280
Here also is used vermilion, saffron, rose

01:37:30.320 --> 01:37:34.800
water, a

01:37:31.280 --> 01:37:39.199
great store of opium, sandalwood, aloes-

01:37:34.800 --> 01:37:42.880
-wood, camphor musk, and scented materials.

01:37:39.199 --> 01:37:48.040
Likewise, much pepper is used here, which

01:37:42.880 --> 01:37:48.040
they bring from Malabar on donkeys and pack

01:37:50.639 --> 01:37:54.320
cattle. Here, we can imagine scenes of family

01:37:53.360 --> 01:37:56.639
life;

01:37:54.320 --> 01:37:58.880
children running in the streets, wood

01:37:56.639 --> 01:38:01.040
smoke billowing overhead.

01:37:58.880 --> 01:38:03.920
Men would gather here to play games of

01:38:01.040 --> 01:38:06.719
chance and strategy on street corners,

01:38:03.920 --> 01:38:09.280
chewing betel nuts and leaves, which are

01:38:06.719 --> 01:38:10.480
chewed across India for a mild stimulant

01:38:09.280 --> 01:38:12.320
effect.

01:38:10.480 --> 01:38:13.920
Women would talk in the shade of

01:38:12.320 --> 01:38:16.239
coloured awnings,

01:38:13.920 --> 01:38:17.360
cows wondering unhindered among the

01:38:16.239 --> 01:38:20.000
crowds,

01:38:17.360 --> 01:38:21.520
and groups of musicians playing on the

01:38:20.000 --> 01:38:23.119
streets.

01:38:21.520 --> 01:38:25.920
It's during this time in the

01:38:23.119 --> 01:38:29.119
Vijayanagara Empire that the distinctive

01:38:25.920 --> 01:38:32.080
form of Indian classical music known as

01:38:29.119 --> 01:38:34.239
Carnatic music was laid down.

01:38:32.080 --> 01:38:38.080
We're joined on this episode by the

01:38:34.239 --> 01:38:40.320
virtuoso of Carnatic music, Aruna Sairam,

01:38:38.080 --> 01:38:43.040
who has recorded a number of authentic

01:38:40.320 --> 01:38:44.719
Carnatic pieces especially for this

01:38:43.040 --> 01:38:48.880
podcast,

01:38:44.719 --> 01:38:48.880
one of which you're listening to now.

01:38:50.080 --> 01:38:55.119
We can imagine the sounds of this music

01:38:52.400 --> 01:38:57.840
drifting over the streets and rooftops

01:38:55.119 --> 01:39:01.440
of Vijayanagara as the business of

01:38:57.840 --> 01:39:01.440
everyday life went on.

01:39:01.760 --> 01:39:06.480
The day of an average citizen would have

01:39:04.080 --> 01:39:08.000
started with a bath in a local

01:39:06.480 --> 01:39:10.080
bathhouse.

01:39:08.000 --> 01:39:12.480
Men and women had separate bathing

01:39:10.080 --> 01:39:14.719
places, which were available at different

01:39:12.480 --> 01:39:17.119
times of the day.

01:39:14.719 --> 01:39:19.280
After bathing, families would go to their

01:39:17.119 --> 01:39:22.239
local temple to give offerings and

01:39:19.280 --> 01:39:24.080
receive blessings for the day ahead.

01:39:22.239 --> 01:39:26.960
We can see the clothing worn by the

01:39:24.080 --> 01:39:29.679
people of Vijayanagara in the colorful

01:39:26.960 --> 01:39:32.960
16th century murals that decorate the

01:39:29.679 --> 01:39:35.280
walls of temples to Shiva and Vishnu in

01:39:32.960 --> 01:39:37.920
the village of Lepakshi.

01:39:35.280 --> 01:39:41.199
They show women with strikingly varied

01:39:37.920 --> 01:39:43.600
skin tones wearing saris in multiple

01:39:41.199 --> 01:39:47.360
ornate patterns drawn from different

01:39:43.600 --> 01:39:49.920
regions, with pearls in their hair.

01:39:47.360 --> 01:39:52.000
Other murals show noblemen hunting a

01:39:49.920 --> 01:39:55.280
boar through the forest, with their

01:39:52.000 --> 01:39:57.920
facial hair cut into refined beards,

01:39:55.280 --> 01:40:00.400
wearing kilt-like lower garments and

01:39:57.920 --> 01:40:02.639
jeweled necklaces.

01:40:00.400 --> 01:40:05.119
Turbans and other headdresses were

01:40:02.639 --> 01:40:07.840
popular headgear among the rich.

01:40:05.119 --> 01:40:11.520
Both men and women wore perfumes made of

01:40:07.840 --> 01:40:12.880
sandalwood, rose water, flowers, civet, and

01:40:11.520 --> 01:40:15.280
musk.

01:40:12.880 --> 01:40:17.199
Shopkeepers in this part of the city and

01:40:15.280 --> 01:40:19.760
everywhere else would need to be

01:40:17.199 --> 01:40:22.639
constantly alert to the mischief of the

01:40:19.760 --> 01:40:25.360
monkeys that still live to this day in

01:40:22.639 --> 01:40:28.080
huge numbers in the region of Hampi; the

01:40:25.360 --> 01:40:32.000
red-faced rhesus macaques and the

01:40:28.080 --> 01:40:34.880
silvery-grey or Hanuman langurs.

01:40:32.000 --> 01:40:37.280
Then as now, these animals love nothing

01:40:34.880 --> 01:40:39.679
better than to slink along the rooftops

01:40:37.280 --> 01:40:42.800
in their troops, drop down from shop

01:40:39.679 --> 01:40:46.000
awnings, and steal food from whoever has

01:40:42.800 --> 01:40:46.000
let down their guard.

01:40:46.480 --> 01:40:51.760
Towering over this bustling residential

01:40:48.880 --> 01:40:54.560
district was the royal center.

01:40:51.760 --> 01:40:57.280
This was an area of walled enclosures

01:40:54.560 --> 01:40:59.280
that guard the large monumental palaces

01:40:57.280 --> 01:41:02.159
and mansions that were home to the

01:40:59.280 --> 01:41:05.119
city's wealthy elite, and it's clear that

01:41:02.159 --> 01:41:07.280
while they were Hindu, these city elites

01:41:05.119 --> 01:41:10.000
had a great deal of admiration for their

01:41:07.280 --> 01:41:12.159
Muslim rivals to the north.

01:41:10.000 --> 01:41:14.800
In these spacious houses, the

01:41:12.159 --> 01:41:17.440
architecture clearly shows a blend of

01:41:14.800 --> 01:41:20.000
Indian and Islamic styles.

01:41:17.440 --> 01:41:22.080
Some wall paintings in Vijayanagara even

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:24.080
show the court wearing clothing in the

01:41:22.080 --> 01:41:25.600
style of their Muslim neighbours for

01:41:24.080 --> 01:41:29.199
formal events;

01:41:25.600 --> 01:41:31.520
tall caps and flowing gowns.

01:41:29.199 --> 01:41:33.760
Outside the walls of the city, the

01:41:31.520 --> 01:41:36.800
surrounding countryside was divided into

01:41:33.760 --> 01:41:39.280
a lacework of roads and fields joining

01:41:36.800 --> 01:41:42.320
villages and larger towns that all

01:41:39.280 --> 01:41:44.880
provided grains like rice and millet, as

01:41:42.320 --> 01:41:47.840
well as squashes, gourds, and other

01:41:44.880 --> 01:41:50.080
vegetables to the great city itself,

01:41:47.840 --> 01:41:52.480
brought in enormous quantities by

01:41:50.080 --> 01:41:56.480
bullock carts that would have filled the

01:41:52.480 --> 01:41:56.480
roads with a thick traffic.

01:41:58.560 --> 01:42:04.320
The perspectives of historians on

01:42:01.199 --> 01:42:07.360
Vijayanagara vary greatly, and in the

01:42:04.320 --> 01:42:09.760
past has caused huge disagreements,

01:42:07.360 --> 01:42:11.760
often among historians who may be

01:42:09.760 --> 01:42:13.679
approaching the evidence from a

01:42:11.760 --> 01:42:16.800
nationalist perspective or from a

01:42:13.679 --> 01:42:18.960
colonial or post-colonial perspective.

01:42:16.800 --> 01:42:21.520
Some of this is down to the differing

01:42:18.960 --> 01:42:25.119
ideologies of these historians,

01:42:21.520 --> 01:42:28.159
but the Vijayanagara Empire was a place of

01:42:25.119 --> 01:42:30.880
paradoxes and contrasts.

01:42:28.159 --> 01:42:33.679
On one hand, its rulers clearly modeled

01:42:30.880 --> 01:42:35.679
themselves on the old Hindu South Indian

01:42:33.679 --> 01:42:38.159
empires of the past.

01:42:35.679 --> 01:42:40.400
One clear example is in the temples they

01:42:38.159 --> 01:42:43.280
built, which drew inspiration from

01:42:40.400 --> 01:42:46.000
ancient Hindu empires like the Chalukyas,

01:42:43.280 --> 01:42:47.920
the Pandyas, and the Cholas.

01:42:46.000 --> 01:42:50.400
These buildings were designed to

01:42:47.920 --> 01:42:53.119
reinforce the empire's connection to the

01:42:50.400 --> 01:42:55.520
Hindu powers of the past, but in many

01:42:53.119 --> 01:42:58.800
other ways, it was also a surprisingly

01:42:55.520 --> 01:43:01.600
radical experiment, a hybrid culture that

01:42:58.800 --> 01:43:03.440
took Hindu traditions and married them

01:43:01.600 --> 01:43:06.320
with an outward and forward-looking

01:43:03.440 --> 01:43:09.360
desire for new influences from the

01:43:06.320 --> 01:43:11.600
Muslim world and beyond.

01:43:09.360 --> 01:43:14.239
The world of medieval India was

01:43:11.600 --> 01:43:17.040
fast-moving and competitive, and those

01:43:14.239 --> 01:43:19.280
kingdoms that fell behind often didn't

01:43:17.040 --> 01:43:22.239
last long.

01:43:19.280 --> 01:43:25.600
One king of Vijayanagara in particular,

01:43:22.239 --> 01:43:26.800
named Devaraya II, was all too aware of

01:43:25.600 --> 01:43:29.280
this.

01:43:26.800 --> 01:43:32.320
He was determined to modernize and

01:43:29.280 --> 01:43:35.199
hybridize the empire of Vijayanagara,

01:43:32.320 --> 01:43:37.360
and end the days of it paying tribute to

01:43:35.199 --> 01:43:38.400
the powerful Muslim kingdoms to the

01:43:37.360 --> 01:43:40.639
north.

01:43:38.400 --> 01:43:44.639
To do this, he would open the

01:43:40.639 --> 01:43:44.639
empire's doors to the world.

01:43:47.600 --> 01:43:52.639
Devaraya II

01:43:49.280 --> 01:43:56.239
came to the throne in the year 1432

01:43:52.639 --> 01:43:58.639
as a boy of only eight years old.

01:43:56.239 --> 01:44:00.880
One Persian visitor to his court, who

01:43:58.639 --> 01:44:03.199
arrived about eight years later, gives

01:44:00.880 --> 01:44:05.440
the following description of the teenage

01:44:03.199 --> 01:44:08.560
king.

01:44:05.440 --> 01:44:12.000
The king was dressed in a robe of green

01:44:08.560 --> 01:44:15.600
satin. Around his neck he wore a collar

01:44:12.000 --> 01:44:18.639
composed of pearls of beautiful water

01:44:15.600 --> 01:44:22.400
and other splendid gems.

01:44:18.639 --> 01:44:24.159
He was of an olive color, of a spare body,

01:44:22.400 --> 01:44:26.880
and rather tall.

01:44:24.159 --> 01:44:30.639
He was exceedingly young, for there was

01:44:26.880 --> 01:44:32.960
only some slight down upon his cheeks,

01:44:30.639 --> 01:44:35.440
and none upon his chin.

01:44:32.960 --> 01:44:38.000
His whole appearance was very

01:44:35.440 --> 01:44:40.400
repossessing.

01:44:38.000 --> 01:44:43.119
This young king Devaraya was

01:44:40.400 --> 01:44:45.480
determined to turn his empire into a

01:44:43.119 --> 01:44:47.440
modern outward-looking state.

01:44:47.440 --> 01:44:51.199
To do this,

01:44:48.480 --> 01:44:53.360
he sent out word to the Muslim world

01:44:51.199 --> 01:44:54.560
that the doors of his kingdom were now

01:44:53.360 --> 01:44:57.199
open.

01:44:54.560 --> 01:44:59.840
He welcomed talented Muslim courtiers

01:44:57.199 --> 01:45:03.040
into his kingdom, and enlisted as many as

01:44:59.840 --> 01:45:06.800
200 Muslim officers into his army, as the

01:45:03.040 --> 01:45:06.800
scholar Ferishta recalls.

01:45:07.119 --> 01:45:12.639
Devaraya gave orders to enlist Muslims

01:45:09.920 --> 01:45:14.719
in his service, allotting them estates

01:45:12.639 --> 01:45:18.400
and erecting a mosque for their use in

01:45:14.719 --> 01:45:20.320
Vijayanagara. He also commanded that no

01:45:18.400 --> 01:45:22.639
one should molest them in exercise of

01:45:20.320 --> 01:45:24.960
their religion, and moreover,

01:45:22.639 --> 01:45:27.600
he ordered a Quran to be placed before

01:45:24.960 --> 01:45:30.080
his throne on a rich desk so that the

01:45:27.600 --> 01:45:33.360
faithful might perform the ceremony of

01:45:30.080 --> 01:45:36.320
obeisance in his presence without sinning

01:45:33.360 --> 01:45:36.320
against their laws.

01:45:36.560 --> 01:45:42.159
Some carvings on the great temples of

01:45:38.719 --> 01:45:44.960
the city show Muslims taking part in its

01:45:42.159 --> 01:45:47.280
daily life, showing Arab horse handlers

01:45:44.960 --> 01:45:50.080
taking care of their steeds,

01:45:47.280 --> 01:45:53.119
and columns in the great Vitthala temple

01:45:50.080 --> 01:45:55.440
show Muslim horse riders wearing turbans,

01:45:53.119 --> 01:45:56.840
rearing up on the backs of powerful,

01:45:55.440 --> 01:46:00.320
imported

01:45:56.840 --> 01:46:03.199
horses. The borders of Vijayanagara were

01:46:00.320 --> 01:46:05.840
now guarded by large forces of Muslim

01:46:03.199 --> 01:46:07.760
cavalry, mercenaries paid from the vast

01:46:05.840 --> 01:46:10.000
coffers of the empire,

01:46:07.760 --> 01:46:13.360
and to these would soon be added units

01:46:10.000 --> 01:46:16.080
of Portuguese and Muslim gunners trained

01:46:13.360 --> 01:46:18.880
in the use of muskets.

01:46:16.080 --> 01:46:21.440
This influx of newcomers would change

01:46:18.880 --> 01:46:23.280
the nature of Vijayanagara's military,

01:46:21.440 --> 01:46:25.440
bringing advanced modern battle

01:46:23.280 --> 01:46:26.800
strategies and the increased use of

01:46:25.440 --> 01:46:28.960
cavalry,

01:46:26.800 --> 01:46:31.760
and it would have changed the fabric of

01:46:28.960 --> 01:46:35.280
the city itself.

01:46:31.760 --> 01:46:37.679
Devaraya II also engaged in large-scale

01:46:35.280 --> 01:46:40.159
infrastructure projects, digging large

01:46:37.679 --> 01:46:42.320
networks of canals that expanded the

01:46:40.159 --> 01:46:43.679
agricultural potential of the land

01:46:42.320 --> 01:46:46.400
around the city.

01:46:43.679 --> 01:46:47.440
The metropolis boomed to even greater

01:46:46.400 --> 01:46:50.159
size,

01:46:47.440 --> 01:46:52.000
and the Persian ambassador Abdur Razzak

01:46:50.159 --> 01:46:54.960
was so impressed by the city when he

01:46:52.000 --> 01:46:57.280
visited in the year 1443 that he gave

01:46:54.960 --> 01:47:01.520
the following incredible account of the

01:46:57.280 --> 01:47:01.520
bustling life of the city's markets.

01:47:02.639 --> 01:47:08.000
From the third to the seventh fortress,

01:47:05.360 --> 01:47:09.119
shops and bazaars are loosely crowded

01:47:08.000 --> 01:47:11.520
together.

01:47:09.119 --> 01:47:15.360
By the palace of the king, there are four

01:47:11.520 --> 01:47:17.840
bazaars situated opposite to one another.

01:47:15.360 --> 01:47:21.760
At the head of each bazaar there is a

01:47:17.840 --> 01:47:24.239
lofty arcade and magnificent gallery, but

01:47:21.760 --> 01:47:25.679
the palace of the king is loftier than

01:47:24.239 --> 01:47:28.719
all of them.

01:47:25.679 --> 01:47:31.199
The bazaars are very broad and long so

01:47:28.719 --> 01:47:33.920
that the sellers of flowers are able to

01:47:31.199 --> 01:47:36.639
sell flowers from both sides.

01:47:33.920 --> 01:47:40.960
Sweet-scented flowers are always

01:47:36.639 --> 01:47:40.960
procurable fresh in that city.

01:47:42.320 --> 01:47:47.920
Even traveling from the wealthy Silk

01:47:44.400 --> 01:47:50.080
Road city of Samarkand, Abdur Razzak was

01:47:47.920 --> 01:47:53.520
struck by the obvious wealth of the

01:47:50.080 --> 01:47:56.960
citizens of Vijayanagara.

01:47:53.520 --> 01:47:59.920
This country is so well-populated that

01:47:56.960 --> 01:48:02.400
it is impossible in a reasonable space

01:47:59.920 --> 01:48:04.480
to convey an idea of it.

01:48:02.400 --> 01:48:07.679
In the king's treasury, there are

01:48:04.480 --> 01:48:11.280
chambers with excavations in them filled

01:48:07.679 --> 01:48:13.360
with molten gold forming one mass.

01:48:11.280 --> 01:48:16.159
All the inhabitants of the country,

01:48:13.360 --> 01:48:18.480
whether high or low, even down to the

01:48:16.159 --> 01:48:21.119
artificers of the bazaar,

01:48:18.480 --> 01:48:24.400
wear jewels and gilt ornaments in their

01:48:21.119 --> 01:48:26.320
ears and around their necks, arms, wrists,

01:48:24.400 --> 01:48:29.199
and fingers.

01:48:26.320 --> 01:48:32.080
Abdur Razzak was especially struck by the

01:48:29.199 --> 01:48:34.239
vast stone elephant stables which can

01:48:32.080 --> 01:48:37.600
still be seen in the ruins of

01:48:34.239 --> 01:48:37.600
Vijayanagara today.

01:48:38.159 --> 01:48:42.400
Opposite the minister's office are the

01:48:40.159 --> 01:48:44.639
elephant sheds. The king has many

01:48:42.400 --> 01:48:46.800
elephants in the country, but the large

01:48:44.639 --> 01:48:47.840
ones are especially reserved for the

01:48:46.800 --> 01:48:49.679
palace.

01:48:47.840 --> 01:48:52.239
The king has a white elephant,

01:48:49.679 --> 01:48:55.199
exceedingly large, with here and there as

01:48:52.239 --> 01:48:57.199
many as 30 spots of color.

01:48:55.199 --> 01:48:59.360
Every morning, this animal is brought

01:48:57.199 --> 01:49:01.600
into the presence of the monarch, for to

01:48:59.360 --> 01:49:03.440
cast an eye upon him is thought a

01:49:01.600 --> 01:49:05.760
favorable omen.

01:49:03.440 --> 01:49:08.639
Each has a separate stall;

01:49:05.760 --> 01:49:12.080
the walls are very strong and high, and

01:49:08.639 --> 01:49:14.560
are covered with strong wood.

01:49:12.080 --> 01:49:16.880
He gives a clearly quite bashful

01:49:14.560 --> 01:49:20.239
account of the city's apparently

01:49:16.880 --> 01:49:22.639
thriving red light district.

01:49:20.239 --> 01:49:25.840
Opposite the mint is the office of the

01:49:22.639 --> 01:49:29.199
prefect of the city, to which it is said

01:49:25.840 --> 01:49:32.159
12,000 policemen are attached, and their

01:49:29.199 --> 01:49:34.000
pay, which equals each day twelve

01:49:32.159 --> 01:49:36.400
thousand fanams,

01:49:34.000 --> 01:49:38.000
is derived from the proceeds of the

01:49:36.400 --> 01:49:41.440
brothels.

01:49:38.000 --> 01:49:43.360
The splendor of those houses, the beauty

01:49:41.440 --> 01:49:45.760
of the heart ravishers, their

01:49:43.360 --> 01:49:48.560
blandishments and ogles,

01:49:45.760 --> 01:49:51.320
are beyond all description.

01:49:48.560 --> 01:49:53.840
It is best to be brief on the matter.

01:49:53.840 --> 01:49:58.719
Finally, he was brought in to meet the

01:49:56.239 --> 01:50:01.840
king Devaraya, who at that point would

01:49:58.719 --> 01:50:03.840
have been around the age of 19.

01:50:01.840 --> 01:50:06.239
Perhaps most illuminating about this

01:50:03.840 --> 01:50:08.960
meeting is how many questions the Hindu

01:50:06.239 --> 01:50:11.520
king asked his Muslim visitor.

01:50:08.960 --> 01:50:13.920
He bombarded the Persian ambassador with

01:50:11.520 --> 01:50:16.080
inquiries about the great Muslim powers

01:50:13.920 --> 01:50:18.800
of the world, how many horsemen the king

01:50:16.080 --> 01:50:20.880
of Persia had under his command, what his

01:50:18.800 --> 01:50:22.159
great nobles were like, and how they

01:50:20.880 --> 01:50:24.400
behaved.

01:50:22.159 --> 01:50:27.360
He asked many questions about the great

01:50:24.400 --> 01:50:29.840
cities of Herat and Shiraz, and it's

01:50:27.360 --> 01:50:32.840
clear from this the curiosity and

01:50:29.840 --> 01:50:35.440
fascination he held for the Muslim world.

01:50:35.440 --> 01:50:40.400
But being the king of a medieval kingdom

01:50:38.639 --> 01:50:43.199
like Vijayanagara

01:50:40.400 --> 01:50:46.239
could be a dangerous business.

01:50:43.199 --> 01:50:49.199
Devaraya sat at the top of a towering

01:50:46.239 --> 01:50:51.280
and fragile hierarchy packed with

01:50:49.199 --> 01:50:54.080
jealous rivals.

01:50:51.280 --> 01:50:57.280
While the Persian ambassador Abdur Razzak

01:50:54.080 --> 01:51:00.080
was staying in the city, Devaraya II was

01:50:57.280 --> 01:51:02.639
the target of one particularly dramatic

01:51:00.080 --> 01:51:05.360
and audacious assassination attempt by

01:51:02.639 --> 01:51:09.920
one of his brothers, which shows just how

01:51:05.360 --> 01:51:09.920
dangerous the life of a king could be.

01:51:13.599 --> 01:51:18.639
This brother of King Devaraya plotted to

01:51:16.320 --> 01:51:20.400
first slaughter all the high-ranking

01:51:18.639 --> 01:51:22.320
officials in his government

01:51:20.400 --> 01:51:26.080
before finally heading to the royal

01:51:22.320 --> 01:51:28.320
chambers and killing the king himself.

01:51:26.080 --> 01:51:33.599
The first part of the plan went off

01:51:28.320 --> 01:51:36.159
without a hitch, as Abdur Razzak writes.

01:51:33.599 --> 01:51:38.239
The king's brother, who had had a new

01:51:36.159 --> 01:51:40.480
house built for himself,

01:51:38.239 --> 01:51:43.280
invited thither the monarch and the

01:51:40.480 --> 01:51:45.760
principal personages of the empire. At

01:51:43.280 --> 01:51:48.800
short intervals, the prince either came

01:51:45.760 --> 01:51:51.280
in person or sent some messengers to say

01:51:48.800 --> 01:51:53.360
that such-and-such great personage

01:51:51.280 --> 01:51:54.719
should come and eat his part of the

01:51:53.360 --> 01:51:57.040
banquet.

01:51:54.719 --> 01:52:00.320
Care had been taken to bring together

01:51:57.040 --> 01:52:02.400
all the drums, kettle drums, trumpets, and

01:52:00.320 --> 01:52:04.719
flutes that could be found in the city,

01:52:02.400 --> 01:52:08.239
and these instruments playing all at the

01:52:04.719 --> 01:52:10.400
same time made a tremendous uproar.

01:52:08.239 --> 01:52:12.719
As soon as the individual who had been

01:52:10.400 --> 01:52:15.679
sent for entered the above-mentioned

01:52:12.719 --> 01:52:17.760
house, two assassins placed in ambush

01:52:15.679 --> 01:52:20.400
sprang out upon him, pierced him with a

01:52:17.760 --> 01:52:22.800
dagger, and cut him to pieces. In

01:52:20.400 --> 01:52:25.599
consequence of the noise of the drums,

01:52:22.800 --> 01:52:28.159
the clamour, and the tumult, no one, with

01:52:25.599 --> 01:52:31.280
the exception of a small number to whom

01:52:28.159 --> 01:52:33.040
the secret was entrusted, was aware of

01:52:31.280 --> 01:52:35.760
what was going on.

01:52:33.040 --> 01:52:37.920
In this manner, all those who had any

01:52:35.760 --> 01:52:40.480
name or rank in the state were

01:52:37.920 --> 01:52:40.480
slaughtered.

01:52:42.000 --> 01:52:46.320
Once his grisly work was done, the

01:52:44.320 --> 01:52:49.119
treacherous brother went to the king's

01:52:46.320 --> 01:52:50.400
quarters to strike the final blow of his

01:52:49.119 --> 01:52:52.239
coup.

01:52:50.400 --> 01:52:54.800
He entered the royal chamber with a

01:52:52.239 --> 01:52:56.239
plate of betel nuts and leaves for the

01:52:54.800 --> 01:52:58.080
king to chew,

01:52:56.239 --> 01:53:00.480
but beneath these leaves he had

01:52:58.080 --> 01:53:02.320
concealed a hidden blade.

01:53:00.480 --> 01:53:04.239
Coming close to the king, the brother

01:53:02.320 --> 01:53:07.599
told him that the court was ready for

01:53:04.239 --> 01:53:09.760
him, and offered him some of the betel.

01:53:07.599 --> 01:53:12.000
But perhaps the king had detected

01:53:09.760 --> 01:53:13.679
something strange in the way his brother

01:53:12.000 --> 01:53:16.080
stepped towards him.

01:53:13.679 --> 01:53:18.000
He declined, saying that he didn't feel

01:53:16.080 --> 01:53:21.360
well that day.

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:23.840
Abdur Razzak recalls what happened next

01:53:21.360 --> 01:53:26.000
as the treacherous brother lost his

01:53:23.840 --> 01:53:28.880
patience.

01:53:26.000 --> 01:53:31.440
This unnatural brother, thus losing the

01:53:28.880 --> 01:53:34.080
hope of enticing the king to his house,

01:53:31.440 --> 01:53:37.599
drew his poniard and struck him there

01:53:34.080 --> 01:53:41.040
with several violent blows so that the

01:53:37.599 --> 01:53:43.520
prince fell at the back of his throne.

01:53:41.040 --> 01:53:45.760
The traitor, thus believing that the king

01:53:43.520 --> 01:53:48.639
was dead, left there one of his

01:53:45.760 --> 01:53:51.360
confidants to cut off the monarch's head.

01:53:48.639 --> 01:53:53.520
Then, going out of the hall, he ascended

01:53:51.360 --> 01:53:56.639
to the portico of the palace and thus

01:53:53.520 --> 01:53:57.760
addressed the people; I have slain the

01:53:56.639 --> 01:54:01.119
king.

01:53:57.760 --> 01:54:03.840
His brothers and such-and-such emirs,

01:54:01.119 --> 01:54:04.800
Brahmins, and viziers,

01:54:03.840 --> 01:54:07.360
now

01:54:04.800 --> 01:54:10.080
I am king.

01:54:07.360 --> 01:54:12.080
But he had not counted on the king's

01:54:10.080 --> 01:54:14.239
resilience.

01:54:12.080 --> 01:54:16.800
As the treacherous brother’s accomplice

01:54:14.239 --> 01:54:19.760
approached King Devaraya to decapitate

01:54:16.800 --> 01:54:22.000
him, the king fought back in dramatic

01:54:19.760 --> 01:54:24.880
fashion.

01:54:22.000 --> 01:54:27.040
Meanwhile, his emissary had approached

01:54:24.880 --> 01:54:30.000
the throne with the intention of cutting

01:54:27.040 --> 01:54:32.480
off the king's head, but that prince,

01:54:30.000 --> 01:54:35.520
seizing the seat behind which he had

01:54:32.480 --> 01:54:38.239
fallen, struck the wretch with it with so

01:54:35.520 --> 01:54:41.040
much violence on the chest that he fell

01:54:38.239 --> 01:54:43.679
upon his back. The king then, with the

01:54:41.040 --> 01:54:46.159
help of one of his guards, slew this

01:54:43.679 --> 01:54:48.159
assassin and went out of the palace by

01:54:46.159 --> 01:54:50.560
the way of the harem.

01:54:48.159 --> 01:54:53.440
His brother, still standing on the top of

01:54:50.560 --> 01:54:56.639
the steps of the hall of council, invited

01:54:53.440 --> 01:54:57.840
the multitude to recognize him as their

01:54:56.639 --> 01:55:00.400
king.

01:54:57.840 --> 01:55:05.199
At that moment, the monarch cried out,

01:55:00.400 --> 01:55:06.480
I am alive! I am well and safe! Seize that

01:55:05.199 --> 01:55:09.360
wretch.

01:55:06.480 --> 01:55:11.760
The whole crowd assembled together, threw

01:55:09.360 --> 01:55:14.719
themselves upon the guilty prince, and

01:55:11.760 --> 01:55:14.719
put him to death.

01:55:16.080 --> 01:55:21.199
This dramatic episode gives us a sense

01:55:18.880 --> 01:55:25.520
of the life-and-death stakes that the

01:55:21.199 --> 01:55:28.239
emperors of Vijayanagara faced every day.

01:55:25.520 --> 01:55:33.320
The kings who followed Devaraya II

01:55:28.239 --> 01:55:33.320
were not always as lucky as he was.

01:55:39.840 --> 01:55:46.080
The great King Devaraya finally died in

01:55:43.040 --> 01:55:49.280
the year 1446.

01:55:46.080 --> 01:55:51.520
His reign had been a golden age;

01:55:49.280 --> 01:55:54.159
he had left his kingdom a larger,

01:55:51.520 --> 01:55:56.480
wealthier, and more outward-looking place

01:55:54.159 --> 01:55:59.040
than he had found it, but the period that

01:55:56.480 --> 01:56:01.920
followed was one of chaos and

01:55:59.040 --> 01:56:03.520
dissolution in the empire.

01:56:01.920 --> 01:56:06.480
Devaraya’s son

01:56:03.520 --> 01:56:09.119
is said quite mysteriously to have died

01:56:06.480 --> 01:56:11.199
of a broken heart, which is perhaps a

01:56:09.119 --> 01:56:13.920
euphemism for poison.

01:56:11.199 --> 01:56:17.440
His grandson took the throne, but would

01:56:13.920 --> 01:56:20.000
go on to be murdered by his own son.

01:56:17.440 --> 01:56:22.239
In a Shakespearean turn, this

01:56:20.000 --> 01:56:24.719
great-grandson of Devaraya was

01:56:22.239 --> 01:56:27.199
apparently horrified by what he had done,

01:56:24.719 --> 01:56:29.280
and refused to take up the throne he had

01:56:27.199 --> 01:56:31.119
murdered his father for.

01:56:29.280 --> 01:56:33.599
He passed it on to one of his younger

01:56:31.119 --> 01:56:35.360
brothers, who quickly had him put to

01:56:33.599 --> 01:56:38.880
death.

01:56:35.360 --> 01:56:42.159
As blood ran in torrents from the throne,

01:56:38.880 --> 01:56:44.560
chaos began to engulf the empire, and

01:56:42.159 --> 01:56:48.320
soon, the commanders of the military

01:56:44.560 --> 01:56:50.480
began to hunger for power themselves.

01:56:48.320 --> 01:56:54.159
One of these was a powerful general

01:56:50.480 --> 01:56:57.760
named Saluva Narasimha, a name that means

01:56:54.159 --> 01:56:58.800
‘man-lion’. This general was a colorful

01:56:57.760 --> 01:57:02.159
character,

01:56:58.800 --> 01:57:03.760
a poet, and a self-styled expert in

01:57:02.159 --> 01:57:04.760
lovemaking.

01:57:03.760 --> 01:57:08.159
In the year

01:57:04.760 --> 01:57:11.520
1485, he seized the throne in a military

01:57:08.159 --> 01:57:14.880
coup and ended the Sangama Dynasty that

01:57:11.520 --> 01:57:17.920
had ruled for 150 years since the first

01:57:14.880 --> 01:57:20.480
days of Vijayanagara and the two Sangama

01:57:17.920 --> 01:57:22.800
brothers, Bukka and Harihara, who had

01:57:20.480 --> 01:57:26.000
founded it.

01:57:22.800 --> 01:57:28.239
The libidinous general Saluva Narasimha

01:57:26.000 --> 01:57:31.599
didn't seem to care much for the boring

01:57:28.239 --> 01:57:33.760
business of actually ruling his kingdom.

01:57:31.599 --> 01:57:36.840
He spent much of his time apparently

01:57:33.760 --> 01:57:40.080
writing a long book of detailed erotic

01:57:36.840 --> 01:57:42.639
instruction, but he died only a few years

01:57:40.080 --> 01:57:45.199
after taking the throne.

01:57:42.639 --> 01:57:47.840
It's during this period of chaos and the

01:57:45.199 --> 01:57:51.040
reign of the hapless kings that followed

01:57:47.840 --> 01:57:53.440
that in the year 1498, the first

01:57:51.040 --> 01:57:56.560
Portuguese ship, captained by the

01:57:53.440 --> 01:57:59.360
explorer Vasco de Gama, arrived in South

01:57:56.560 --> 01:58:02.080
India, having sailed all the way around

01:57:59.360 --> 01:58:04.560
the coast of Africa.

01:58:02.080 --> 01:58:07.440
He would be the first European captain

01:58:04.560 --> 01:58:09.040
to ever do so, but he would be followed

01:58:07.440 --> 01:58:10.960
by many others.

01:58:09.040 --> 01:58:13.760
The Portuguese would soon set up a

01:58:10.960 --> 01:58:16.239
trading post at Goa on India's west

01:58:13.760 --> 01:58:18.719
coast, and in the coming centuries,

01:58:16.239 --> 01:58:22.159
European powers would increase their

01:58:18.719 --> 01:58:24.239
presence and influence in India.

01:58:22.159 --> 01:58:26.880
But at the time, the appearance of these

01:58:24.239 --> 01:58:30.800
foreigners excited little attention in

01:58:26.880 --> 01:58:30.800
the court of Vijayanagara.

01:58:31.199 --> 01:58:36.400
This time of chaos and upheaval in the

01:58:34.080 --> 01:58:38.800
empire would only come to an end with

01:58:36.400 --> 01:58:41.280
the reign of a man who would come to be

01:58:38.800 --> 01:58:43.599
known as one of the greatest and

01:58:41.280 --> 01:58:46.320
certainly the most famous of the

01:58:43.599 --> 01:58:49.840
emperors of South India.

01:58:46.320 --> 01:58:54.599
He was a man named Krishnadeva Raya,

01:58:49.840 --> 01:58:54.599
the last great king of Vijayanagara.

01:59:05.280 --> 01:59:09.599
Krishnadeva was never meant to be the

01:59:08.320 --> 01:59:12.000
king.

01:59:09.599 --> 01:59:14.320
He was a prince, but his mother was a

01:59:12.000 --> 01:59:15.679
lower-ranking woman than any of his

01:59:14.320 --> 01:59:18.880
other brothers,

01:59:15.679 --> 01:59:21.520
and so, his older brothers Immadi and

01:59:18.880 --> 01:59:23.360
Viranarasimha each took a turn at the throne

01:59:21.520 --> 01:59:26.080
before he did.

01:59:23.360 --> 01:59:29.040
But they catastrophically mismanaged the

01:59:26.080 --> 01:59:31.199
kingdom and faced constant rebellions

01:59:29.040 --> 01:59:34.000
and uprisings.

01:59:31.199 --> 01:59:36.719
When Krishnadeva's older brother finally

01:59:34.000 --> 01:59:39.360
lay on his deathbed, he was determined

01:59:36.719 --> 01:59:41.920
that his own infant grandson should take

01:59:39.360 --> 01:59:45.599
the throne, but he knew that many of the

01:59:41.920 --> 01:59:48.639
lords backed his brother Krishnadeva.

01:59:45.599 --> 01:59:50.960
In a final dying wish, he ordered that

01:59:48.639 --> 01:59:53.360
his brother should be blinded,

01:59:50.960 --> 01:59:55.920
which under Indian law would mean he

01:59:53.360 --> 01:59:58.719
could not become king.

01:59:55.920 --> 02:00:01.520
According to legend, the king's servants

01:59:58.719 --> 02:00:03.920
had no confidence in his baby son

02:00:01.520 --> 02:00:07.040
actually taking the throne, but they were

02:00:03.920 --> 02:00:09.199
still afraid to anger the dying king.

02:00:07.040 --> 02:00:11.840
In a daring move, they brought him the

02:00:09.199 --> 02:00:14.639
eyes of a recently slaughtered goat,

02:00:11.840 --> 02:00:17.520
still dripping with blood, and told him

02:00:14.639 --> 02:00:20.560
that his wishes had been carried out.

02:00:17.520 --> 02:00:23.679
The king died satisfied that his line

02:00:20.560 --> 02:00:27.159
was secure, and Krishnadeva effortlessly

02:00:23.679 --> 02:00:27.159
took the throne.

02:00:27.760 --> 02:00:32.800
The Portuguese traveller Domingo Paes

02:00:30.719 --> 02:00:36.800
gives the following account of the

02:00:32.800 --> 02:00:36.800
appearance of King Krishnadeva.

02:00:37.280 --> 02:00:41.599
The king is of medium height and a fair

02:00:39.520 --> 02:00:43.440
complexion and good figure,

02:00:41.599 --> 02:00:46.400
rather fat than thin.

02:00:43.440 --> 02:00:48.239
He has on his face signs of smallpox.

02:00:46.400 --> 02:00:50.000
He is the most feared and perfect king

02:00:48.239 --> 02:00:53.040
that could possibly be,

02:00:50.000 --> 02:00:54.719
cheerful of disposition and very merry.

02:00:53.040 --> 02:00:56.960
He is one that seeks to honor foreigners

02:00:54.719 --> 02:00:58.800
and receives them kindly, asking about

02:00:56.960 --> 02:01:00.480
all their affairs, whatever their

02:00:58.800 --> 02:01:02.400
condition may be.

02:01:00.480 --> 02:01:03.440
He is a great ruler and a man of much

02:01:02.400 --> 02:01:05.920
justice,

02:01:03.440 --> 02:01:07.599
but subject to certain fits of rage,

02:01:05.920 --> 02:01:10.080
and this is his title;

02:01:07.599 --> 02:01:12.639
king of kings, lord of great lords of

02:01:10.080 --> 02:01:14.960
India, lord of the three seas and of the

02:01:12.639 --> 02:01:14.960
land.

02:01:15.599 --> 02:01:22.000
Krishna Devaraya was also what we might

02:01:18.639 --> 02:01:24.320
think of today as a fitness fanatic.

02:01:22.000 --> 02:01:28.080
Domingo Paes writes the following

02:01:24.320 --> 02:01:29.920
account of his daily routine.

02:01:28.080 --> 02:01:32.159
The king is accustomed every day to

02:01:29.920 --> 02:01:34.560
drink a three-quarter pint of sesame oil

02:01:32.159 --> 02:01:36.400
before daylight, and anoints himself all

02:01:34.560 --> 02:01:38.560
over with the same oil.

02:01:36.400 --> 02:01:40.400
He covers his loins with a small cloth

02:01:38.560 --> 02:01:42.719
and takes in his arms great weights made

02:01:40.400 --> 02:01:45.360
of earthenware, and then,

02:01:42.719 --> 02:01:47.360
taking a sword, he exercises himself

02:01:45.360 --> 02:01:49.440
with it ‘til has sweated out all the

02:01:47.360 --> 02:01:50.719
oil, and then he wrestles with one of his

02:01:49.440 --> 02:01:52.960
wrestlers.

02:01:50.719 --> 02:01:55.040
After this labor, he mounts a horse and

02:01:52.960 --> 02:01:56.800
gallops about the plain in one direction

02:01:55.040 --> 02:02:01.400
and another ‘til dawn, for

02:01:56.800 --> 02:02:01.400
he does all this before daybreak.

02:02:07.920 --> 02:02:13.679
Krishnadeva showed a similar

02:02:10.480 --> 02:02:16.159
energetic attitude to his rule.

02:02:13.679 --> 02:02:18.880
One of his first acts was to embark on a

02:02:16.159 --> 02:02:21.679
campaign against the troublesome Lord of

02:02:18.880 --> 02:02:23.280
Elephants, the king of the Gajapatis

02:02:21.679 --> 02:02:25.599
in the east.

02:02:23.280 --> 02:02:28.800
He marched his armies into that humid

02:02:25.599 --> 02:02:30.560
forest region and seized important forts

02:02:28.800 --> 02:02:33.119
along the way.

02:02:30.560 --> 02:02:35.199
King Krishnadeva was a poet,

02:02:33.119 --> 02:02:36.719
and he wrote the following words in his

02:02:35.199 --> 02:02:39.679
epic poem Aamuktamaalyada

02:02:36.719 --> 02:02:43.280
about his campaign against the

02:02:39.679 --> 02:02:43.280
Gajapatis in the east.

02:02:43.440 --> 02:02:48.719
In the Blue Hills of Puri, under the

02:02:45.920 --> 02:02:51.199
protective gaze of blue-robed Balram and

02:02:48.719 --> 02:02:54.480
lord Krishna, whose eyes are like blue

02:02:51.199 --> 02:02:56.400
water lilies, I prepared for battle and

02:02:54.480 --> 02:02:59.280
struck fear into the Gajapatis’

02:02:56.400 --> 02:03:02.239
heart with my powerful arms pounding the

02:02:59.280 --> 02:03:02.239
drums of war.

02:03:03.040 --> 02:03:07.920
The Gajapatis king eventually

02:03:05.199 --> 02:03:10.639
surrendered, and in a classic example of

02:03:07.920 --> 02:03:12.320
conflict resolution in this period, he

02:03:10.639 --> 02:03:15.040
offered his daughter in marriage to

02:03:12.320 --> 02:03:18.000
Krishnadeva, who returned all the coastal

02:03:15.040 --> 02:03:19.520
territory back to the now humbled

02:03:18.000 --> 02:03:21.840
Gajapatis.

02:03:19.520 --> 02:03:24.880
This victory must have boosted his

02:03:21.840 --> 02:03:27.599
reputation at home and fed what was

02:03:24.880 --> 02:03:30.320
apparently an enormous ego.

02:03:27.599 --> 02:03:33.840
Krishna Devaraya's royal inscriptions

02:03:30.320 --> 02:03:33.840
gush with self-praise.

02:03:34.480 --> 02:03:40.719
Overcome by his glory, the sun sinks into

02:03:37.920 --> 02:03:43.119
the western ocean as if quite unable to

02:03:40.719 --> 02:03:45.040
endure the distress of mine.

02:03:43.119 --> 02:03:47.840
As if fearing that the seven oceans

02:03:45.040 --> 02:03:50.480
would provide a refuge to his enemies,

02:03:47.840 --> 02:03:53.119
they were dried up by the clouds of dust

02:03:50.480 --> 02:03:56.239
raised by the earth, trampled to pieces

02:03:53.119 --> 02:03:58.960
by his horsemen.

02:03:56.239 --> 02:04:01.040
But Krishnadeva was also an eminently

02:03:58.960 --> 02:04:03.280
practical man.

02:04:01.040 --> 02:04:06.320
He published a series of political

02:04:03.280 --> 02:04:08.719
maxims that contained advice for how a

02:04:06.320 --> 02:04:11.360
kingdom should be ruled, how it should

02:04:08.719 --> 02:04:14.239
operate efficiently and secure its

02:04:11.360 --> 02:04:18.480
access to resources, as the following

02:04:14.239 --> 02:04:18.480
example written by him shows.

02:04:18.639 --> 02:04:23.679
A king should improve the harvest of his

02:04:20.960 --> 02:04:26.960
country, and so encourage its commoners

02:04:23.679 --> 02:04:29.679
that horses, elephants, precious gems,

02:04:26.960 --> 02:04:32.719
sandalwood, pearls, and other articles are

02:04:29.679 --> 02:04:32.719
freely imported.

02:04:32.960 --> 02:04:38.719
Under King Krishnadeva, the Vijayanagara

02:04:35.760 --> 02:04:42.239
Empire nearly doubled in size and would

02:04:38.719 --> 02:04:44.639
soon reach its largest historical extent,

02:04:42.239 --> 02:04:46.520
and it would also achieve its greatest

02:04:44.639 --> 02:04:48.480
degree of centralization.

02:04:48.480 --> 02:04:54.079
At heart, it was still a feudal society,

02:04:51.520 --> 02:04:56.239
and its regions were ruled by lords

02:04:54.079 --> 02:04:59.360
known as nayakas.

02:04:56.239 --> 02:05:01.440
These nayakas paid taxes to the empire

02:04:59.360 --> 02:05:02.800
but otherwise enjoyed a degree of

02:05:01.440 --> 02:05:06.079
independence,

02:05:02.800 --> 02:05:07.010
as the Portuguese visitor Domingo Paes

02:05:06.079 --> 02:05:09.199
recalls.

02:05:09.199 --> 02:05:12.719
These captains who he has over these

02:05:10.800 --> 02:05:13.679
troops of his are the nobles of his

02:05:12.719 --> 02:05:15.599
kingdom.

02:05:13.679 --> 02:05:17.840
They are lords and they hold the city and

02:05:15.599 --> 02:05:19.520
the towns and villages of the kingdom.

02:05:17.840 --> 02:05:21.679
There are captains amongst them who have

02:05:19.520 --> 02:05:23.599
a revenue of a million and a million a

02:05:21.679 --> 02:05:26.000
half of pardaos,

02:05:23.599 --> 02:05:27.599
others a hundred thousand pardaos,

02:05:26.000 --> 02:05:32.000
others 200,

02:05:27.599 --> 02:05:34.480
300, or 500,000 pardaos.

02:05:32.000 --> 02:05:36.480
As each one has revenue,

02:05:34.480 --> 02:05:38.159
so the king fixes for him the number of

02:05:36.480 --> 02:05:39.280
troops he must maintain

02:05:38.159 --> 02:05:40.159
in foot,

02:05:39.280 --> 02:05:41.679
horse,

02:05:40.159 --> 02:05:44.400
and elephants.

02:05:41.679 --> 02:05:46.560
These troops are always ready for duty

02:05:44.400 --> 02:05:47.440
whenever they may be called out,

02:05:46.560 --> 02:05:49.520
and

02:05:47.440 --> 02:05:51.679
wherever they may have to go.

02:05:49.520 --> 02:05:53.760
Besides maintaining these troops, each

02:05:51.679 --> 02:05:56.239
captain has to make his annual payments

02:05:53.760 --> 02:05:56.239
to the king.

02:05:56.560 --> 02:06:00.880
Krishna Devaraya was also a great

02:05:59.199 --> 02:06:04.239
builder.

02:06:00.880 --> 02:06:06.560
To mark his coming to the throne, in 1510

02:06:04.239 --> 02:06:10.000
he ordered the construction of a grand

02:06:06.560 --> 02:06:12.159
gateway tower known as a gopura to adorn

02:06:10.000 --> 02:06:14.400
the temple to Virupaksha,

02:06:12.159 --> 02:06:16.880
as well as a central pillared hall

02:06:14.400 --> 02:06:19.440
covered in ornate carvings.

02:06:16.880 --> 02:06:21.440
This remarkable temple tower was

02:06:19.440 --> 02:06:24.719
designed based on mathematical

02:06:21.440 --> 02:06:27.280
principles using a fractal design in

02:06:24.719 --> 02:06:28.960
which small parts of the tower resemble

02:06:27.280 --> 02:06:32.239
the whole.

02:06:28.960 --> 02:06:34.400
This gives the tower a mesmerizing shape

02:06:32.239 --> 02:06:37.520
and represents the infinite repetition

02:06:34.400 --> 02:06:39.520
of universes that lies at the heart of

02:06:37.520 --> 02:06:41.679
Hindu cosmology,

02:06:39.520 --> 02:06:44.480
as the scholar William J. Jackson

02:06:41.679 --> 02:06:46.320
describes.

02:06:44.480 --> 02:06:48.320
The ideal form,

02:06:46.320 --> 02:06:51.679
gracefully artificed,

02:06:48.320 --> 02:06:54.079
suggests the infinite rising levels of

02:06:51.679 --> 02:06:57.040
existence and consciousness,

02:06:54.079 --> 02:06:59.360
expanding sizes rising towards

02:06:57.040 --> 02:07:02.480
transcendence above,

02:06:59.360 --> 02:07:03.670
and at the same time, housing the sacred

02:07:02.480 --> 02:07:08.239
deep within.

02:07:08.239 --> 02:07:13.360
For the nearby Vittala temple, Krishna

02:07:10.880 --> 02:07:16.079
Devaraya also commissioned a striking

02:07:13.360 --> 02:07:17.840
piece of art to be carved out of several

02:07:16.079 --> 02:07:21.440
blocks of granite.

02:07:17.840 --> 02:07:23.599
It was a temple chariot made of stone,

02:07:21.440 --> 02:07:24.960
complete with wheels and ornate

02:07:23.599 --> 02:07:27.440
decorations

02:07:24.960 --> 02:07:31.840
which can still be seen in the courtyard

02:07:27.440 --> 02:07:34.400
of the Vittala temple in Hampi today.

02:07:31.840 --> 02:07:35.360
This was a true golden age in South

02:07:34.400 --> 02:07:38.880
India,

02:07:35.360 --> 02:07:42.320
a time of peace, stability, and prosperity,

02:07:38.880 --> 02:07:44.800
but this period of calm would not last.

02:07:42.320 --> 02:07:48.079
In fact, Krishna Devaraya would be the

02:07:44.800 --> 02:07:50.719
last great king of Vijayanagara.

02:07:48.079 --> 02:07:54.239
In little more than 50 years,

02:07:50.719 --> 02:07:58.000
this vast city would be destroyed, its

02:07:54.239 --> 02:08:01.360
temples and palaces burned, its streets

02:07:58.000 --> 02:08:03.840
emptied of people, and its houses left to

02:08:01.360 --> 02:08:06.239
crumble into the earth.

02:08:03.840 --> 02:08:09.920
The beginning of the downfall of

02:08:06.239 --> 02:08:12.400
Vijayanagara began with an event that to

02:08:09.920 --> 02:08:14.880
its people must have felt like a

02:08:12.400 --> 02:08:17.760
fantastic development.

02:08:14.880 --> 02:08:20.320
That's the fragmentation and collapse of

02:08:17.760 --> 02:08:24.639
their long-standing rival to the north,

02:08:20.320 --> 02:08:24.639
the Muslim Bahmani Sultanate.

02:08:29.199 --> 02:08:35.280
Like the empire of Vijayanagara, the

02:08:32.400 --> 02:08:38.400
Bahmani Sultanate had been successful

02:08:35.280 --> 02:08:40.440
by combining disparate elements.

02:08:38.400 --> 02:08:43.119
For decades, they had been

02:08:40.440 --> 02:08:45.119
enthusiastically importing people from

02:08:43.119 --> 02:08:49.119
across the Muslim world;

02:08:45.119 --> 02:08:52.320
soldiers, architects, artists, holy men, and

02:08:49.119 --> 02:08:55.440
scholars, and these people had helped to

02:08:52.320 --> 02:08:57.760
transform it into a world center of

02:08:55.440 --> 02:09:01.440
culture and innovation.

02:08:57.760 --> 02:09:04.480
But this policy also had its costs.

02:09:01.440 --> 02:09:07.840
Soon, conflicts began to unfold between

02:09:04.480 --> 02:09:11.119
the Indian Bahmanis and the newcomers,

02:09:07.840 --> 02:09:14.400
mostly Persian-speaking Iranians who

02:09:11.119 --> 02:09:17.040
were referred to as the Westerners.

02:09:14.400 --> 02:09:19.280
Throughout the 15th century, the Indian

02:09:17.040 --> 02:09:21.760
Muslims in the sultanate became

02:09:19.280 --> 02:09:24.560
increasingly angry at the growing

02:09:21.760 --> 02:09:27.760
influence of these foreign arrivals, and

02:09:24.560 --> 02:09:30.159
as the 16th century neared, their anger

02:09:27.760 --> 02:09:33.360
turned mutinous.

02:09:30.159 --> 02:09:36.079
When the enraged ruler of Ahmednagar

02:09:33.360 --> 02:09:38.560
rebelled in the year 1490,

02:09:36.079 --> 02:09:39.920
the other regions of the sultanate soon

02:09:38.560 --> 02:09:42.639
followed.

02:09:39.920 --> 02:09:46.159
By the time Krishna Devaraya came to the

02:09:42.639 --> 02:09:48.560
throne of Vijayanagara in the year 1509,

02:09:46.159 --> 02:09:50.480
the Bahmani Sultanate was already

02:09:48.560 --> 02:09:54.000
splintering.

02:09:50.480 --> 02:09:57.280
By the year 1518, it had fractured into

02:09:54.000 --> 02:09:59.280
five individual kingdoms, whose sultans

02:09:57.280 --> 02:10:03.199
immediately began fighting amongst

02:09:59.280 --> 02:10:06.480
themselves over small pieces of land.

02:10:03.199 --> 02:10:09.760
The power of the Bahmanis evaporated in

02:10:06.480 --> 02:10:12.000
just a matter of years, and Vijayanagara

02:10:09.760 --> 02:10:14.880
was now all but unchallenged in the

02:10:12.000 --> 02:10:17.520
south of India.

02:10:14.880 --> 02:10:20.800
For King Krishna Devaraya, still only a

02:10:17.520 --> 02:10:22.639
young man of 17 years old and still

02:10:20.800 --> 02:10:25.040
buzzing from his victory against the

02:10:22.639 --> 02:10:27.280
Gajapatis, the chaos in these

02:10:25.040 --> 02:10:29.920
neighboring kingdoms presented an

02:10:27.280 --> 02:10:32.960
obvious opportunity.

02:10:29.920 --> 02:10:36.239
That rich triangle of land known as the

02:10:32.960 --> 02:10:38.719
Raichur Doab, with its fertile farmland

02:10:36.239 --> 02:10:42.079
and wealth of diamonds, had been in the

02:10:38.719 --> 02:10:44.159
hands of the Bahmanis for many years now.

02:10:42.079 --> 02:10:46.960
But with the collapse of the sultanate,

02:10:44.159 --> 02:10:48.560
it was now held by just one of these

02:10:46.960 --> 02:10:51.840
five sultans,

02:10:48.560 --> 02:10:55.040
a man named Ismail Adil Shah,

02:10:51.840 --> 02:10:57.679
the sultan of Bijapur.

02:10:55.040 --> 02:11:02.079
Alone, he would be no match for the might

02:10:57.679 --> 02:11:04.800
of Vijayanagara, and so, in the year 1520,

02:11:02.079 --> 02:11:07.360
King Krishnadeva moved to take it from

02:11:04.800 --> 02:11:10.360
him with an army of a hundred thousand

02:11:07.360 --> 02:11:10.360
soldiers.

02:11:14.079 --> 02:11:20.239
The Portuguese-Jewish traveler Fernao

02:11:17.119 --> 02:11:22.719
Nuniz was staying in Vijayanagara at the

02:11:20.239 --> 02:11:26.000
time of this campaign, and he wrote a

02:11:22.719 --> 02:11:28.320
dramatic and colorful account of how it

02:11:26.000 --> 02:11:30.800
unfolded.

02:11:28.320 --> 02:11:34.480
After the king had made his offerings

02:11:30.800 --> 02:11:37.440
and performed sacrifices to his idols,

02:11:34.480 --> 02:11:38.480
he left the city of Bisnaga with all his

02:11:37.440 --> 02:11:41.679
troops,

02:11:38.480 --> 02:11:44.320
and they marched in the following order.

02:11:41.679 --> 02:11:46.960
The chief of the guard led the advance

02:11:44.320 --> 02:11:50.480
with 30,000 infantry;

02:11:46.960 --> 02:11:54.079
archers, men and shields, and musketeers,

02:11:50.480 --> 02:11:55.840
and spear-men, and a thousand horse and

02:11:54.079 --> 02:11:58.480
his elephants.

02:11:55.840 --> 02:12:00.719
All were equally well-armed,

02:11:58.480 --> 02:12:02.960
each after his own fashion;

02:12:00.719 --> 02:12:06.320
the archers and musketeers with their

02:12:02.960 --> 02:12:08.159
quilted tunics, and the shield-men with

02:12:06.320 --> 02:12:10.480
their swords and daggers in their

02:12:08.159 --> 02:12:12.320
girdles.

02:12:10.480 --> 02:12:14.880
In the days that followed, King

02:12:12.320 --> 02:12:17.599
Krishnadeva marched this large army

02:12:14.880 --> 02:12:21.520
across the Tungabhadra River, and laid

02:12:17.599 --> 02:12:23.920
siege to the fort of Raichur.

02:12:21.520 --> 02:12:25.840
But this would not be as easy as

02:12:23.920 --> 02:12:28.560
Krishnadeva hoped.

02:12:25.840 --> 02:12:30.639
The kings of Vijayanagara had still not

02:12:28.560 --> 02:12:32.800
taken advantage of the developing

02:12:30.639 --> 02:12:34.800
technology of the cannon, although they

02:12:32.800 --> 02:12:37.679
had employed several Portuguese

02:12:34.800 --> 02:12:40.800
musketeers as mercenaries.

02:12:37.679 --> 02:12:43.280
Raichur Fort was a powerful fortress

02:12:40.800 --> 02:12:45.360
perched on top of a rocky hilltop, and

02:12:43.280 --> 02:12:47.760
without effective siege equipment, the

02:12:45.360 --> 02:12:50.639
Hindus resorted to old old-fashioned

02:12:47.760 --> 02:12:53.040
tactics, hacking away at the fort walls

02:12:50.639 --> 02:12:55.520
with pickaxes and hammers.

02:12:53.040 --> 02:12:58.320
The defenders meanwhile were well-

02:12:55.520 --> 02:13:01.040
-stocked with cannons and rained down

02:12:58.320 --> 02:13:03.840
fire from the walls.

02:13:01.040 --> 02:13:05.920
These cannons did have one weakness;

02:13:03.840 --> 02:13:08.560
they were unable to fire directly

02:13:05.920 --> 02:13:11.119
downwards at the men with their pickaxes

02:13:08.560 --> 02:13:13.760
hacking away at the masonry beneath.

02:13:11.119 --> 02:13:16.800
Still, they dealt a terrible toll on the

02:13:13.760 --> 02:13:18.560
besieging soldiers as they approached.

02:13:16.800 --> 02:13:21.440
The siege looked like it would last

02:13:18.560 --> 02:13:24.079
forever, but then one morning, Krishnadeva

02:13:21.440 --> 02:13:27.040
got word that the sultan of Bijapur

02:13:24.079 --> 02:13:31.000
himself was marching south towards him

02:13:27.040 --> 02:13:31.000
at the head of an army.

02:13:33.119 --> 02:13:38.639
This army was made up of his best crack

02:13:36.159 --> 02:13:41.679
troops, equipped with nearly a thousand

02:13:38.639 --> 02:13:43.360
of the latest powerful cannons imported

02:13:41.679 --> 02:13:45.679
from Persia.

02:13:43.360 --> 02:13:48.079
Perhaps feeling just a tremble of

02:13:45.679 --> 02:13:51.119
apprehension, Krishnadeva lifted the

02:13:48.079 --> 02:13:52.639
siege and went out to meet the sultan in

02:13:51.119 --> 02:13:55.599
battle.

02:13:52.639 --> 02:13:58.079
Fernao Nuniz, who witnessed these two

02:13:55.599 --> 02:14:00.880
armies come together, describes in

02:13:58.079 --> 02:14:03.760
visceral terms the noise they made as

02:14:00.880 --> 02:14:06.719
they prepared to fight.

02:14:03.760 --> 02:14:08.960
Seeing that dawn was now breaking, the

02:14:06.719 --> 02:14:11.440
drums and trumpets and other music in

02:14:08.960 --> 02:14:13.199
the king's camp began to sound and the

02:14:11.440 --> 02:14:15.440
men to shout

02:14:13.199 --> 02:14:17.280
so that it seemed as if the sky would

02:14:15.440 --> 02:14:19.119
fall to the earth,

02:14:17.280 --> 02:14:21.199
then the neighing and excitement of the

02:14:19.119 --> 02:14:22.400
horses and the trumpeting of the

02:14:21.199 --> 02:14:25.440
elephants;

02:14:22.400 --> 02:14:26.719
it is impossible for anyone to describe

02:14:25.440 --> 02:14:29.040
how it was.

02:14:26.719 --> 02:14:31.440
It would hardly be believed the great

02:14:29.040 --> 02:14:34.400
fear and terror that struck those who

02:14:31.440 --> 02:14:36.719
heard it, so that even those very men

02:14:34.400 --> 02:14:38.560
that caused the noise were themselves

02:14:36.719 --> 02:14:41.280
frightened at it,

02:14:38.560 --> 02:14:44.639
and the enemy on their part made no less

02:14:41.280 --> 02:14:47.040
noise so that if you asked anything, you

02:14:44.639 --> 02:14:49.199
could not hear yourself speak, and you

02:14:47.040 --> 02:14:50.960
had to ask by signs,

02:14:49.199 --> 02:14:52.840
since in no manner could you make

02:14:50.960 --> 02:14:55.920
yourself

02:14:52.840 --> 02:14:58.639
understood. This encounter, which has come

02:14:55.920 --> 02:15:01.199
to be known as the Battle of Raichur,

02:14:58.639 --> 02:15:04.159
is the perfect embodiment of the chaos

02:15:01.199 --> 02:15:06.239
and violence of a medieval battle.

02:15:04.159 --> 02:15:09.360
Although Vijayanagara had brought the

02:15:06.239 --> 02:15:12.159
larger army, the sultan of Bijapur was

02:15:09.360 --> 02:15:14.639
confident that his superior firepower

02:15:12.159 --> 02:15:16.400
would scatter the Hindus and bring him

02:15:14.639 --> 02:15:18.480
victory.

02:15:16.400 --> 02:15:20.960
When the battle began, he ordered his

02:15:18.480 --> 02:15:25.040
cannoneers to fire all of their guns at

02:15:20.960 --> 02:15:25.040
once in a devastating volley.

02:15:25.199 --> 02:15:30.800
Fernao Nuniz recounts what happened

02:15:27.679 --> 02:15:32.880
next, as a thousand cannonballs tore

02:15:30.800 --> 02:15:34.480
through the ranks of the Vijayanagara

02:15:32.880 --> 02:15:37.280
soldiers.

02:15:34.480 --> 02:15:40.800
He commanded the whole of the artillery

02:15:37.280 --> 02:15:43.840
at once to open fire, which discharged as

02:15:40.800 --> 02:15:47.280
it was very great, did much damage to the

02:15:43.840 --> 02:15:49.119
enemy, killing many of the horse and foot

02:15:47.280 --> 02:15:52.239
and many elephants,

02:15:49.119 --> 02:15:54.400
and it compelled the King Krishnadeva’s

02:15:52.239 --> 02:15:57.199
troops to retire.

02:15:54.400 --> 02:15:59.760
As soon as the Moors saw their enemies

02:15:57.199 --> 02:16:02.000
beginning to leave the field,

02:15:59.760 --> 02:16:04.079
they charged all amongst them,

02:16:02.000 --> 02:16:06.239
slaughtering them for about half a

02:16:04.079 --> 02:16:08.239
league.

02:16:06.239 --> 02:16:09.840
It looked like all was lost for

02:16:08.239 --> 02:16:12.480
Vijayanagara,

02:16:09.840 --> 02:16:13.599
but King Krishnadeva refused to admit

02:16:12.480 --> 02:16:15.599
defeat.

02:16:13.599 --> 02:16:18.560
He rallied his generals and elite

02:16:15.599 --> 02:16:22.400
cavalry around him, and gave a stunning

02:16:18.560 --> 02:16:22.400
and quite ruthless order.

02:16:23.040 --> 02:16:28.639
When the king saw the way in which his

02:16:25.760 --> 02:16:30.320
troops fled, he began to cry that they

02:16:28.639 --> 02:16:33.120
were traitors

02:16:30.320 --> 02:16:35.760
and that he would see who was his side,

02:16:33.120 --> 02:16:38.399
and that since they all had to die,

02:16:35.760 --> 02:16:41.920
they should meet their fate boldly.

02:16:38.399 --> 02:16:44.559
“Who ranges himself with me?” he cried.

02:16:41.920 --> 02:16:46.800
Immediately, there thronged about him

02:16:44.559 --> 02:16:49.040
all those lords and captains that were

02:16:46.800 --> 02:16:51.920
ready to side with him,

02:16:49.040 --> 02:16:54.399
then he took a ring from his finger and

02:16:51.920 --> 02:16:57.040
gave it to one of his pages so that he

02:16:54.399 --> 02:16:58.399
might show it to his queens in token of

02:16:57.040 --> 02:17:00.559
his death.

02:16:58.399 --> 02:17:03.200
Then he mounted a horse and moved

02:17:00.559 --> 02:17:06.639
forward with all his remaining divisions,

02:17:03.200 --> 02:17:10.719
commanding to slay without mercy every

02:17:06.639 --> 02:17:10.719
man of those who had fled.

02:17:12.960 --> 02:17:17.280
According to this account, Krishnadeva

02:17:15.280 --> 02:17:19.840
and his generals began slaughtering

02:17:17.280 --> 02:17:21.920
their own fleeing men until they managed

02:17:19.840 --> 02:17:24.240
to make them turn and flee in the

02:17:21.920 --> 02:17:27.120
opposite direction.

02:17:24.240 --> 02:17:30.960
The pure crushing weight of these bodies,

02:17:27.120 --> 02:17:33.439
backed by as many as 27,000 horses,

02:17:30.960 --> 02:17:35.599
seems to have turned the tide back on

02:17:33.439 --> 02:17:38.080
the Muslim soldiers.

02:17:35.599 --> 02:17:40.880
The sultan's cannons had all fired at

02:17:38.080 --> 02:17:43.439
once, and they all had to stop to reload

02:17:40.880 --> 02:17:46.240
at the same time, meaning that they were

02:17:43.439 --> 02:17:48.240
unable to summon another volley.

02:17:46.240 --> 02:17:50.880
While pursuing the fleeing men of

02:17:48.240 --> 02:17:52.639
Vijayanagara, the sultan's men had

02:17:50.880 --> 02:17:54.399
abandoned their ranks,

02:17:52.639 --> 02:17:57.920
and when the enemy turned and pushed

02:17:54.399 --> 02:18:00.800
back, they found themselves in disarray.

02:17:57.920 --> 02:18:04.160
The fleeing rabbit had once again turned

02:18:00.800 --> 02:18:06.559
around and bitten its pursuer.

02:18:04.160 --> 02:18:10.120
Nuniz breathlessly describes what

02:18:06.559 --> 02:18:10.120
happened next.

02:18:10.240 --> 02:18:14.960
The confusion was so great amongst the

02:18:12.240 --> 02:18:17.280
Moors and such havoc was wrought in

02:18:14.960 --> 02:18:19.599
their ranks that they did not even try

02:18:17.280 --> 02:18:22.240
to defend the camp they had made so

02:18:19.599 --> 02:18:25.280
strong and enclosed so well.

02:18:22.240 --> 02:18:27.920
But like lost men, they leapt into the

02:18:25.280 --> 02:18:30.639
river to save themselves.

02:18:27.920 --> 02:18:33.280
Then after them came large numbers of

02:18:30.639 --> 02:18:35.280
the king's troops and elephants, which

02:18:33.280 --> 02:18:37.920
latter worked amongst the mischief

02:18:35.280 --> 02:18:39.200
without end, for they seized men with

02:18:37.920 --> 02:18:43.599
their trunks

02:18:39.200 --> 02:18:43.599
and tore them into small pieces.

02:18:44.639 --> 02:18:49.840
A final push by the elite troops of

02:18:46.880 --> 02:18:52.000
Vijayanagara drove the sultan's entire

02:18:49.840 --> 02:18:56.639
army into the waters of the Krishna

02:18:52.000 --> 02:18:56.639
River, where a massacre began.

02:18:57.679 --> 02:19:02.719
The army of Bijapur was defeated, but at

02:19:01.200 --> 02:19:05.439
terrible cost.

02:19:02.719 --> 02:19:08.319
Sixteen thousand of Krishnadeva's men

02:19:05.439 --> 02:19:11.359
had been killed in the battle, as Fernao

02:19:08.319 --> 02:19:13.920
Nuniz recounts.

02:19:11.359 --> 02:19:15.439
Here, the king stayed till all the dead

02:19:13.920 --> 02:19:17.920
had been burned,

02:19:15.439 --> 02:19:18.960
and the customary honours had been paid

02:19:17.920 --> 02:19:21.920
to them,

02:19:18.960 --> 02:19:24.160
and here he gave much arms for the souls

02:19:21.920 --> 02:19:25.920
of those who had been killed in battle

02:19:24.160 --> 02:19:31.040
on his side.

02:19:25.920 --> 02:19:31.040
Those numbered sixteen thousand and odd.

02:19:31.200 --> 02:19:36.880
Krishnadeva now returned to the siege of

02:19:34.399 --> 02:19:39.280
the fort, and it's here that he seems to

02:19:36.880 --> 02:19:42.800
have employed the help of a company of

02:19:39.280 --> 02:19:46.240
Portuguese mercenaries led by a captain

02:19:42.800 --> 02:19:48.640
named Christovao de Figueyredo.

02:19:46.240 --> 02:19:50.800
While Krishnadeva seems to have employed

02:19:48.640 --> 02:19:53.520
a limited number of soldiers with

02:19:50.800 --> 02:19:55.840
matchlock muskets in his army, these

02:19:53.520 --> 02:19:58.319
European mercenaries had brought with

02:19:55.840 --> 02:20:00.960
them the latest arquebuses.

02:19:58.319 --> 02:20:03.600
These long-barreled guns achieved an

02:20:00.960 --> 02:20:06.240
astonishing degree of accuracy for early

02:20:03.600 --> 02:20:09.040
firearms.

02:20:06.240 --> 02:20:12.160
Fernao Nuniz writes an account of this

02:20:09.040 --> 02:20:15.359
final siege and how this small group of

02:20:12.160 --> 02:20:17.840
Portuguese snipers tipped the balance in

02:20:15.359 --> 02:20:20.720
the battle for Raichur Fort,

02:20:17.840 --> 02:20:22.800
with either a very skillful or a very

02:20:20.720 --> 02:20:26.640
lucky shot.

02:20:22.800 --> 02:20:29.520
Christovao de Figueyredo went close to the

02:20:26.640 --> 02:20:32.479
trench before the walls, keeping himself

02:20:29.520 --> 02:20:34.800
as much concealed as possible.

02:20:32.479 --> 02:20:37.040
Seeing how fearlessly the Moors

02:20:34.800 --> 02:20:39.840
exposed themselves on the wall,

02:20:37.040 --> 02:20:42.960
began with the musketeers, whom he had

02:20:39.840 --> 02:20:46.399
brought, to open fire on them in such a

02:20:42.960 --> 02:20:49.520
way that he slew many, the Moors being

02:20:46.399 --> 02:20:51.680
careless and free from fear.

02:20:49.520 --> 02:20:53.840
The captain of the city, seeing the

02:20:51.680 --> 02:20:54.800
dismay that had spread amongst his

02:20:53.840 --> 02:20:57.200
people,

02:20:54.800 --> 02:21:00.479
began to turn them back with encouraging

02:20:57.200 --> 02:21:02.720
words, and he, wishing to see for himself

02:21:00.479 --> 02:21:05.760
where the Portuguese were,

02:21:02.720 --> 02:21:08.479
reached over with his body in front of

02:21:05.760 --> 02:21:10.720
one of the embrasures and was killed

02:21:08.479 --> 02:21:13.359
with a musket shot that struck him in

02:21:10.720 --> 02:21:16.080
the middle of his forehead.

02:21:13.359 --> 02:21:19.200
As soon as the captain was thus killed,

02:21:16.080 --> 02:21:21.439
there was great lamentation in the city,

02:21:19.200 --> 02:21:23.680
and soon there was no one defending the

02:21:21.439 --> 02:21:23.680
wall.

02:21:25.520 --> 02:21:32.479
Raichur Fort surrendered soon after.

02:21:30.080 --> 02:21:34.000
These rich lands now belonged to

02:21:32.479 --> 02:21:36.640
Vijayanagara,

02:21:34.000 --> 02:21:38.840
an accomplishment that many kings before

02:21:36.640 --> 02:21:41.600
had tried and failed to

02:21:38.840 --> 02:21:44.479
achieve. Krishnadeva was clearly

02:21:41.600 --> 02:21:47.280
overjoyed, but his victory had caused a

02:21:44.479 --> 02:21:49.680
ripple of concern among all the Muslim

02:21:47.280 --> 02:21:52.240
kingdoms of the region.

02:21:49.680 --> 02:21:55.280
Fernao Nuniz recounts that the king

02:21:52.240 --> 02:21:57.359
soon received a number of diplomats, all

02:21:55.280 --> 02:21:59.680
carrying similar messages from the

02:21:57.359 --> 02:22:01.760
neighboring sultans.

02:21:59.680 --> 02:22:04.319
They all warned him that he should not

02:22:01.760 --> 02:22:07.200
attempt to overreach, he should be

02:22:04.319 --> 02:22:10.160
content with his victory, and not upset

02:22:07.200 --> 02:22:12.720
the natural balance of the region.

02:22:10.160 --> 02:22:14.880
With the hindsight that history gives us,

02:22:12.720 --> 02:22:17.840
we know that Krishnadeva should have

02:22:14.880 --> 02:22:20.000
taken this warning seriously,

02:22:17.840 --> 02:22:23.040
but he did not.

02:22:20.000 --> 02:22:25.680
Krishnadeva sent out the same reply to

02:22:23.040 --> 02:22:29.040
every one of the sultans, which Fernao

02:22:25.680 --> 02:22:29.040
Nuniz recorded.

02:22:29.120 --> 02:22:33.920
I have seen your letters and thank you

02:22:31.600 --> 02:22:36.960
much for what you have sent to say.

02:22:33.920 --> 02:22:39.359
As regards Adil Shah, what I have done to

02:22:36.960 --> 02:22:40.720
him and taken from him, he has richly

02:22:39.359 --> 02:22:43.439
deserved.

02:22:40.720 --> 02:22:46.319
As regards returning it to him, that does

02:22:43.439 --> 02:22:47.520
not seem to me reasonable, nor am I going

02:22:46.319 --> 02:22:49.760
to do it.

02:22:47.520 --> 02:22:52.000
As for your further statement that

02:22:49.760 --> 02:22:53.439
you will all turn against me if I do not

02:22:52.000 --> 02:22:55.760
do as you ask,

02:22:53.439 --> 02:22:57.040
I pray you do not take the trouble to

02:22:55.760 --> 02:22:59.359
come to me,

02:22:57.040 --> 02:23:02.080
for I will come to find you myself if

02:22:59.359 --> 02:23:05.840
you dare to await me in your lands.

02:23:02.080 --> 02:23:05.840
This I send you for answer.

02:23:06.560 --> 02:23:12.479
In fact, the young Krishnadeva was so

02:23:09.439 --> 02:23:15.359
emboldened that he decided to do what no

02:23:12.479 --> 02:23:16.840
king of Vijayanagara had dreamed of for

02:23:15.359 --> 02:23:20.640
more than a hundred

02:23:16.840 --> 02:23:23.680
years; that was to march north and seize

02:23:20.640 --> 02:23:26.680
the sultan's capital city of Bijapur

02:23:23.680 --> 02:23:26.680
itself.

02:23:34.800 --> 02:23:40.319
Bijapur was one of the great cities of

02:23:37.920 --> 02:23:42.479
South India, and the largest and

02:23:40.319 --> 02:23:45.200
wealthiest in the lands that had once

02:23:42.479 --> 02:23:47.840
been part of the Bahmani Sultanate. It

02:23:45.200 --> 02:23:50.560
was a great center of culture, trade, and

02:23:47.840 --> 02:23:54.319
commerce, and was home to a great variety

02:23:50.560 --> 02:23:56.880
of gardens and water pavilions.

02:23:54.319 --> 02:23:59.200
One North Indian visitor to the city

02:23:56.880 --> 02:24:02.240
would later describe it in the following

02:23:59.200 --> 02:24:02.240
glowing terms.

02:24:02.640 --> 02:24:08.080
All around the gate of my residence were

02:24:05.120 --> 02:24:10.720
lofty buildings with houses very healthy

02:24:08.080 --> 02:24:13.359
and airy. Before each shop was a

02:24:10.720 --> 02:24:17.040
beautiful green tree, and the whole

02:24:13.359 --> 02:24:19.600
bizarre was extremely clean and pure.

02:24:17.040 --> 02:24:22.000
It was filled with rare goods such as

02:24:19.600 --> 02:24:22.880
are not seen or heard of in any other

02:24:22.000 --> 02:24:25.760
town.

02:24:22.880 --> 02:24:28.319
Perhaps no place in the wide world could

02:24:25.760 --> 02:24:31.439
present a more wonderful spectacle to

02:24:28.319 --> 02:24:34.800
the eye of the traveller.

02:24:31.439 --> 02:24:37.359
The Portuguese observer Fernao Nuniz

02:24:34.800 --> 02:24:40.399
traveled with Krishna Devaraya as he

02:24:37.359 --> 02:24:43.399
embarked on this campaign far into enemy

02:24:40.399 --> 02:24:43.399
territory.

02:24:43.520 --> 02:24:48.560
He recalls the site of the great city of

02:24:46.000 --> 02:24:51.120
Bijapur as Krishnadeva's armies

02:24:48.560 --> 02:24:53.920
approached it, and mentions that its

02:24:51.120 --> 02:24:57.200
houses reminded him of buildings back

02:24:53.920 --> 02:24:59.680
home in Europe.

02:24:57.200 --> 02:25:03.040
The king journeyed so far that he

02:24:59.680 --> 02:25:06.080
even went as far as Bijapur, which is

02:25:03.040 --> 02:25:08.640
the best city in all the kingdom.

02:25:06.080 --> 02:25:11.280
It has numbers of beautiful houses built

02:25:08.640 --> 02:25:14.160
according to our own fashion, with many

02:25:11.280 --> 02:25:17.680
gardens and bowers made of grape vines

02:25:14.160 --> 02:25:21.359
and pomegranates and oranges and lemons,

02:25:17.680 --> 02:25:24.080
and all other kind of garden produce.

02:25:21.359 --> 02:25:25.280
Seeing Krishnadeva’s massive army

02:25:24.080 --> 02:25:28.080
approach,

02:25:25.280 --> 02:25:31.359
the sultan of Bijapur did the only thing

02:25:28.080 --> 02:25:33.120
he could; he fled the city and went into

02:25:31.359 --> 02:25:36.000
hiding.

02:25:33.120 --> 02:25:39.040
Krishnadeva marched into Bijapur without

02:25:36.000 --> 02:25:41.520
a fight and decided to stay there for as

02:25:39.040 --> 02:25:43.200
long as it took for the sultan to turn

02:25:41.520 --> 02:25:46.319
himself over.

02:25:43.200 --> 02:25:47.680
But the sultan Adil Shah refused to come

02:25:46.319 --> 02:25:50.319
out of hiding,

02:25:47.680 --> 02:25:54.560
and so, Krishnadeva and his army settled

02:25:50.319 --> 02:25:54.560
down in the city and waited.

02:25:54.640 --> 02:25:59.600
During his lengthy stay in Bijapur,

02:25:57.359 --> 02:26:02.399
Krishnadeva's army put an enormous

02:25:59.600 --> 02:26:05.439
strain on the city, and in fact, they

02:26:02.399 --> 02:26:08.000
would all but destroy it.

02:26:05.439 --> 02:26:10.000
To keep themselves warm at night, the

02:26:08.000 --> 02:26:13.359
soldiers demolished its beautiful

02:26:10.000 --> 02:26:15.600
buildings and burned them as firewood,

02:26:13.359 --> 02:26:18.160
and drank so much water that its

02:26:15.600 --> 02:26:20.720
reservoirs ran dry.

02:26:18.160 --> 02:26:23.840
The whole city of Bijapur was slowly

02:26:20.720 --> 02:26:26.399
demolished as though eaten by termites,

02:26:23.840 --> 02:26:29.680
until only the palaces where Krishnadeva

02:26:26.399 --> 02:26:32.880
was staying were still standing, as Fernao

02:26:29.680 --> 02:26:35.680
Nuniz recalls.

02:26:32.880 --> 02:26:38.000
The city was left almost in ruins,

02:26:35.680 --> 02:26:39.280
not that the king had commanded it to be

02:26:38.000 --> 02:26:41.760
destroyed,

02:26:39.280 --> 02:26:44.720
but that his troops, in order to make

02:26:41.760 --> 02:26:48.880
fires for cooking, had torn down so many

02:26:44.720 --> 02:26:51.280
houses that it was a great grief to see.

02:26:48.880 --> 02:26:53.600
The sultan Adil Shah

02:26:51.280 --> 02:26:56.240
went to ask the king what wrong the

02:26:53.600 --> 02:26:57.920
houses had done that he had commanded to

02:26:56.240 --> 02:27:00.160
destroy them,

02:26:57.920 --> 02:27:03.280
for there remained no other houses

02:27:00.160 --> 02:27:06.640
standing save only the palaces where the

02:27:03.280 --> 02:27:10.000
king Krishnadeva was staying.

02:27:06.640 --> 02:27:12.720
The king sent answer that it was not he

02:27:10.000 --> 02:27:16.520
who had done it, but that he could not

02:27:12.720 --> 02:27:16.520
control his people.

02:27:17.359 --> 02:27:22.800
Eventually, drinking water in the city

02:27:19.840 --> 02:27:24.880
ran out, and Krishnadeva was finally

02:27:22.800 --> 02:27:26.720
forced to leave.

02:27:24.880 --> 02:27:29.920
He had not captured the sultan of

02:27:26.720 --> 02:27:31.640
Bijapur, but he had certainly made his

02:27:29.920 --> 02:27:34.399
point.

02:27:31.640 --> 02:27:37.120
Vijayanagara was now without doubt the

02:27:34.399 --> 02:27:39.760
strongest power in South India.

02:27:37.120 --> 02:27:42.640
The sultans who had once loomed over it

02:27:39.760 --> 02:27:44.880
now fled at the advance of its armies,

02:27:42.640 --> 02:27:46.960
and their cities could be plucked like

02:27:44.880 --> 02:27:49.200
ripe fruit.

02:27:46.960 --> 02:27:51.600
It was a point that King Krishnadeva

02:27:49.200 --> 02:27:54.080
clearly delighted in making, but it was

02:27:51.600 --> 02:27:55.359
one that the Deccan sultans would not

02:27:54.080 --> 02:27:57.760
forget.

02:27:55.359 --> 02:28:00.319
The destruction of Bijapur left a

02:27:57.760 --> 02:28:02.960
stinging reminder that if they continued

02:28:00.319 --> 02:28:05.920
fighting amongst themselves, a greater

02:28:02.960 --> 02:28:08.000
power to the south would swallow them up

02:28:05.920 --> 02:28:10.560
one by one.

02:28:08.000 --> 02:28:12.800
Krishnadeva's actions would remind these

02:28:10.560 --> 02:28:15.600
sultans that they would soon need to

02:28:12.800 --> 02:28:18.160
stand together, and in that way, this

02:28:15.600 --> 02:28:20.720
resounding victory would lead in the

02:28:18.160 --> 02:28:23.280
coming years to the dissolution and

02:28:20.720 --> 02:28:26.280
collapse of the entire empire of

02:28:23.280 --> 02:28:26.280
Vijayanagara.

02:28:30.560 --> 02:28:35.960
If you had the choice to travel back in

02:28:32.640 --> 02:28:38.720
time and see just one week in the age of

02:28:35.960 --> 02:28:41.760
Vijayanagara, a good choice would be the

02:28:38.720 --> 02:28:44.720
week of the Mahanavami Festival,

02:28:41.760 --> 02:28:47.760
a lavish ceremony that ran for 10 days,

02:28:44.720 --> 02:28:50.560
usually in October.

02:28:47.760 --> 02:28:52.840
The Persian ambassador Abdur Razzak

02:28:50.560 --> 02:28:55.920
witnessed this event in the year

02:28:52.840 --> 02:28:59.600
1443, and gave the following account of

02:28:55.920 --> 02:29:01.920
its chaotic and colourful scenes.

02:28:59.600 --> 02:29:04.880
All the readers and storytellers,

02:29:01.920 --> 02:29:08.399
musicians and jugglers, were rewarded by

02:29:04.880 --> 02:29:11.920
the king with gold and garments. For

02:29:08.399 --> 02:29:15.520
three continuous days, this royal fate

02:29:11.920 --> 02:29:17.840
continued with the most gorgeous display.

02:29:15.520 --> 02:29:21.200
One cannot without entering into great

02:29:17.840 --> 02:29:22.399
detail mention all the various kinds of

02:29:21.200 --> 02:29:24.800
pyrotechnic

02:29:22.399 --> 02:29:28.319
and fireworks and various other

02:29:24.800 --> 02:29:30.399
amusements which were exhibited.

02:29:28.319 --> 02:29:33.040
He recounts the splendor of the elephant

02:29:30.399 --> 02:29:34.640
procession that took place during this

02:29:33.040 --> 02:29:36.800
festival.

02:29:34.640 --> 02:29:39.280
They brought with them a thousand

02:29:36.800 --> 02:29:42.319
elephants resembling the waves of a

02:29:39.280 --> 02:29:44.880
troubled sea or a stormy cloud which

02:29:42.319 --> 02:29:48.000
were covered with brilliant armor, and

02:29:44.880 --> 02:29:51.120
with castles magnificently adorned in

02:29:48.000 --> 02:29:53.439
which were jugglers and artificers.

02:29:51.120 --> 02:29:56.160
On the trunks and ears of these animals

02:29:53.439 --> 02:29:57.399
had been drawn with cinnabar and other

02:29:56.160 --> 02:30:00.000
substances

02:29:57.399 --> 02:30:02.880
extraordinary pictures and figures of

02:30:00.000 --> 02:30:05.439
wonderful beauty.

02:30:02.880 --> 02:30:07.840
The traveler Domingo Paes was lucky

02:30:05.439 --> 02:30:11.120
enough to see this event when he visited

02:30:07.840 --> 02:30:13.200
Vijayanagara nearly 80 years later, in

02:30:11.120 --> 02:30:15.439
the year 1520.

02:30:13.200 --> 02:30:18.160
It's clear that by that time, the

02:30:15.439 --> 02:30:20.880
opulence of the ceremony had only

02:30:18.160 --> 02:30:20.880
increased.

02:30:21.280 --> 02:30:24.880
As soon as the king had finished his

02:30:22.800 --> 02:30:26.800
ceremonies, he again took horse and

02:30:24.880 --> 02:30:27.680
returned to the city in the same way he

02:30:26.800 --> 02:30:30.319
had come,

02:30:27.680 --> 02:30:32.160
the troops never weary of their shouting.

02:30:30.319 --> 02:30:33.840
As soon as he passed by them, they began

02:30:32.160 --> 02:30:34.640
to march.

02:30:33.840 --> 02:30:36.640
Then,

02:30:34.640 --> 02:30:38.720
to see those who were on the hills and

02:30:36.640 --> 02:30:40.800
slopes and the descent of them with

02:30:38.720 --> 02:30:42.880
their shouts and beating of shields and

02:30:40.800 --> 02:30:44.880
shaking of arrows and bows, they were

02:30:42.880 --> 02:30:47.600
without count.

02:30:44.880 --> 02:30:49.439
Truly, I was so carried out with myself

02:30:47.600 --> 02:30:53.359
that it seemed as if what I saw was a

02:30:49.439 --> 02:30:53.359
vision and that I was in a dream.

02:30:54.080 --> 02:30:59.760
As Paes saw this procession pass by, he

02:30:57.200 --> 02:31:02.720
could have had no idea that the final

02:30:59.760 --> 02:31:04.000
decades of this great society were now

02:31:02.720 --> 02:31:06.800
at hand,

02:31:04.000 --> 02:31:10.160
that in only a few decades, these streets

02:31:06.800 --> 02:31:14.280
would be empty, with grasses and vines

02:31:10.160 --> 02:31:14.280
pushing up through the stones.

02:31:28.319 --> 02:31:34.640
The last great king of Vijayanagara,

02:31:31.439 --> 02:31:36.600
Krishna Devaraya, died on the 17th of

02:31:34.640 --> 02:31:38.240
October in the year

02:31:36.600 --> 02:31:40.880
1529,

02:31:38.240 --> 02:31:43.280
apparently after falling ill while

02:31:40.880 --> 02:31:48.000
preparing for another campaign against

02:31:43.280 --> 02:31:48.000
his old enemy, the sultan of Bijapur.

02:31:48.240 --> 02:31:53.359
While successful at all other aspects of

02:31:50.640 --> 02:31:56.000
being king, he'd had little luck with

02:31:53.359 --> 02:31:59.120
siring a son.

02:31:56.000 --> 02:32:02.479
Krishnadeva did have two sons, one of

02:31:59.120 --> 02:32:04.640
whom at six years old became a casualty

02:32:02.479 --> 02:32:07.200
of courtly intrigue.

02:32:04.640 --> 02:32:09.680
He was named the crown prince, but this

02:32:07.200 --> 02:32:12.560
was also his death sentence.

02:32:09.680 --> 02:32:14.960
Within a year, the boy was poisoned, with

02:32:12.560 --> 02:32:19.280
Krishnadeva suspecting his own prime

02:32:14.960 --> 02:32:22.000
minister, who he then had blinded.

02:32:19.280 --> 02:32:24.319
When the king died, his remaining son was

02:32:22.000 --> 02:32:26.319
too young to be considered, and so, the

02:32:24.319 --> 02:32:28.000
crown passed to his younger brother

02:32:26.319 --> 02:32:30.640
Achyuta.

02:32:28.000 --> 02:32:34.960
This man seems to have had no talent for

02:32:30.640 --> 02:32:36.080
ruling, as Fernao Nuniz recalls.

02:32:34.960 --> 02:32:39.680
King

02:32:36.080 --> 02:32:43.760
Achyutaraya, after he ascended the throne,

02:32:39.680 --> 02:32:47.280
gave himself over to vice and tyranny.

02:32:43.760 --> 02:32:49.840
Here is a man of very little honesty, and

02:32:47.280 --> 02:32:52.560
on account of this, the people and the

02:32:49.840 --> 02:32:53.840
captains are much discontented with his

02:32:52.560 --> 02:32:57.040
evil life

02:32:53.840 --> 02:32:57.040
and inclinations.

02:32:57.680 --> 02:33:03.040
In the vacuum left by the death of the

02:32:59.920 --> 02:33:06.319
great king, a number of opportunists were

02:33:03.040 --> 02:33:09.280
beginning to fancy their chances. Chief

02:33:06.319 --> 02:33:12.479
among these was a divisive and ruthless

02:33:09.280 --> 02:33:15.439
social climber in whose hands the empire

02:33:12.479 --> 02:33:18.160
of Vijayanagara would finally collapse

02:33:15.439 --> 02:33:22.319
into ash and flame.

02:33:18.160 --> 02:33:22.319
His name was Ramaraya.

02:33:31.600 --> 02:33:36.399
Ramaraya had led a remarkably colorful

02:33:35.280 --> 02:33:38.960
life.

02:33:36.399 --> 02:33:41.840
He began his career as a courtier in the

02:33:38.960 --> 02:33:44.720
kingdom of Golcanda to the north,

02:33:41.840 --> 02:33:47.200
but he had a keen sense for situations

02:33:44.720 --> 02:33:48.800
in which he could better his position,

02:33:47.200 --> 02:33:51.359
and during the golden age of

02:33:48.800 --> 02:33:54.399
Krishnadeva's reign, he made his way

02:33:51.359 --> 02:33:56.640
south to the Vijayanagara court to serve

02:33:54.399 --> 02:33:56.640
him.

02:33:58.720 --> 02:34:03.439
Ramaraya's mother had been the daughter

02:34:01.040 --> 02:34:05.920
of a chieftain in the east, and these

02:34:03.439 --> 02:34:08.960
family credentials were apparently

02:34:05.920 --> 02:34:11.520
enough for him to marry a princess.

02:34:08.960 --> 02:34:14.319
This ambitious young man was now the

02:34:11.520 --> 02:34:16.640
son-in-law to the king, and at every turn

02:34:14.319 --> 02:34:19.280
he would work to increase his power and

02:34:16.640 --> 02:34:22.640
influence in the court.

02:34:19.280 --> 02:34:25.920
When Krishnadeva's brother Achyuta died

02:34:22.640 --> 02:34:28.240
after ruling for 13 years, his young son

02:34:25.920 --> 02:34:32.000
took the throne, and the plotting at

02:34:28.240 --> 02:34:32.000
court reached fever pitch.

02:34:32.960 --> 02:34:37.760
Ramaraya joined a number of

02:34:35.120 --> 02:34:40.399
unsuccessful plots before finally

02:34:37.760 --> 02:34:43.120
raising a successful rebellion with the

02:34:40.399 --> 02:34:45.680
intention of putting a young boy named

02:34:43.120 --> 02:34:48.399
Sadasiva on the throne,

02:34:45.680 --> 02:34:50.479
who was a quite distant nephew of the

02:34:48.399 --> 02:34:53.280
dead king Krishnadeva.

02:34:50.479 --> 02:34:56.160
But of course it was Ramaraya who was

02:34:53.280 --> 02:34:58.960
truly in charge.

02:34:56.160 --> 02:35:01.680
This young boy Sadasiva was put on the

02:34:58.960 --> 02:35:04.160
throne in the year 1542,

02:35:01.680 --> 02:35:07.520
and Ramaraya, then around the age of

02:35:04.160 --> 02:35:10.080
57, became his regent.

02:35:07.520 --> 02:35:12.560
A regent was a person who runs the

02:35:10.080 --> 02:35:15.280
complicated affairs of state while a

02:35:12.560 --> 02:35:18.160
young boy king grows up.

02:35:15.280 --> 02:35:20.960
The idea was that at the age of 16, the

02:35:18.160 --> 02:35:23.840
boy could take up these duties himself,

02:35:20.960 --> 02:35:24.840
and the regent, his duty done, would be

02:35:23.840 --> 02:35:28.399
quietly

02:35:24.840 --> 02:35:31.120
excused. But of course, this is not quite

02:35:28.399 --> 02:35:33.439
how things played out.

02:35:31.120 --> 02:35:35.920
When the young boy king Sadasiva

02:35:33.439 --> 02:35:38.399
reached adulthood, he demanded to take

02:35:35.920 --> 02:35:41.760
over the reins of the state.

02:35:38.399 --> 02:35:44.319
Ramaraya had him imprisoned.

02:35:41.760 --> 02:35:47.280
The boy king would now appear only once

02:35:44.319 --> 02:35:50.640
a year to the crowds while Ramaraya

02:35:47.280 --> 02:35:53.040
acted as emperor in all but name.

02:35:50.640 --> 02:35:55.200
By the year 1562,

02:35:53.040 --> 02:35:57.680
even these annual appearances were

02:35:55.200 --> 02:35:57.680
stopped.

02:36:01.120 --> 02:36:06.800
One of the great historical composers of

02:36:04.000 --> 02:36:09.200
Carnatic music was a man named Kanaka

02:36:06.800 --> 02:36:10.960
Dasa.

02:36:09.200 --> 02:36:14.000
He lived during the life of King

02:36:10.960 --> 02:36:16.240
Krishnadeva and saw his death,

02:36:14.000 --> 02:36:17.760
as well as the time of chaos that

02:36:16.240 --> 02:36:20.240
followed.

02:36:17.760 --> 02:36:23.120
During this time, he wrote a surviving

02:36:20.240 --> 02:36:25.600
piece of poetry that describes how many

02:36:23.120 --> 02:36:28.560
of the citizens of Vijayanagara must

02:36:25.600 --> 02:36:32.000
have felt as the kingdom descended over

02:36:28.560 --> 02:36:35.359
the 23 years that the usurper Ramaraya

02:36:32.000 --> 02:36:35.359
remained on the throne.

02:36:35.520 --> 02:36:42.080
Where did truth and duty go?

02:36:39.439 --> 02:36:44.399
The noble can't survive anymore.

02:36:42.080 --> 02:36:45.600
Thieves and habitual adulterers strike

02:36:44.399 --> 02:36:47.520
it rich.

02:36:45.600 --> 02:36:50.720
The rest are poor.

02:36:47.520 --> 02:36:54.399
Family members turn hostile. Fools puffed

02:36:50.720 --> 02:36:57.600
up with pride forget god, guru, and elders.

02:36:54.399 --> 02:37:00.240
Decent holy people go unprotected.

02:36:57.600 --> 02:37:02.560
No one pays the soldiers. No helping

02:37:00.240 --> 02:37:04.399
rains shower the earth.

02:37:02.560 --> 02:37:07.040
Those with food and clothes are

02:37:04.399 --> 02:37:09.760
corrupted by bribery.

02:37:07.040 --> 02:37:11.840
Immature dogs full of trickery multiply

02:37:09.760 --> 02:37:15.040
like cruel snakes.

02:37:11.840 --> 02:37:17.120
Traitors to god win houses, gain cows and

02:37:15.040 --> 02:37:19.920
wealth and grain.

02:37:17.120 --> 02:37:21.680
Earth groans under the weight,

02:37:19.920 --> 02:37:23.680
tottering,

02:37:21.680 --> 02:37:25.760
crying.

02:37:23.680 --> 02:37:27.680
Worshipers of Shiva are clashing with

02:37:25.760 --> 02:37:29.680
the Vishnu devotees.

02:37:27.680 --> 02:37:34.160
Great offerings are made to the most

02:37:29.680 --> 02:37:38.479
horrific violent gods. Who could list

02:37:34.160 --> 02:37:38.479
all the wrongs of the time?

02:37:39.280 --> 02:37:46.479
While operating the empire's foreign

02:37:41.760 --> 02:37:48.880
policy, Ramaraya acted just as deviously.

02:37:46.479 --> 02:37:51.200
As the emperor of Vijayanagara, he

02:37:48.880 --> 02:37:54.319
plotted to turn the sultans of the

02:37:51.200 --> 02:37:56.520
Deccan against one another.

02:37:54.319 --> 02:37:58.720
These sultans often asked for

02:37:56.520 --> 02:38:01.280
Vijayanagara's help in their wars

02:37:58.720 --> 02:38:04.000
against one another, and so, he would ally

02:38:01.280 --> 02:38:06.880
first with one, then another, with the

02:38:04.000 --> 02:38:10.399
hope of thereby weakening them all

02:38:06.880 --> 02:38:12.479
and keeping them at each other's throats.

02:38:10.399 --> 02:38:15.359
He would often promise not to destroy

02:38:12.479 --> 02:38:18.319
mosques or unnecessarily hurt Muslim

02:38:15.359 --> 02:38:21.439
civilians, but according to some sources,

02:38:18.319 --> 02:38:24.479
these promises were not often kept.

02:38:21.439 --> 02:38:27.520
Eventually, one of these sultans, a man

02:38:24.479 --> 02:38:30.720
named Hussain Nizam Shah I of

02:38:27.520 --> 02:38:33.760
the sultanate of Ahmadnagar, would soon

02:38:30.720 --> 02:38:33.760
have had enough.

02:38:38.080 --> 02:38:41.840
It's clear that the sultan Hussain hated

02:38:40.880 --> 02:38:44.319
Ramaraya

02:38:41.840 --> 02:38:47.120
on a personal level.

02:38:44.319 --> 02:38:50.240
Ferishta recalls one meeting between

02:38:47.120 --> 02:38:54.240
these men when the king of Vijayanagara

02:38:50.240 --> 02:38:54.240
openly insulted his guest.

02:38:54.560 --> 02:38:58.960
Hussain and Nizam Shah went to meet

02:38:57.439 --> 02:39:00.640
Ramaraya.

02:38:58.960 --> 02:39:03.760
At the time of the meeting,

02:39:00.640 --> 02:39:06.479
Ramaraya showed great vanity and

02:39:03.760 --> 02:39:09.280
loftiness and remained seated,

02:39:06.479 --> 02:39:10.880
and had Hussain Nizam Shah kiss his hand

02:39:09.280 --> 02:39:14.080
in this manner.

02:39:10.880 --> 02:39:16.960
Hussain Nizam Shah was furious at the

02:39:14.080 --> 02:39:19.439
improper behavior of Ramaraya, and in

02:39:16.960 --> 02:39:21.760
order to reproach the Raja,

02:39:19.439 --> 02:39:23.600
he at once called for water and washed

02:39:21.760 --> 02:39:25.120
his hands.

02:39:23.600 --> 02:39:28.720
On seeing this,

02:39:25.120 --> 02:39:31.840
Ramaraya was enraged and said in the

02:39:28.720 --> 02:39:35.040
Kannada language, if this man were not my

02:39:31.840 --> 02:39:38.520
guest, I would instantly cut him to bits

02:39:35.040 --> 02:39:38.520
with my sword.

02:39:40.080 --> 02:39:45.680
These insults clearly stung Hussain, but

02:39:43.200 --> 02:39:48.080
the final straw would come when

02:39:45.680 --> 02:39:50.800
Ramaraya apparently sent a long and

02:39:48.080 --> 02:39:52.880
insulting list of demands for tribute to

02:39:50.800 --> 02:39:55.840
the Muslim sultan.

02:39:52.880 --> 02:39:59.200
According to one obscure poet, an Indian

02:39:55.840 --> 02:40:02.399
Muslim named Shauqi, this list of demands

02:39:59.200 --> 02:40:06.240
included camels from Kabul, ambergris,

02:40:02.399 --> 02:40:09.680
aloes, musk, a large silver bell, a golden

02:40:06.240 --> 02:40:12.880
flute, gold and precious goods, weapons

02:40:09.680 --> 02:40:16.880
such as maces and Bahmani daggers, jade

02:40:12.880 --> 02:40:19.840
pitchers, ruby cups, diamond cubes,

02:40:16.880 --> 02:40:23.200
and perhaps most insultingly of all, the

02:40:19.840 --> 02:40:25.920
foot bracelets of the sultan's wife.

02:40:23.200 --> 02:40:27.279
Finally, he demanded that Hussain stop

02:40:25.920 --> 02:40:29.200
eating beef,

02:40:27.279 --> 02:40:32.479
turn away from Mecca,

02:40:29.200 --> 02:40:35.359
and convert to worshiping Shiva.

02:40:32.479 --> 02:40:38.000
If Hussain refused, the poet relates the

02:40:35.359 --> 02:40:40.800
following threat allegedly delivered by

02:40:38.000 --> 02:40:40.800
Ramaraya.

02:40:41.279 --> 02:40:47.279
I'll spare neither Turk nor Turkish bow.

02:40:44.560 --> 02:40:49.920
I'll spare neither rich nor poor.

02:40:47.279 --> 02:40:52.640
I will not spare the brides of India,

02:40:49.920 --> 02:40:56.000
nor will I spare the brides of Sind. I

02:40:52.640 --> 02:40:58.240
won't spare a single scholar or holy man,

02:40:56.000 --> 02:41:02.880
neither aged nor youth,

02:40:58.240 --> 02:41:05.040
neither young man or old.

02:41:02.880 --> 02:41:06.960
Whether this episode is true

02:41:05.040 --> 02:41:10.080
or just one of the many poetic

02:41:06.960 --> 02:41:12.479
flourishes invented by the poet Shauqi,

02:41:10.080 --> 02:41:15.439
what is certain is that for this Sultan

02:41:12.479 --> 02:41:18.960
Hussain, the king of Vijayanagara had

02:41:15.439 --> 02:41:20.800
finally gone too far.

02:41:18.960 --> 02:41:22.800
He was determined to put aside his

02:41:20.800 --> 02:41:25.680
differences with the other sultans of

02:41:22.800 --> 02:41:28.720
South India and together join in

02:41:25.680 --> 02:41:31.840
partnership against King Ramaraya.

02:41:28.720 --> 02:41:36.240
The Portuguese chronicler Diego de Couto

02:41:31.840 --> 02:41:36.240
recounts the decision they made next.

02:41:36.640 --> 02:41:41.279
After Ramaraya entered their kingdoms

02:41:39.040 --> 02:41:43.680
and destroyed and devastated them and

02:41:41.279 --> 02:41:46.160
carried great riches away from them,

02:41:43.680 --> 02:41:48.319
King Hussain was so afflicted that he

02:41:46.160 --> 02:41:49.439
invited the other Moorish kings of the

02:41:48.319 --> 02:41:51.439
Deccan

02:41:49.439 --> 02:41:55.120
so that they could all set out together

02:41:51.439 --> 02:41:59.840
against Ramaraya and destroy him and

02:41:55.120 --> 02:41:59.840
divide his kingdoms amongst them.

02:42:00.240 --> 02:42:05.120
By this time, after years of war, there

02:42:03.120 --> 02:42:06.399
was a deep bitterness between these

02:42:05.120 --> 02:42:08.399
sultans.

02:42:06.399 --> 02:42:11.200
But faced with the growing insults from

02:42:08.399 --> 02:42:13.200
the south, they were prepared to set this

02:42:11.200 --> 02:42:15.680
aside.

02:42:13.200 --> 02:42:18.399
The sultans of the Deccan sealed their

02:42:15.680 --> 02:42:20.720
tentative alliance with marriages, even

02:42:18.399 --> 02:42:23.040
exchanging forts as part of their

02:42:20.720 --> 02:42:24.880
daughter's dowries in order to settle

02:42:23.040 --> 02:42:27.920
the territorial disputes that had

02:42:24.880 --> 02:42:29.120
divided them. Through King Ramaraya's

02:42:27.920 --> 02:42:31.920
arrogance,

02:42:29.120 --> 02:42:34.319
Vijayanagara had united its enemies

02:42:31.920 --> 02:42:37.660
against it, and they were now all

02:42:34.319 --> 02:42:43.359
marching south, hungry for revenge.

02:42:43.359 --> 02:42:49.920
The year was 1565.

02:42:47.279 --> 02:42:52.720
By this time, the treacherous usurper

02:42:49.920 --> 02:42:55.600
Ramaraya was an old man

02:42:52.720 --> 02:42:57.520
now well into his eighties, but when he

02:42:55.600 --> 02:43:00.640
heard of the combined forces of the

02:42:57.520 --> 02:43:03.359
sultans marching south, he was determined

02:43:00.640 --> 02:43:05.200
to ride out with his great army and lead

02:43:03.359 --> 02:43:09.120
it to victory,

02:43:05.200 --> 02:43:11.760
and he had good reason to be confident.

02:43:09.120 --> 02:43:14.040
Despite banding together, the sultans of

02:43:11.760 --> 02:43:17.200
the Deccan were still no match for

02:43:14.040 --> 02:43:20.080
Vijayanagara in sheer numbers.

02:43:17.200 --> 02:43:23.040
According to records, Ramaraya marched

02:43:20.080 --> 02:43:25.040
out with 70,000 cavalry and more

02:43:23.040 --> 02:43:26.160
than 700,000 foot

02:43:25.040 --> 02:43:28.080
soldiers.

02:43:26.160 --> 02:43:30.240
More conservative estimates put the

02:43:28.080 --> 02:43:31.840
number at around a hundred and fifty

02:43:30.240 --> 02:43:34.000
thousand.

02:43:31.840 --> 02:43:36.960
This would have been the entirety of the

02:43:34.000 --> 02:43:40.160
army of Vijayanagara, with every soldier

02:43:36.960 --> 02:43:42.000
withdrawn from every far-flung post and

02:43:40.160 --> 02:43:45.040
distant border fort,

02:43:42.000 --> 02:43:48.240
and brought to bear for a final decisive

02:43:45.040 --> 02:43:51.120
battle for the future of South India.

02:43:48.240 --> 02:43:53.840
The stakes for both sides couldn't have

02:43:51.120 --> 02:43:53.840
been higher.

02:43:54.960 --> 02:44:00.720
After a number of skirmishes, the two

02:43:57.600 --> 02:44:02.640
vast armies finally met on the plains

02:44:00.720 --> 02:44:05.359
that stretch out on the banks of the

02:44:02.640 --> 02:44:07.760
river Krishna, between the villages of

02:44:05.359 --> 02:44:09.920
Rakkasa and Tangadi.

02:44:07.760 --> 02:44:12.240
But today, this confrontation is

02:44:09.920 --> 02:44:15.439
remembered by the name of a fortified

02:44:12.240 --> 02:44:18.100
town about 25 kilometers to the north,

02:44:15.439 --> 02:44:20.160
a place called Talikota.

02:44:20.160 --> 02:44:25.600
For the sultans of the Deccan, the odds

02:44:22.800 --> 02:44:27.520
at the battle of Talikota didn't look

02:44:25.600 --> 02:44:30.240
good.

02:44:27.520 --> 02:44:33.200
The forces of Vijayanagara outnumbered

02:44:30.240 --> 02:44:35.680
them significantly, and the advantage in

02:44:33.200 --> 02:44:38.240
firepower that the sultan's ancestors

02:44:35.680 --> 02:44:41.040
had enjoyed at the Battle of Raichur

02:44:38.240 --> 02:44:43.359
had also been wiped out.

02:44:41.040 --> 02:44:45.520
In the more than 40 years since the

02:44:43.359 --> 02:44:47.359
armies of Krishnadeva had scraped a

02:44:45.520 --> 02:44:49.760
victory on the banks of the river

02:44:47.359 --> 02:44:52.640
Krishna, they had learned to respect the

02:44:49.760 --> 02:44:56.399
power of cannon fire, and Vijayanagara

02:44:52.640 --> 02:44:58.960
had truly joined the gunpowder age.

02:44:56.399 --> 02:45:01.439
Sources claim that Ramaraya marched

02:44:58.960 --> 02:45:02.880
to meet the sultans with a thousand

02:45:01.439 --> 02:45:05.040
cannons.

02:45:02.880 --> 02:45:08.080
He clearly believed that with superior

02:45:05.040 --> 02:45:10.800
numbers and now with superior firepower

02:45:08.080 --> 02:45:12.399
too, the result of the battle would not

02:45:10.800 --> 02:45:14.640
be in question.

02:45:12.399 --> 02:45:19.279
The scholar Ferishta recalls the

02:45:14.640 --> 02:45:19.279
daunting sight that awaited the sultans.

02:45:19.840 --> 02:45:24.960
It was at length fully ascertained that

02:45:22.240 --> 02:45:28.160
the only safe passage for the army

02:45:24.960 --> 02:45:30.160
was directly in the enemy's front, which

02:45:28.160 --> 02:45:32.080
was in his possession

02:45:30.160 --> 02:45:34.800
and who had constructed field

02:45:32.080 --> 02:45:36.319
fortifications strengthened by cannon

02:45:34.800 --> 02:45:38.800
and fireworks

02:45:36.319 --> 02:45:41.600
on the opposite bank.

02:45:38.800 --> 02:45:44.080
Two thousand war elephants and one

02:45:41.600 --> 02:45:47.439
thousand pieces of cannon were placed at

02:45:44.080 --> 02:45:49.600
different intervals of his line.

02:45:47.439 --> 02:45:52.160
But the armies of the sultans had also

02:45:49.600 --> 02:45:54.080
learned lessons from their defeat 40

02:45:52.160 --> 02:45:55.920
years earlier,

02:45:54.080 --> 02:45:59.439
and they now marched to battle with

02:45:55.920 --> 02:46:01.680
decades of experience in using cannon.

02:45:59.439 --> 02:46:04.240
This time, instead of arranging their

02:46:01.680 --> 02:46:07.120
cannons in a single line that fired all

02:46:04.240 --> 02:46:09.760
at once, they were placed in three lines

02:46:07.120 --> 02:46:10.399
which could stagger their fire.

02:46:09.760 --> 02:46:12.399
Now,

02:46:10.399 --> 02:46:15.120
one line could fire while the others

02:46:12.399 --> 02:46:16.800
reloaded, creating an almost continuous

02:46:15.120 --> 02:46:20.319
blanket of fire.

02:46:16.800 --> 02:46:22.720
The effect was truly devastating.

02:46:20.319 --> 02:46:25.600
When the battle began, the forces of

02:46:22.720 --> 02:46:30.720
Vijayanagara unleashed one big

02:46:25.600 --> 02:46:32.960
terrifying barrage, as Ferishta recounts.

02:46:30.720 --> 02:46:34.000
Both armies being in motion soon came to

02:46:32.960 --> 02:46:35.920
battle,

02:46:34.000 --> 02:46:38.880
and the infidels began the attack by

02:46:35.920 --> 02:46:42.240
vast flights of rockets and rapid

02:46:38.880 --> 02:46:42.240
discharges of artillery.

02:46:42.800 --> 02:46:48.720
Ramaraya, now an old man, declined to

02:46:46.080 --> 02:46:50.720
travel on horseback, and instead was

02:46:48.720 --> 02:46:52.800
carried around the battlefield in a

02:46:50.720 --> 02:46:55.120
litter or palanquin.

02:46:52.800 --> 02:46:57.439
At one point, he's apparently said to

02:46:55.120 --> 02:47:00.399
have surrounded himself with piles of

02:46:57.439 --> 02:47:02.640
jewels and coins, and handed these out to

02:47:00.399 --> 02:47:04.640
anyone who would charge into the heat of

02:47:02.640 --> 02:47:07.520
the battle.

02:47:04.640 --> 02:47:08.960
The infidels, inspired by the generosity

02:47:07.520 --> 02:47:11.920
of their prince,

02:47:08.960 --> 02:47:14.160
charged the right and left of the allies

02:47:11.920 --> 02:47:16.479
with such vigor that they were thrown

02:47:14.160 --> 02:47:18.399
into temporary disorder, and even to

02:47:16.479 --> 02:47:21.359
prepare for retreat.

02:47:18.399 --> 02:47:22.399
Hussain, however, remained firm in the

02:47:21.359 --> 02:47:24.000
center

02:47:22.399 --> 02:47:27.200
and pushed on

02:47:24.000 --> 02:47:31.040
so ardently, for the division of Ramraj

02:47:27.200 --> 02:47:33.439
was thrown into confusion.

02:47:31.040 --> 02:47:36.399
It seemed that the overwhelming numbers

02:47:33.439 --> 02:47:38.560
of Vijayanagara would win the day, but

02:47:36.399 --> 02:47:40.880
then something happened that would turn

02:47:38.560 --> 02:47:44.800
the tide completely.

02:47:40.880 --> 02:47:46.160
That is, Ramaraya, the regent, the usurper

02:47:44.800 --> 02:47:49.399
of the throne,

02:47:46.160 --> 02:47:49.399
was killed.

02:47:49.439 --> 02:47:53.680
Accounts of exactly how this happened

02:47:51.840 --> 02:47:56.720
differ.

02:47:53.680 --> 02:47:58.800
One unlikely-sounding source describes

02:47:56.720 --> 02:48:01.520
how the sultans packed their cannons

02:47:58.800 --> 02:48:04.000
with copper coins, blasting them into the

02:48:01.520 --> 02:48:06.640
enemy ranks in what would be one of the

02:48:04.000 --> 02:48:09.120
first uses of a weapon that would come

02:48:06.640 --> 02:48:11.920
to be known as grapeshot.

02:48:09.120 --> 02:48:14.080
These superheated coins would have torn

02:48:11.920 --> 02:48:16.880
like bullets into the Vijayanagara

02:48:14.080 --> 02:48:19.200
soldiers, killing their horses and

02:48:16.880 --> 02:48:21.520
maiming hundreds.

02:48:19.200 --> 02:48:23.520
One source recounts that one of these

02:48:21.520 --> 02:48:25.840
coins flew through the sky of the

02:48:23.520 --> 02:48:27.680
battlefield, punched through the side of

02:48:25.840 --> 02:48:30.240
the palanquin that was carrying the

02:48:27.680 --> 02:48:31.680
treacherous King Ramaraya, and killed

02:48:30.240 --> 02:48:34.240
him.

02:48:31.680 --> 02:48:37.200
Other sources claim that a stampeding

02:48:34.240 --> 02:48:39.760
elephant caused Ramaraya's bodyguard to

02:48:37.200 --> 02:48:42.640
flee in terror, leaving him to be

02:48:39.760 --> 02:48:45.120
captured by an enemy vanguard.

02:48:42.640 --> 02:48:47.520
These sources describe him being taken

02:48:45.120 --> 02:48:50.319
back to the sultan Hussain, who

02:48:47.520 --> 02:48:53.040
immediately ordered him to be beheaded.

02:48:50.319 --> 02:48:55.680
Some sources describe Ramaraya's severed

02:48:53.040 --> 02:48:57.680
head being stuffed with straw and sent

02:48:55.680 --> 02:49:00.000
north to be paraded around the

02:48:57.680 --> 02:49:02.560
subcontinent.

02:49:00.000 --> 02:49:03.920
But however it happened, the result was

02:49:02.560 --> 02:49:07.520
clear;

02:49:03.920 --> 02:49:09.439
Ramaraya was killed, and his army fell

02:49:07.520 --> 02:49:12.490
into disarray.

02:49:09.439 --> 02:49:13.840
Ferishta recounts what happened next.

02:49:13.840 --> 02:49:19.359
The Hindus, according to custom, when they

02:49:16.640 --> 02:49:21.840
saw their chief destroyed, fled in the

02:49:19.359 --> 02:49:25.200
utmost disorder from the field and were

02:49:21.840 --> 02:49:27.600
pursued by the allies with such success

02:49:25.200 --> 02:49:29.200
that the river was dyed red with their

02:49:27.600 --> 02:49:32.240
blood.

02:49:29.200 --> 02:49:36.319
It is computed by the best authorities

02:49:32.240 --> 02:49:37.760
that above 100,000 infidels were slain

02:49:36.319 --> 02:49:41.240
during the action

02:49:37.760 --> 02:49:41.240
and in the pursuit.

02:49:41.840 --> 02:49:47.120
Those who were able with horses and

02:49:44.319 --> 02:49:49.760
elephants fled the battlefield,

02:49:47.120 --> 02:49:53.600
while a huge number of foot soldiers

02:49:49.760 --> 02:49:57.120
were left behind to be massacred.

02:49:53.600 --> 02:50:00.319
The historian Mirza Ibrahim al-Zubairi,

02:49:57.120 --> 02:50:03.520
in his work Basatin al-Salatin,

02:50:00.319 --> 02:50:08.319
recalls how the sultans now prepared to

02:50:03.520 --> 02:50:11.359
march on the defenseless capital city.

02:50:08.319 --> 02:50:14.880
During the course of 20 days that they

02:50:11.359 --> 02:50:17.840
remained at the seat of war, the sultans

02:50:14.880 --> 02:50:18.960
took their ease and nursed the wounded

02:50:17.840 --> 02:50:23.399
and sick,

02:50:18.960 --> 02:50:23.399
then they turned toward Vijayanagar.

02:50:23.920 --> 02:50:28.240
We can imagine the scenes as the

02:50:25.760 --> 02:50:30.319
frightened people of Vijayanagara

02:50:28.240 --> 02:50:33.680
watched the dribs and drabs of their

02:50:30.319 --> 02:50:36.560
defeated grand army returning home,

02:50:33.680 --> 02:50:39.040
columns of the wounded and dirty winding

02:50:36.560 --> 02:50:41.600
down the road without leaders, telling

02:50:39.040 --> 02:50:43.359
stories of the battle and the death of

02:50:41.600 --> 02:50:46.160
the king.

02:50:43.359 --> 02:50:48.960
Some of Ramaraya's brothers did manage

02:50:46.160 --> 02:50:51.680
to escape from the battle of Talikota

02:50:48.960 --> 02:50:54.080
and fled back to the capital.

02:50:51.680 --> 02:50:56.479
They were now the assumed rulers of the

02:50:54.080 --> 02:50:59.840
empire, and the frightened people of the

02:50:56.479 --> 02:51:03.040
city must have looked to them for hope,

02:50:59.840 --> 02:51:06.160
and they had good reason to be hopeful.

02:51:03.040 --> 02:51:09.279
Capital cities were rarely sacked in

02:51:06.160 --> 02:51:12.080
medieval India, where ideas of honor were

02:51:09.279 --> 02:51:15.200
held in high regard.

02:51:12.080 --> 02:51:18.160
It was common to demolish mosques and

02:51:15.200 --> 02:51:20.080
Hindu temples in conquered territories,

02:51:18.160 --> 02:51:24.080
but unrestrained violence against

02:51:20.080 --> 02:51:26.560
civilian populations was relatively rare.

02:51:24.080 --> 02:51:29.200
More often, the victorious side would

02:51:26.560 --> 02:51:31.520
simply demand an enormous payment to

02:51:29.200 --> 02:51:33.840
cover the costs of their campaign and

02:51:31.520 --> 02:51:36.640
then some, and then they would return to

02:51:33.840 --> 02:51:38.160
their lands triumphant and a good deal

02:51:36.640 --> 02:51:40.560
richer.

02:51:38.160 --> 02:51:43.520
But when Ramaraya's brothers fled back

02:51:40.560 --> 02:51:47.200
to the city, it soon became clear that

02:51:43.520 --> 02:51:49.600
they had no intention of paying anything.

02:51:47.200 --> 02:51:51.439
In the next days, they gathered up all

02:51:49.600 --> 02:51:54.800
the treasure they could,

02:51:51.439 --> 02:51:58.080
piled it onto ox carts, and fled,

02:51:54.800 --> 02:52:01.439
leaving the city to its fate.

02:51:58.080 --> 02:52:02.319
The city of Vijayanagara was now without an

02:52:01.439 --> 02:52:05.600
army,

02:52:02.319 --> 02:52:09.200
without leaders, and crucially, without

02:52:05.600 --> 02:52:11.920
any money to pay off its enemies.

02:52:09.200 --> 02:52:15.840
From this point on, the consequences

02:52:11.920 --> 02:52:15.840
would have been clear.

02:52:24.160 --> 02:52:28.240
The complete loss of the city's

02:52:26.080 --> 02:52:30.960
leadership and the collapse of its

02:52:28.240 --> 02:52:34.160
military meant that law and order in the

02:52:30.960 --> 02:52:36.160
city broke down almost immediately.

02:52:34.160 --> 02:52:39.600
Sources recount that hordes of the

02:52:36.160 --> 02:52:41.359
empire's own citizens rioted in panic

02:52:39.600 --> 02:52:43.600
and anger.

02:52:41.359 --> 02:52:46.000
Bands of its own soldiers who had fled

02:52:43.600 --> 02:52:48.720
the battle suddenly found themselves

02:52:46.000 --> 02:52:50.960
unemployed, and they turned to rampaging

02:52:48.720 --> 02:52:53.439
through the streets, stealing whatever

02:52:50.960 --> 02:52:55.600
Ramaraya's brothers had left behind,

02:52:53.439 --> 02:52:57.920
stripping the city of its wealth before

02:52:55.600 --> 02:52:59.279
the sultan's armies had even come into

02:52:57.920 --> 02:53:01.760
sight.

02:52:59.279 --> 02:53:05.600
We can imagine the pure panic on the

02:53:01.760 --> 02:53:08.479
streets during these final days.

02:53:05.600 --> 02:53:10.399
The Portuguese writer Diego de Couto

02:53:08.479 --> 02:53:12.240
writes that the armies of the sultans

02:53:10.399 --> 02:53:14.640
took only three days to reach

02:53:12.240 --> 02:53:17.840
Vijayanagara, while the chronicler

02:53:14.640 --> 02:53:20.560
Ferishta says it took ten.

02:53:17.840 --> 02:53:24.479
During this time, the mood in the city

02:53:20.560 --> 02:53:26.800
must have been one of abject terror.

02:53:24.479 --> 02:53:29.279
When the sultans reached the city,

02:53:26.800 --> 02:53:33.359
they found that Ramaraya's brothers had

02:53:29.279 --> 02:53:35.520
fled and its treasuries had been emptied.

02:53:33.359 --> 02:53:37.920
With no tribute to be paid, they were

02:53:35.520 --> 02:53:41.359
determined to get their money's worth

02:53:37.920 --> 02:53:43.760
and began a campaign of looting.

02:53:41.359 --> 02:53:46.160
Over the next days and weeks, they would

02:53:43.760 --> 02:53:47.279
strip Vijayanagara of any wealth it

02:53:46.160 --> 02:53:50.560
had left,

02:53:47.279 --> 02:53:53.200
and destroyed the symbols of its leaders,

02:53:50.560 --> 02:53:55.439
burning its temples and palaces to the

02:53:53.200 --> 02:53:58.399
ground.

02:53:55.439 --> 02:54:01.600
The poet Shauqi described this event in

02:53:58.399 --> 02:54:01.600
triumphant terms.

02:54:02.960 --> 02:54:08.000
The Shah ordered the plunder of the city.

02:54:06.000 --> 02:54:09.040
The order was given to both noble and

02:54:08.000 --> 02:54:11.439
commoner.

02:54:09.040 --> 02:54:14.240
They then rendered the city desolate.

02:54:11.439 --> 02:54:16.479
They harassed and killed. Both open and

02:54:14.240 --> 02:54:18.319
hidden wealth were revealed.

02:54:16.479 --> 02:54:19.600
Treasure was brought up from beneath the

02:54:18.319 --> 02:54:23.200
ground.

02:54:19.600 --> 02:54:26.160
People came to acquire riches and wealth,

02:54:23.200 --> 02:54:29.200
full of merriment, happiness, and delight;

02:54:26.160 --> 02:54:33.479
boxes of jewels in the thousands, gold

02:54:29.200 --> 02:54:33.479
and silver beyond count. The historian Mirza

02:54:37.760 --> 02:54:43.680
Ibrahim al-Zubairi gives a devastating account

02:54:40.080 --> 02:54:43.680
of the destruction of the city.

02:54:44.960 --> 02:54:49.760
They razed the lofty building and

02:54:47.680 --> 02:54:51.760
temples to the ground.

02:54:49.760 --> 02:54:53.479
The work of destruction was carried out

02:54:51.760 --> 02:54:56.800
with a vengeance.

02:54:53.479 --> 02:54:59.359
Vijayanagara was an extensive city,

02:54:56.800 --> 02:55:01.840
flourishing and well-populated.

02:54:59.359 --> 02:55:04.000
It had never experienced any foreign

02:55:01.840 --> 02:55:06.720
invasion for ages.

02:55:04.000 --> 02:55:09.680
The nobility, the wealthy, the soldiery,

02:55:06.720 --> 02:55:11.760
the peasants, and the artisans all drove

02:55:09.680 --> 02:55:13.760
a roaring trade.

02:55:11.760 --> 02:55:16.000
During the confusion and disorder

02:55:13.760 --> 02:55:18.240
following the Muslim invasion, the

02:55:16.000 --> 02:55:21.600
citizens, out of fear,

02:55:18.240 --> 02:55:22.960
lurked in their houses, cellars, wells, and

02:55:21.600 --> 02:55:25.520
reservoirs.

02:55:22.960 --> 02:55:27.600
Those that were well-to-do betook

02:55:25.520 --> 02:55:29.359
themselves to the neighboring mountains

02:55:27.600 --> 02:55:32.240
and caverns with their family and

02:55:29.359 --> 02:55:35.600
chattels. The Muslim army remained at

02:55:32.240 --> 02:55:39.040
Vijayanagar for about six months. To a

02:55:35.600 --> 02:55:44.840
distance of 20 leagues around the city,

02:55:39.040 --> 02:55:44.840
everything was burnt and reduced to ashes.

02:55:46.000 --> 02:55:53.200
The historian Robert Sewell describes

02:55:48.880 --> 02:55:56.399
the destruction in mournful terms.

02:55:53.200 --> 02:55:59.359
With fire and sword, with crowbars and

02:55:56.399 --> 02:56:02.160
axes, they carried on day after day their

02:55:59.359 --> 02:56:04.880
work of destruction. Never perhaps in the

02:56:02.160 --> 02:56:07.600
history of the world has such havoc been

02:56:04.880 --> 02:56:10.399
wrought, and wrought suddenly on so

02:56:07.600 --> 02:56:12.479
splendid a city, teeming with a wealthy

02:56:10.399 --> 02:56:15.120
and industrious population

02:56:12.479 --> 02:56:19.040
in the full plenitude of prosperity one

02:56:15.120 --> 02:56:22.160
day, and on the next, seized, pillaged, and

02:56:19.040 --> 02:56:22.160
reduced to ruins.

02:56:22.399 --> 02:56:28.319
Finally, the armies of the sultans left

02:56:25.279 --> 02:56:31.359
with what loot they could find, and left

02:56:28.319 --> 02:56:34.399
the city in ruins.

02:56:31.359 --> 02:56:37.359
The Persian historian Ferishta recounts

02:56:34.399 --> 02:56:40.160
the devastated condition of Vijayanagara

02:56:37.359 --> 02:56:43.040
and the fragmenting empire it had once

02:56:40.160 --> 02:56:43.040
been the heart of.

02:56:43.359 --> 02:56:48.080
The kingdom of Beejanuggur

02:56:45.840 --> 02:56:49.680
since this battle has never recovered

02:56:48.080 --> 02:56:52.640
its ancient splendor.

02:56:49.680 --> 02:56:55.359
The city itself was so destroyed that it

02:56:52.640 --> 02:56:56.370
is now totally in ruin

02:56:55.359 --> 02:56:57.600
and uninhabited,

02:56:57.600 --> 02:57:02.319
while the country has been seized on by

02:56:59.600 --> 02:57:04.960
the tributary chiefs, each of whom hath

02:57:02.319 --> 02:57:07.960
assumed an independent power in his own

02:57:04.960 --> 02:57:07.960
district.

02:57:09.680 --> 02:57:14.399
But archaeological evidence of the

02:57:12.080 --> 02:57:15.760
destruction of the city is not as

02:57:14.399 --> 02:57:18.000
damning.

02:57:15.760 --> 02:57:20.399
In the royal center, there is a great

02:57:18.000 --> 02:57:22.640
deal of fire damage to be found on the

02:57:20.399 --> 02:57:25.520
stones of the temples.

02:57:22.640 --> 02:57:28.560
Here, the superstructures of wood and

02:57:25.520 --> 02:57:30.160
other flammable material were set fire

02:57:28.560 --> 02:57:32.560
and burned,

02:57:30.160 --> 02:57:34.800
collapsing in and causing the stones

02:57:32.560 --> 02:57:37.680
that supported them to crack.

02:57:34.800 --> 02:57:39.760
Buildings such as the main royal complex

02:57:37.680 --> 02:57:42.240
and the audience hall, with a hundred

02:57:39.760 --> 02:57:44.960
stone columns supporting its roof, were

02:57:42.240 --> 02:57:47.520
all burned, as well as others that

02:57:44.960 --> 02:57:49.040
represented the royal authority of the

02:57:47.520 --> 02:57:51.279
state.

02:57:49.040 --> 02:57:53.920
But in the residential parts of the city,

02:57:51.279 --> 02:57:56.720
the houses and markets, the destruction

02:57:53.920 --> 02:57:59.600
was much less, and there's no evidence of

02:57:56.720 --> 02:58:01.520
a wholesale burning of the city or of an

02:57:59.600 --> 02:58:05.120
enormous massacre.

02:58:01.520 --> 02:58:08.160
The Italian Cesare Federici, writing two

02:58:05.120 --> 02:58:10.800
years after the empire's defeat, reports

02:58:08.160 --> 02:58:10.800
the following.

02:58:11.279 --> 02:58:14.960
When news came to the cities of the

02:58:12.880 --> 02:58:17.279
overthrow in the battle, the wives and

02:58:14.960 --> 02:58:19.120
children of the tyrant fled away,

02:58:17.279 --> 02:58:22.000
and the four kings of the Moors entered

02:58:19.120 --> 02:58:24.399
the city of Bezeneger with great triumph,

02:58:22.000 --> 02:58:26.800
and they remained there six months,

02:58:24.399 --> 02:58:28.240
searching under houses and in all places

02:58:26.800 --> 02:58:29.680
for money and other things that were

02:58:28.240 --> 02:58:30.720
hidden,

02:58:29.680 --> 02:58:33.200
and then

02:58:30.720 --> 02:58:34.800
they departed to their own kingdoms

02:58:33.200 --> 02:58:36.720
because they were not able to maintain

02:58:34.800 --> 02:58:40.319
such a kingdom as that was,

02:58:36.720 --> 02:58:42.640
so far distant from their own country.

02:58:40.319 --> 02:58:44.080
The city of Bezeneger is not altogether

02:58:42.640 --> 02:58:47.680
destroyed;

02:58:44.080 --> 02:58:50.800
the houses still stand, but empty,

02:58:47.680 --> 02:58:52.240
and there is dwelling in them nothing

02:58:50.800 --> 02:58:54.690
but tigers

02:58:52.240 --> 02:58:57.680
and other wild beasts.

02:58:57.680 --> 02:59:03.680
When the armies of the sultans left, the

02:59:00.479 --> 02:59:05.040
population of Vijayanagara would emerge

02:59:03.680 --> 02:59:07.920
from the caves.

02:59:05.040 --> 02:59:10.560
With its leaders gone, its administration

02:59:07.920 --> 02:59:13.200
collapsed, and the entire empire

02:59:10.560 --> 02:59:15.600
fragmenting into smaller kingdoms, it

02:59:13.200 --> 02:59:18.399
seems that the people of the city could

02:59:15.600 --> 02:59:21.840
no longer maintain the large and complex

02:59:18.399 --> 02:59:24.160
metropolis they had once called home.

02:59:21.840 --> 02:59:27.520
They would soon be forced to loot what

02:59:24.160 --> 02:59:30.720
remained of the city in order to survive.

02:59:27.520 --> 02:59:33.200
Bit by bit, the stone buildings that had

02:59:30.720 --> 02:59:36.720
withstood the invading army would be

02:59:33.200 --> 02:59:39.279
dismantled or simply left to the vines

02:59:36.720 --> 02:59:42.399
and the wild dogs.

02:59:39.279 --> 02:59:45.120
The great city of victory was now a

02:59:42.399 --> 02:59:45.120
ghost town.

02:59:46.240 --> 02:59:51.600
The farmers who continued their lives in

02:59:48.560 --> 02:59:54.080
this area would sow rice in the once

02:59:51.600 --> 02:59:56.240
lavish gardens of the kings.

02:59:54.080 --> 02:59:58.399
They would take stones from the palaces

02:59:56.240 --> 03:00:01.040
to build their houses,

02:59:58.399 --> 03:00:03.600
and women would wash their clothes in

03:00:01.040 --> 03:00:05.840
the once opulent bath houses,

03:00:03.600 --> 03:00:07.680
hanging them to dry on the fallen

03:00:05.840 --> 03:00:10.160
pillars.

03:00:07.680 --> 03:00:12.640
Now, only troops of monkeys would make

03:00:10.160 --> 03:00:16.880
their homes among the rocks and the

03:00:12.640 --> 03:00:19.279
skeletal remains of ancient halls.

03:00:16.880 --> 03:00:21.920
With its status reduced,

03:00:19.279 --> 03:00:26.160
the city of Vijayanagara

03:00:21.920 --> 03:00:28.880
no longer seemed to suit its grand name.

03:00:26.160 --> 03:00:31.040
Instead, it became known by the name of

03:00:28.880 --> 03:00:34.240
one of its smaller districts which

03:00:31.040 --> 03:00:36.840
remained inhabited among the ruins,

03:00:34.240 --> 03:00:40.399
now a small village named

03:00:36.840 --> 03:00:43.120
Hampi. This was the ruined place that the

03:00:40.399 --> 03:00:47.600
Scottish captain Colin Mackenzie would

03:00:43.120 --> 03:00:50.240
wander through nearly 150 years later.

03:00:47.600 --> 03:00:54.399
Birds would soon make their homes in the

03:00:50.240 --> 03:00:57.920
temple roofs; Indian robins, large grey

03:00:54.399 --> 03:01:01.120
babblers, blue rock thrushes, quails, and

03:00:57.920 --> 03:01:03.760
the rare yellow-throated bulbul.

03:01:01.120 --> 03:01:07.520
Plant life would have gradually

03:01:03.760 --> 03:01:10.520
crept in to reclaim the empty streets.

03:01:07.520 --> 03:01:12.960
Soon after its abandonment, the stones of

03:01:10.520 --> 03:01:16.479
Vijayanagara would have sprouted with

03:01:12.960 --> 03:01:18.720
grasses. Banana and coconut palms would

03:01:16.479 --> 03:01:21.760
have begun to spring up in the streets

03:01:18.720 --> 03:01:24.479
and yards. The wiry branches of the

03:01:21.760 --> 03:01:27.040
frangipani tree would burst up through

03:01:24.479 --> 03:01:29.359
the temple courtyards, lifting the

03:01:27.040 --> 03:01:31.920
flagstones with their roots,

03:01:29.359 --> 03:01:34.560
while perennial weeds like the lion's

03:01:31.920 --> 03:01:38.960
ear and prickly pears would have

03:01:34.560 --> 03:01:38.960
sprouted between the cobblestones.

03:01:40.880 --> 03:01:46.640
The kings of Vijayanagara who fled the

03:01:44.000 --> 03:01:49.120
destruction of the city did continue to

03:01:46.640 --> 03:01:52.000
rule in a much diminished form for

03:01:49.120 --> 03:01:54.880
several more decades, and shifted their

03:01:52.000 --> 03:01:57.040
courts to their remaining territories in

03:01:54.880 --> 03:01:59.840
southern Andhra.

03:01:57.040 --> 03:02:02.720
In their grandeur and ceremony, their

03:01:59.840 --> 03:02:06.000
processions and festivals, they attempted

03:02:02.720 --> 03:02:08.399
to recreate the splendor of their past,

03:02:06.000 --> 03:02:11.520
but in reality, they would never again

03:02:08.399 --> 03:02:14.160
wield power in the same way.

03:02:11.520 --> 03:02:16.720
The glorious days of the great capital

03:02:14.160 --> 03:02:18.880
were now a distant memory.

03:02:16.720 --> 03:02:21.359
Like their great rivals the Delhi

03:02:18.880 --> 03:02:24.560
Sultanate and Bahmani Sultanate before

03:02:21.359 --> 03:02:26.880
them, they now ruled over a tiny portion

03:02:24.560 --> 03:02:29.680
of what they once had.

03:02:26.880 --> 03:02:32.720
By the dawn of the 17th century, that

03:02:29.680 --> 03:02:35.760
power, too, evaporated, and the last of

03:02:32.720 --> 03:02:39.359
Vijayanagara's Nayaka lords

03:02:35.760 --> 03:02:39.359
went their separate ways.

03:02:39.760 --> 03:02:44.720
With the economic heart ripped out of

03:02:41.920 --> 03:02:47.040
the empire, without the booming economy

03:02:44.720 --> 03:02:49.760
of the temples and the markets of the

03:02:47.040 --> 03:02:53.359
great metropolis, the surrounding towns

03:02:49.760 --> 03:02:56.640
and villages also went into decline.

03:02:53.359 --> 03:02:59.279
Port towns far away on the western coast

03:02:56.640 --> 03:03:02.000
like Bhatkal and on the eastern coast

03:02:59.279 --> 03:03:03.359
like Pulicat also shrunk around this

03:03:02.000 --> 03:03:06.319
time.

03:03:03.359 --> 03:03:09.680
The dance of Shiva went on,

03:03:06.319 --> 03:03:11.120
and another great empire had passed into

03:03:09.680 --> 03:03:14.080
ruins.

03:03:11.120 --> 03:03:16.000
The historian Manu Pillai describes this

03:03:14.080 --> 03:03:17.920
time.

03:03:16.000 --> 03:03:20.720
The lessons for the sultans in the

03:03:17.920 --> 03:03:22.399
northern Deccan from this episode should

03:03:20.720 --> 03:03:24.720
have been clear;

03:03:22.399 --> 03:03:28.399
it was the inability of the Deccan's

03:03:24.720 --> 03:03:31.200
ancient rulers, the Kakatiyas, Hoysalas,

03:03:28.399 --> 03:03:34.080
and Yadavas, to join together against

03:03:31.200 --> 03:03:36.240
their common enemy that led to the fall

03:03:34.080 --> 03:03:39.120
of their order at the hands of the

03:03:36.240 --> 03:03:41.840
Khiljis and Tughlaqs.

03:03:39.120 --> 03:03:44.720
When the Bahmani Sultanate emerged, its

03:03:41.840 --> 03:03:47.439
leaders too ultimately failed to reign

03:03:44.720 --> 03:03:50.399
in dissension, and in only a few

03:03:47.439 --> 03:03:53.680
generations, the kingdom was on its way

03:03:50.399 --> 03:03:56.160
to decline and disintegration.

03:03:53.680 --> 03:03:58.560
The rebel sultans who seceded from the

03:03:56.160 --> 03:04:01.640
Bahmanis continued this tradition by

03:03:58.560 --> 03:04:04.560
constantly feuding with one another, but

03:04:01.640 --> 03:04:07.760
Ramaraya's ambition reminded them at

03:04:04.560 --> 03:04:10.080
last that in the game they were playing,

03:04:07.760 --> 03:04:11.359
they were all destined to suffer as

03:04:10.080 --> 03:04:14.560
losers.

03:04:11.359 --> 03:04:18.000
Together then, they rose against Ramaraya

03:04:14.560 --> 03:04:21.439
and demolished Vijayanagar for once and

03:04:18.000 --> 03:04:24.240
forever, achieving in a stroke something

03:04:21.439 --> 03:04:26.440
that even they perhaps could not have

03:04:24.240 --> 03:04:29.610
believed was entirely possible.

03:04:30.080 --> 03:04:34.640
In the following years,

03:04:31.840 --> 03:04:37.520
in the north of India, a new power would

03:04:34.640 --> 03:04:40.240
rise in Delhi, founded by a warrior

03:04:37.520 --> 03:04:43.920
chieftain from Uzbekistan.

03:04:40.240 --> 03:04:46.960
He was Turco-Mongolian in ethnicity, and

03:04:43.920 --> 03:04:49.680
today we know the dynasty he founded by

03:04:46.960 --> 03:04:51.040
a name derived from the Persian word for

03:04:49.680 --> 03:04:54.080
Mongol.

03:04:51.040 --> 03:04:57.279
The age of the Mughals had dawned, and a

03:04:54.080 --> 03:04:59.120
new, glorious stage of Indian history

03:04:57.279 --> 03:05:01.840
would now begin.

03:04:59.120 --> 03:05:04.960
But the center of Indian power would now

03:05:01.840 --> 03:05:06.720
forever be in the north.

03:05:04.960 --> 03:05:09.359
Around the same time,

03:05:06.720 --> 03:05:11.200
another much more underwhelming event

03:05:09.359 --> 03:05:13.600
would take place,

03:05:11.200 --> 03:05:16.399
far from the resplendent finery of the

03:05:13.600 --> 03:05:18.880
Mughal court that would have perhaps an

03:05:16.399 --> 03:05:21.120
even greater impact on the history of

03:05:18.880 --> 03:05:24.640
this land.

03:05:21.120 --> 03:05:27.439
In the year 1626, little more than 60

03:05:24.640 --> 03:05:30.160
years after the battle of Talikota, the

03:05:27.439 --> 03:05:32.960
British East India Company built its

03:05:30.160 --> 03:05:35.279
first fortified port near the coastal

03:05:32.960 --> 03:05:38.240
town of Pulicat.

03:05:35.279 --> 03:05:41.279
This town was once the gateway by sea to

03:05:38.240 --> 03:05:43.920
the Vijayanagara Empire, and through here,

03:05:41.279 --> 03:05:47.760
the empire had traded with Sri Lanka,

03:05:43.920 --> 03:05:50.560
Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, and China.

03:05:47.760 --> 03:05:53.120
But in the decades since, the port town

03:05:50.560 --> 03:05:55.600
had fallen on hard times.

03:05:53.120 --> 03:05:58.479
The fort the British built was shoddy

03:05:55.600 --> 03:06:01.680
and indefensible, and the trading company

03:05:58.479 --> 03:06:04.160
abandoned it after only six years.

03:06:01.680 --> 03:06:07.200
But two years later, the British tried

03:06:04.160 --> 03:06:09.840
again a little further to the south, at a

03:06:07.200 --> 03:06:11.600
small fishing village called

03:06:09.840 --> 03:06:13.600
Madraspatnam.

03:06:11.600 --> 03:06:15.920
It's said that the site was chosen

03:06:13.600 --> 03:06:18.800
because the head of the company factory,

03:06:15.920 --> 03:06:22.319
a man named Francis Day, had fallen in

03:06:18.800 --> 03:06:25.040
love with a Tamil girl who lived nearby.

03:06:22.319 --> 03:06:27.120
At this time, the land was ruled by one

03:06:25.040 --> 03:06:29.920
of the lords left over from the

03:06:27.120 --> 03:06:30.960
fragmented and scattered Vijayanagara

03:06:29.920 --> 03:06:33.600
Empire.

03:06:30.960 --> 03:06:36.479
He was more than happy to grant a lease

03:06:33.600 --> 03:06:38.000
to that small bit of humble land to this

03:06:36.479 --> 03:06:41.439
foreign company

03:06:38.000 --> 03:06:44.080
in exchange for a share of their takings.

03:06:41.439 --> 03:06:46.960
This was the first true foothold of the

03:06:44.080 --> 03:06:49.600
British East India Company in India, a

03:06:46.960 --> 03:06:52.640
foothold that would grow into colonial

03:06:49.600 --> 03:06:55.040
domination of the entire land mass, and

03:06:52.640 --> 03:06:57.840
it came out of the weakness and

03:06:55.040 --> 03:07:00.800
dissolution of the empire of

03:06:57.840 --> 03:07:00.800
Vijayanagara.

03:07:06.160 --> 03:07:11.760
I want to end this episode with an

03:07:08.640 --> 03:07:15.120
extract from the epic poem Aamuktamaalyada,

03:07:11.760 --> 03:07:17.840
a masterpiece composed by the last

03:07:15.120 --> 03:07:20.880
great king of Vijayanagara, Krishna

03:07:17.840 --> 03:07:24.479
Devaraya, in the early 16th century, in

03:07:20.880 --> 03:07:26.800
the final decades of his empire.

03:07:24.479 --> 03:07:29.760
It tells the story of a wedding between

03:07:26.800 --> 03:07:31.920
the god Vishnu and one of his wives, the

03:07:29.760 --> 03:07:34.640
saint Andal.

03:07:31.920 --> 03:07:37.520
In this extract, a king overhears a

03:07:34.640 --> 03:07:40.560
Brahmin priest preaching, and is suddenly

03:07:37.520 --> 03:07:43.840
struck with a sense of the temporary,

03:07:40.560 --> 03:07:46.640
fleeting nature of life and the passing

03:07:43.840 --> 03:07:48.960
glory of great empires.

03:07:46.640 --> 03:07:51.520
I think in this moment you get a sense

03:07:48.960 --> 03:07:54.479
for its author, Krishna Devaraya,

03:07:51.520 --> 03:07:58.080
struggling with his own impermanence, a

03:07:54.479 --> 03:08:01.359
keen awareness of his own mortality, and

03:07:58.080 --> 03:08:02.720
the fleeting nature of his empire.

03:08:01.359 --> 03:08:04.399
As you listen,

03:08:02.720 --> 03:08:06.800
imagine what it would feel like to

03:08:04.399 --> 03:08:10.240
wander the streets of the great stone

03:08:06.800 --> 03:08:11.600
capital of Vijayanagara, now emptied of

03:08:10.240 --> 03:08:13.920
all life.

03:08:11.600 --> 03:08:16.560
Imagine watching the vines and creepers

03:08:13.920 --> 03:08:19.359
push their way between its stones, the

03:08:16.560 --> 03:08:22.640
monkeys clambering over the staircases

03:08:19.359 --> 03:08:24.640
of broken brick reaching up to the sky.

03:08:22.640 --> 03:08:27.600
Imagine watching the once great

03:08:24.640 --> 03:08:30.560
reservoirs and bath houses fill up with

03:08:27.600 --> 03:08:33.840
weeds and water lilies, the great towers

03:08:30.560 --> 03:08:34.960
of the temples now home to bats and wild

03:08:33.840 --> 03:08:37.600
dogs.

03:08:34.960 --> 03:08:40.800
Imagine watching the sun set over this

03:08:37.600 --> 03:08:44.000
great empire as the dance of Shiva, the

03:08:40.800 --> 03:08:49.160
dance of creation and destruction, goes

03:08:44.000 --> 03:08:49.160
on and on into eternity. On his way, he over-

03:08:56.880 --> 03:09:03.520
-heard the visiting Brahman recite another wise

03:09:00.640 --> 03:09:06.080
saying; he said just as you should gather

03:09:03.520 --> 03:09:08.960
provisions for the rainy season

03:09:06.080 --> 03:09:11.279
in the eight months before the monsoon,

03:09:08.960 --> 03:09:13.040
you should prepare for night

03:09:11.279 --> 03:09:16.800
during the day,

03:09:13.040 --> 03:09:19.680
for old age when still young,

03:09:16.800 --> 03:09:21.279
and for the next life

03:09:19.680 --> 03:09:24.160
right now,

03:09:21.279 --> 03:09:24.160
in this life.

03:09:24.479 --> 03:09:29.359
While you still can,

03:09:26.880 --> 03:09:33.279
you should try your very best

03:09:29.359 --> 03:09:33.279
to lead a righteous life.

03:09:33.840 --> 03:09:38.319
These words about life's inevitable

03:09:36.880 --> 03:09:41.040
future

03:09:38.319 --> 03:09:42.840
pierced the king's soul.

03:09:41.040 --> 03:09:45.439
The king listened to the

03:09:42.840 --> 03:09:46.310
proverb, reflected on it

03:09:45.439 --> 03:09:47.439
in his heart,

03:09:47.439 --> 03:09:52.319
understood its meaning,

03:09:50.080 --> 03:09:54.479
and stopped.

03:09:52.319 --> 03:09:58.000
He was stunned,

03:09:54.479 --> 03:10:00.399
overwhelmed, and petrified.

03:09:58.000 --> 03:10:01.279
He froze and stood in the middle of the

03:10:00.399 --> 03:10:03.060
road

03:10:01.279 --> 03:10:04.319
in utter distress.

03:10:04.319 --> 03:10:12.080
He thought to himself,

03:10:06.960 --> 03:10:14.960
oh, what is this glorious empire?

03:10:12.080 --> 03:10:16.530
What are these pleasures?

03:10:14.960 --> 03:10:18.000
Why these emotions?

03:10:18.000 --> 03:10:22.800
This body is nothing but a bubble about

03:10:20.800 --> 03:10:25.120
to burst.

03:10:22.800 --> 03:10:27.279
Even Manu, the primal man,

03:10:25.120 --> 03:10:29.520
who was born at the dawn of time, was

03:10:27.279 --> 03:10:33.200
ultimately destroyed,

03:10:29.520 --> 03:10:36.000
trampled by the great god of death.

03:10:33.200 --> 03:10:37.680
The joys of an empire are as fleeting as

03:10:36.000 --> 03:10:40.399
lightning.

03:10:37.680 --> 03:10:42.720
Just as travelers ferried to the far

03:10:40.399 --> 03:10:45.359
shore without even noticing the

03:10:42.720 --> 03:10:48.319
movements of the boat,

03:10:45.359 --> 03:10:49.600
so too does time pass,

03:10:48.319 --> 03:10:52.560
quickly,

03:10:49.600 --> 03:10:56.239
without our realizing it,

03:10:52.560 --> 03:10:57.279
and in this trance,

03:10:56.239 --> 03:10:59.230
life

03:10:57.279 --> 03:11:02.430
passes us by.

03:11:10.640 --> 03:11:15.680
Thank you once again for listening to

03:11:12.640 --> 03:11:17.279
The Fall of Civilizations Podcast.

